{"title_page": "Penparcau", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|static_image_name = St Anne's Church, Penparcau - geograph.org.uk - 1451122.jpg\n|static_image_caption = St Anne's Church, Penparcau\n|country = Wales\n|official_name = Penparcau\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.400862|-4.071998|display=inline,title}}\n|unitary_wales = [[Ceredigion]]\n|lieutenancy_wales = [[Dyfed]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[Ceredigion (UK Parliament constituency)|Ceredigion]]\n|constituency_welsh_assembly = [[Ceredigion (Assembly constituency)|Ceredigion]]\n|post_town = ABERYSTWYTH\n|postcode_district = SY23\n|postcode_area = SY\n|dial_code = 01970\n|map_type = \n|os_grid_reference = SN591801\n|cardiff_distance = \n|population = 3122\n}}\n\n'''Penparcau''' is a village in [[Ceredigion]], [[Wales]] situated to the south of [[Aberystwyth]]. It is the largest village in Ceredigion and is also an [[electoral ward]]. The village has the largest number of Welsh language speakers (1095) in the Aberystwyth town area, covering an area from the sea to the river Rheidol.<ref>https://www.ceredigion.gov.uk/media/3229/ceredigionlsblanguagestrategy2015-20.pdf</ref>\n\nThe original village was a small [[hamlet (place)|hamlet]], one mile east of Aberystwyth town centre, but the building of extensive [[Art Deco]] style semi-detached social housing from the 1920s on transformed it. It lies in the shadow of the [[Celt]]ic [[Iron Age]] [[hill fort]] of [[Pen Dinas]], and between the sea at [[Tan-y-Bwlch, Aberystwyth|Tan Y Bwlch]] beach, the [[River Ystwyth]] and the [[River Rheidol]]. Penparcau has the only [[UNESCO]] [[Biosphere reserve]] in the [[Dyfi Biosphere]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dyfibiosphere.org.uk/u/File/map%20Eng.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-06-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007202056/http://www.dyfibiosphere.org.uk/u/File/map%20Eng.pdf |archivedate=2011-10-07 }}</ref> A section of the [[Wales Coast Path]] runs over Tan y Bwlch beach.\n\nThere is an [[Church in Wales|Anglican church]] named after the Saint Anne, a [[Roman Catholic]] church named after the [[:Category:Welsh martyrs|Welsh Martyrs]], which is noted in \"Architecture of Wales, Carmarthenshire and Ceredigion\" <ref>{{Cite book|title=Carmarthenshire and Ceredigion|last=Lloyd, Thomas.|date=2006|publisher=Yale University Press|others=Orbach, Julian., Scourfield, Robert.|isbn=0300101791|location=New Haven, CT|oclc=71164002}}</ref> and is home to a [[Lampedusa]] Cross,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=369192|title=The Lampedusa cross|website=British Museum|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref> as well as two [[Wesleyan Methodist Church (Great Britain)|Methodist]] [[chapel]]s and a [[Religious Society of Friends|Quaker]] meeting house. The recently closed ''Tollgate'' [[Public house|pub]] was named after the original tollgate<ref>Horsfall-Turner, E.R (1906) ''Walks and Wanderings in County Cardigan'' Yorks: Thomas Harrison & Sons.</ref> that stood on the old [[toll road]] at the top of Penparcau and is now in [[St Fagans National History Museum]] near [[Cardiff]].\n\nPenparcau has its own [[woodland]], Coed Geufron <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wt-woods.org.uk/coedgeufron |title=Coed Geufron&nbsp;\u2014 a Woodland Trust wood |publisher=Wt-woods.org.uk |date=2010-01-08 |accessdate=2010-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106203334/http://www.wt-woods.org.uk/CoedGeufron |archivedate=2009-01-06 }}</ref> run by the [[Woodland Trust]] and its own police station.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dyfed-powys.police.uk/en/ceredigion/neighbourhoods/penparcau/ |title=Dyfed Powys Police &#124; Penparcau and Llanbadarn Policing Team |publisher=Dyfed-powys.police.uk |accessdate=2010-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100430144324/http://www.dyfed-powys.police.uk/en/ceredigion/neighbourhoods/penparcau/ |archivedate=2010-04-30 }}</ref> Other amenities include a [[post office]], two small [[supermarket]]s, a garage, holiday park and [[hotel]] and until recently two [[fish and chip shop]]s, one of which has a reputation as one of the best in the area. Until late 2007, it also had its own [[travel agent]].\n\nIn 2008, Penparcau played a part in the [[transition town]] movement in Wales when it hosted the \"Alternative Energy and Transport Festival\" in Neuadd Goffa, attended by the local MP and mayor.<ref>[http://www.socialforumcymru.org.uk/groups/category/transition-town-aberystwyth/lang/en-uk/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609080951/http://www.socialforumcymru.org.uk/groups/category/transition-town-aberystwyth/lang/en-uk/ |date=June 9, 2008 }}</ref> At the bottom of the valley, just below Penparcau, is a [[Welsh Government]] office building, designed to house more than 550 staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/4292133.stm |title=UK &#124; Wales &#124; Assembly jobs move to mid and north |publisher=BBC News |date=2005-02-23 |accessdate=2010-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/mid/6224769.stm |title=UK &#124; Wales &#124; Mid Wales &#124; Assembly base could open in 2008 |publisher=BBC News |date=2007-01-03 |accessdate=2010-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Grass fire on Dinas Hill, Aberystwyth - geograph.org.uk - 453233.jpg|thumb|Grass fire on Pen Dinas behind Penparcau (2007)]]\nPeople have lived in and around Penparcau for over two thousand years. The [[Iron Age]] [[hillfort]] is believed to have been occupied for some 300 years up to and including the 1st century BC. Pen Dinas is the largest Iron Age hillfort in Ceredigion. Estimated to have been first built around 400 BC, the outline of the ancient ramparts is still evident.\n\n===Mesolithic===\nThere is evidence that during the [[Mesolithic]] Age the area of Tan-y-Bwlch at the foot of Pen Dinas (Penparcau) was used as a [[flint knapping]] floor for [[hunter-gatherer]]s making weapons from flint that was deposited as the ice retreated.<ref>Houlder, C. H., \"The Stone Age!, in J. L. Davies and D. P. Kirkby, ''Cardiganshire County History'', I, (1994), pp. 107\u2013123</ref>\n\n==== Submerged Forest ====\nTo the south of Tan-y-Bwlch beach lies an area where during low tides a [[submerged forest]] can be clearly seen. This is thought to be between 4000 \u2013 6000 years old. A record relating to the submerged forest can be found made by the Royal Commission on the Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales <ref>TAN Y BWLCH SUBMERGED FOREST http://www.coflein.gov.uk/en/site/421874/details/tanybwlch-submerged-forest</ref><ref>Evans, J.G., Limbrey, S. and Cleere, H. (eds) 1975. The effect of man on the landscape: the Highland Zone. CBA Research Report No 11 (1975)</ref>\n\n===Bronze and Iron Ages===\nThe remains of a [[Celts|Celtic]] fortress on [[Pen Dinas]] (or more correctly 'Dinas Maelor' home of the mythical Celtic giant king [[Maelor Gawr]]), a hill in Penparcau overlooking Aberystwyth, indicates that the site was inhabited before 700 BC.<ref>Briggs, C. S., \"The Bronze Age\", in J. L. Davies and D. P. Kirkby, ''Cardiganshire County History'', I, (1994), p. 216, : appendix V, : no. 15</ref><ref>Browne, D and Driver, T., ''Bryngaer Pendinas Hill Fort, A Prehistoric Fortress at Aberystwyth'', (2001)</ref> On a hill south of the present town, across the River Ystwyth, are the remains of a medieval [[ringfort]] believed to be the castle from which Princess Nest was abducted. This rare survival is now on private land and can only be accessed by arrangement.<ref>Houlder, C.H., (1957), \"Recent Excavations in Old Aberystwyth\", ''Ceredigion'', III, no. 2, pp. 114\u2013117</ref> A Bronze Age standing stone is also referenced as being in Penparcau in the Ceredigion County History (Volume 1)<ref>Briggs, C S, 1994 \u2018The Bronze Age\u2019, in J L Davies and D P Kirby (Eds.), Cardigan County History, Volume 1, From the Earliest of Times to the Coming of the Normans, 124-218</ref> and the Dyfed Archaeological records.<ref>Bronze Age Standing Stone (Cae Maen) http://cofiadurcahcymru.org.uk/arch/query/page.php?watprn=DAT4844</ref>\n\n===Modern History===\nA distinctive memorial to the [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Duke of Wellington]] in the shape of an upturned cannon was built on the hilltop in 1852. The hilltop comprises a [[twin summit]] system and the mounded defences divide into three systems. [[Archaeological]] excavations in the 1930s demonstrated at least four phases to the defences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gtj.org.uk/en/blowup1/1199 |title=Aerial photograph of Pen Dinas Iron Age hillfort, Aberystwyth, 1989 |publisher=Gtj.org.uk |accessdate=2010-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010084136/http://www.gtj.org.uk/en/blowup1/1199 |archivedate=2007-10-10 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gtj.org.uk/en/blowup1/1198 |title=Aerial photograph of Pen Dinas Iron Age hillfort, Aberystwyth, 1989 |publisher=Gtj.org.uk |accessdate=2010-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927172226/http://www.gtj.org.uk/en/blowup1/1198 |archivedate=2007-09-27 }}</ref> Pen Dinas is now more popular as a tourist attraction for walkers and used in a more sedate manner for [[paragliding]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flymidwales.org.uk/site.php?site=pen-dinas |title=Pen Dinas (Open) (Mid-Wales Hang Gliding and Paragliding Club) |publisher=Flymidwales.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2010-07-15 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nPenparcau (pronounced in the local dialect as 'pen parky' or 'penpark'e with an emphasis on the e, as in the dialectical pronunciation of 'au' in North Ceredigion, where 'pethau' becomes 'pethe'(in Welsh)) in 1841 was spelled Penparke, Penparciau,<ref>[http://www.gigaflop.demon.co.uk/aber/abermap1868f.jpg ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060621184112/http://www.gigaflop.demon.co.uk/aber/abermap1868f.jpg |date=June 21, 2006 }}</ref> Penparkie or even Pen Y Parciau<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/mapsheet.aspx?compid=55182&sheetid=1321&ox=2217&oy=2807&zm=1&czm=1&x=353&y=167 |title=Maps > Ordnance Survey 1:10,560 - Epoch 1 > Wales&nbsp;\u2014 Cardiganshire > 006/SW &#124; British History Online |publisher=British-history.ac.uk |date=2003-06-22 |accessdate=2010-07-15}}</ref> (''on the 1890 OS map'') and stretched on both sides of the [[Toll road|turnpike road]] from Trefechan to Southgate. The population of the hamlet was 239, most of whom were workers in [[agriculture]] and related [[rural]] industries. There were three agricultural labourers and only one farmer; the next most important occupation was that of stonemason of whom there were eight. There were three shoemakers, two [[tailor]]s and two [[Shipbuilding|shipwrights]] as well as the following: rope-maker, joiner, [[Tanner (occupation)|tanner]], carpenter, gardener, [[Occupational surname|sawyer]], [[wheelwright]], [[Weaver (occupation)|weaver]] and [[saddle]]r.\n\nIn the 18th century, smuggling was a key part of the economy, with tea, salt, rum and tobacco being some of the things smuggled into the local area. There are records in the national archive showing an extensive smuggling ring run by the Powell and neighbouring Stedman families. The smuggled goods were bought into Penparcau to avoid the [[excise]] men stationed in Aberystwyth.\n\nThere is also interesting domestic architecture that can be assigned to Richard Emrys Bonsall<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.llgc.org.uk/ardd/pensaeri/arch013.htm |title=The Architecture of Wales&nbsp;\u2014 Architectural Drawings in The National Library of Wales |publisher=Llgc.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2010-07-15}}</ref> such as the Ebeneser Chapel, still in use today. The plans for many of these buildings can be found at the [[National Library of Wales]].\n\nA famous feature that existed in Penparcau was the [[toll house]]. It was built in 1771 and stood at the southern junction of Penparcau (hence the name Southgate). It was built of local [[slate]] stone and was roofed with [[Pembrokeshire]] slates. David Jones of Dihewyd was appointed as the first gatekeeper in November 1771, and the first tolls were charged on 23 March 1772. The building contains just one room, one end being used for the collection of tolls. A single fireplace at the opposite end of the house was used for heating and cooking. Toll houses were very unpopular with people in rural areas who had to pay to travel along the roads. At St Fagans the house has been furnished in the style of 1843, the period of the [[Rebecca Riots]] when many tollgates were destroyed in Wales. Turnpike Trusts were eventually abolished in 1864 with county councils taking over responsibility for building and maintaining the roads but the Penparcau toll house remained a residence until the 1960s.\n\n==Culture==\nThe [[United Kingdom Census 2001]] reported that over 40% of the residents of Penparcau spoke Welsh and used Welsh daily, larger than any other individual census zone within that area, when compared to the other census data sets.<ref>{{cite web|author=Neighbourhood Statistics |url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6116466&c=aberystwyth&d=14&e=16&g=415738&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1255081495663&enc=1&dsFamilyId=197 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604061541/http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6116466&c=aberystwyth&d=14&e=16&g=415738&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1255081495663&enc=1&dsFamilyId=197 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-06-04 |title=Check Browser Settings |publisher=Neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |accessdate=2010-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Residents==\nThe [[bard]] and academic writer [[D. Gwenallt Jones]] (David James Jones) lived in the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://biography.wales/article/s2-JONE-JAM-1899 |title=The National Library of Wales :: Dictionary of Welsh Biography |publisher=Yba.llgc.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2010-07-15}}</ref> More recently another resident, Ifan Morgan Jones,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eisteddfod.org.uk/english/content.php?nID=3&newsID=69 |archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20081123230740/http://www.eisteddfod.org.uk/english/content.php?nID=3&newsID=69 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-11-23 |title=Welcome &#124; The National Eisteddfod of Wales |publisher=Eisteddfod.org.uk |accessdate=2010-07-15 }}</ref> won the [[Daniel Owen Prize|Daniel Owen Memorial Prize]] for his novel at the National [[Eisteddfod]] of Wales in 2008.\n\nThe famous Welsh composer and musician Prof [[David John de Lloyd]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://discoverwelshmusic.com/composers/david-de-lloyd/|title=David de Lloyd - Discover Welsh Music}}</ref> was raised and lived in the village.\n\nOther notable residents are the [[Bishop of Bangor]], the Right Reverend [[Andrew John]]; [[Mike Jenkins (poet)|Mike Jenkins,]] author, poet and father of [[Bethan Jenkins]], who was brought up in the village as a boy; and the historian [[Geraint_H._Jenkins|Emeritus Professor Geraint Huw Jenkins]], who was born and raised in the village. [[Eurfyl ap Gwilym]], a Welsh economist, was from Penparcau.\n\n[[Jane Stanness]] was born in Penparcau. She is an actress, writer, singer and songwriter.<ref name=\"cam\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cambrian-news.co.uk/article.cfm?id=118971&headline=How%20Aberystwyth%20inspired%20multi-talented%20Jane&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2018 |title= How Aberystwyth inspired multi-talented Jane |publisher= cambrian-news.co.uk |year=2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180204231652/http://www.cambrian-news.co.uk/article.cfm?id=118971&headline=How%20Aberystwyth%20inspired%20multi-talented%20Jane&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2018 |archive-date= 4 February 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"som\">{{cite web|url= https://www.somersetlive.co.uk/news/somerset-news/bath-actress-describes-working-friends-3821207|title= Bath actress describes working with Friends star David Schwimmer |publisher= somersetlive.co.uk |year=2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nAberystwyth-Penparcau is the most populous electoral division in Ceredigion and elects two county councillors.\n\nPenparcau is also the name of the village which covers a portion of the electoral division consisting of the areas of Southgate and Caeffynnon.\n\nFive town councillors represent the ward on the [[Aberystwyth Town Council]], one of the 51 town and community councils in Ceredigion and consists of 19 town councillors elected in five wards. The last elections were held in May 2017.\n\nPenparcau is governed by [[Ceredigion County Council]] and Aberystwyth itself elects six of the 42 councillors in five separate wards (Bronglais, Central, North, [[Aberystwyth Rheidol|Rheidol]] and Penparcau - the Penparcau ward elects two of these). The two county councillors for Aberystwyth-Penparcau, elected in May 2017 were [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] and [[Plaid Cymru]].\n\nPenparcau has five [[Welsh Assembly]] members, one of whom is elected as a constituency AM for [[Ceredigion (Assembly constituency)|Ceredigion]], [[Elin Jones]] and four who are elected on the regional list for [[Mid and West Wales (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|Mid and West Wales]].\n\nThe village is also within the [[Ceredigion (UK Parliament constituency)|Ceredigion]] constituency for elections to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]. The current MP is [[Ben Lake]] for [[Plaid Cymru]].\n\n==Sites of Special Scientific Interest==\nThe Penparcau electoral ward stretches from [[Tan-y-Bwlch, Aberystwyth|Tan y Bwlch]] beach to the [[River Rheidol|Rheidol]]. There are two [[Sites of Special Scientific Interest]] and the Pen Dinas and Tan y Bwlch Local Nature Reserves within this area.\n\n==Myth, folklore and legend==\nOne of the more unusual residents is the headless dog of Penparcau. The [[myth]] tells of how a giant, going to his father's rescue, rode at such a rate that his dog could not keep up with him and its head came off in the leash. The dog now roams, mournfully crying and looking for its long-lost owner.<ref>Jones, T. Gwynn (1930) ''Welsh Folklore and Folk-Custom'' London: Methuen & Co Ltd.</ref> It has also been theorised{{By whom|date=February 2020}} that the original inhabitants were the same people that made the Banc Ceilliau sun-disc<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.museumwales.ac.uk/walespast/article.shtml?id=8 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-11-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070603032948/http://www.museumwales.ac.uk/walespast/article.shtml?id=8 |archivedate=2007-06-03 }}</ref> in nearby [[Cwmystwyth]]. There are also many stories relating to the [[pirate]]s that used this part of the coastline such as Bartholomew \u2018[[Bartholomew Roberts|Black Bart]]\u2019 Roberts the Pirate.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nDuring one winter in the late 19th century, villagers woke to find mysterious footprints in the fresh snow. It soon became apparent that these had not been made by any human as they were hoofprints made by a creature who walked on two legs and not four. Villagers followed these hoofprints and found that the creature had walked through fields, roads and even managed to walk over walls and roofs in one uninterrupted path. It was believed that the Devil had walked through Penparcau that snowy night and has never been seen back since.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/mapsheet.aspx?compid=55182&sheetid=1321&ox=2217&oy=2807&zm=1&czm=1&x=353&y=167/ 1890 Map of Penparcau]\n*[http://penparcau.org Penparcau Community Site]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/PenparcauCommunityForum Penparcau Community Forum Site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928061524/http://www.coflein.gov.uk/pls/portal/COFLEIN.REP_CATLIST_B.show?p_arg_names=pnumlink&p_arg_values=6028832 Archives of the Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales 1]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928061533/http://www.coflein.gov.uk/pls/portal/COFLEIN.REP_CATLIST_B.show?p_arg_names=pnumlink&p_arg_values=6028864 Archives of the Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales 2]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928061506/http://www.coflein.gov.uk/pls/portal/COFLEIN.REP_CATLIST_B.show?p_arg_names=pnumlink&p_arg_values=6028918 Archives of the Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales 3]\n*[https://www.geograph.org.uk/search.php?i=3091249 www.geograph.co.uk : photos of Penparcau and surrounding area]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/PenparcauCommunityForum Penparcau]\n*[http://www.nomisweb.co.uk/maps/700/1308631041.aspx A map of the Penparcau ward]\n{{Ceredigion}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Ceredigion]]\n[[Category:Aberystwyth]]\n[[Category:Villages in Wales]]\n[[Category:Lists of places in Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|static_image_name = St Anne's Church, Penparcau - geograph.org.uk - 1451122.jpg\n|static_image_caption = St Anne's Church, Penparcau\n|country = Wales\n|official_name = Penparcau\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.400862|-4.071998|display=inline,title}}\n|unitary_wales = [[Ceredigion]]\n|lieutenancy_wales = [[Dyfed]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[Ceredigion (UK Parliament constituency)|Ceredigion]]\n|constituency_welsh_assembly = [[Ceredigion (Assembly constituency)|Ceredigion]]\n|post_town = ABERYSTWYTH\n|postcode_district = SY23\n|postcode_area = SY\n|dial_code = 01970\n|map_type = \n|os_grid_reference = SN591801\n|cardiff_distance = \n|population = 3122\n}}\n\n'''Penparcau''' is a village in [[Ceredigion]], [[Wales]] situated to the south of [[Aberystwyth]]. It is the largest village in Ceredigion and is also an [[electoral ward]]. The village has the largest number of Welsh language speakers (1095) in the Aberystwyth town area, covering an area from the sea to the river Rheidol.<ref>https://www.ceredigion.gov.uk/media/3229/ceredigionlsblanguagestrategy2015-20.pdf</ref>\n\nThe original village was a small [[hamlet (place)|hamlet]], one mile east of Aberystwyth town centre, but the building of extensive [[Art Deco]] style semi-detached social housing from the 1920s on transformed it. It lies in the shadow of the [[Celt]]ic [[Iron Age]] [[hill fort]] of [[Pen Dinas]], and between the sea at [[Tan-y-Bwlch, Aberystwyth|Tan Y Bwlch]] beach, the [[River Ystwyth]] and the [[River Rheidol]]. Penparcau has the only [[UNESCO]] [[Biosphere reserve]] in the [[Dyfi Biosphere]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dyfibiosphere.org.uk/u/File/map%20Eng.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-06-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007202056/http://www.dyfibiosphere.org.uk/u/File/map%20Eng.pdf |archivedate=2011-10-07 }}</ref> A section of the [[Wales Coast Path]] runs over Tan y Bwlch beach.\n\nThere is an [[Church in Wales|Anglican church]] named after the Saint Anne, a [[Roman Catholic]] church named after the [[:Category:Welsh martyrs|Welsh Martyrs]], which is noted in \"Architecture of Wales, Carmarthenshire and Ceredigion\" <ref>{{Cite book|title=Carmarthenshire and Ceredigion|last=Lloyd, Thomas.|date=2006|publisher=Yale University Press|others=Orbach, Julian., Scourfield, Robert.|isbn=0300101791|location=New Haven, CT|oclc=71164002}}</ref> and is home to a [[Lampedusa]] Cross,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=369192|title=The Lampedusa cross|website=British Museum|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref> as well as two [[Wesleyan Methodist Church (Great Britain)|Methodist]] [[chapel]]s and a [[Religious Society of Friends|Quaker]] meeting house. The recently closed ''Tollgate'' [[Public house|pub]] was named after the original tollgate<ref>Horsfall-Turner, E.R (1906) ''Walks and Wanderings in County Cardigan'' Yorks: Thomas Harrison & Sons.</ref> that stood on the old [[toll road]] at the top of Penparcau and is now in [[St Fagans National History Museum]] near [[Cardiff]].\n\nPenparcau has its own [[woodland]], Coed Geufron <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wt-woods.org.uk/coedgeufron |title=Coed Geufron&nbsp;\u2014 a Woodland Trust wood |publisher=Wt-woods.org.uk |date=2010-01-08 |accessdate=2010-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106203334/http://www.wt-woods.org.uk/CoedGeufron |archivedate=2009-01-06 }}</ref> run by the [[Woodland Trust]] and its own police station.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dyfed-powys.police.uk/en/ceredigion/neighbourhoods/penparcau/ |title=Dyfed Powys Police &#124; Penparcau and Llanbadarn Policing Team |publisher=Dyfed-powys.police.uk |accessdate=2010-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100430144324/http://www.dyfed-powys.police.uk/en/ceredigion/neighbourhoods/penparcau/ |archivedate=2010-04-30 }}</ref> Other amenities include a [[post office]], two small [[supermarket]]s, a garage, holiday park and [[hotel]] and until recently two [[fish and chip shop]]s, one of which has a reputation as one of the best in the area. Until late 2007, it also had its own [[travel agent]].\n\nIn 2008, Penparcau played a part in the [[transition town]] movement in Wales when it hosted the \"Alternative Energy and Transport Festival\" in Neuadd Goffa, attended by the local MP and mayor.<ref>[http://www.socialforumcymru.org.uk/groups/category/transition-town-aberystwyth/lang/en-uk/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609080951/http://www.socialforumcymru.org.uk/groups/category/transition-town-aberystwyth/lang/en-uk/ |date=June 9, 2008 }}</ref> At the bottom of the valley, just below Penparcau, is a [[Welsh Government]] office building, designed to house more than 550 staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/4292133.stm |title=UK &#124; Wales &#124; Assembly jobs move to mid and north |publisher=BBC News |date=2005-02-23 |accessdate=2010-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/mid/6224769.stm |title=UK &#124; Wales &#124; Mid Wales &#124; Assembly base could open in 2008 |publisher=BBC News |date=2007-01-03 |accessdate=2010-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Grass fire on Dinas Hill, Aberystwyth - geograph.org.uk - 453233.jpg|thumb|Grass fire on Pen Dinas behind Penparcau (2007)]]\nPeople have lived in and around Penparcau for over two thousand years. The [[Iron Age]] [[hillfort]] is believed to have been occupied for some 300 years up to and including the 1st century BC. Pen Dinas is the largest Iron Age hillfort in Ceredigion. Estimated to have been first built around 400 BC, the outline of the ancient ramparts is still evident.\n\n===Mesolithic===\nThere is evidence that during the [[Mesolithic]] Age the area of Tan-y-Bwlch at the foot of Pen Dinas (Penparcau) was used as a [[flint knapping]] floor for [[hunter-gatherer]]s making weapons from flint that was deposited as the ice retreated.<ref>Houlder, C. H., \"The Stone Age!, in J. L. Davies and D. P. Kirkby, ''Cardiganshire County History'', I, (1994), pp. 107\u2013123</ref>\n\n==== Submerged Forest ====\nTo the south of Tan-y-Bwlch beach lies an area where during low tides a [[submerged forest]] can be clearly seen. This is thought to be between 4000 \u2013 6000 years old. A record relating to the submerged forest can be found made by the Royal Commission on the Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales <ref>TAN Y BWLCH SUBMERGED FOREST http://www.coflein.gov.uk/en/site/421874/details/tanybwlch-submerged-forest</ref><ref>Evans, J.G., Limbrey, S. and Cleere, H. (eds) 1975. The effect of man on the landscape: the Highland Zone. CBA Research Report No 11 (1975)</ref>\n\n===Bronze and Iron Ages===\nThe remains of a [[Celts|Celtic]] fortress on [[Pen Dinas]] (or more correctly 'Dinas Maelor' home of the mythical Celtic giant king [[Maelor Gawr]]), a hill in Penparcau overlooking Aberystwyth, indicates that the site was inhabited before 700 BC.<ref>Briggs, C. S., \"The Bronze Age\", in J. L. Davies and D. P. Kirkby, ''Cardiganshire County History'', I, (1994), p. 216, : appendix V, : no. 15</ref><ref>Browne, D and Driver, T., ''Bryngaer Pendinas Hill Fort, A Prehistoric Fortress at Aberystwyth'', (2001)</ref> On a hill south of the present town, across the River Ystwyth, are the remains of a medieval [[ringfort]] believed to be the castle from which Princess Nest was abducted. This rare survival is now on private land and can only be accessed by arrangement.<ref>Houlder, C.H., (1957), \"Recent Excavations in Old Aberystwyth\", ''Ceredigion'', III, no. 2, pp. 114\u2013117</ref> A Bronze Age standing stone is also referenced as being in Penparcau in the Ceredigion County History (Volume 1)<ref>Briggs, C S, 1994 \u2018The Bronze Age\u2019, in J L Davies and D P Kirby (Eds.), Cardigan County History, Volume 1, From the Earliest of Times to the Coming of the Normans, 124-218</ref> and the Dyfed Archaeological records.<ref>Bronze Age Standing Stone (Cae Maen) http://cofiadurcahcymru.org.uk/arch/query/page.php?watprn=DAT4844</ref>\n\n===Modern History===\nA distinctive memorial to the [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Duke of Wellington]] in the shape of an upturned cannon was built on the hilltop in 1852. The hilltop comprises a [[twin summit]] system and the mounded defences divide into three systems. [[Archaeological]] excavations in the 1930s demonstrated at least four phases to the defences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gtj.org.uk/en/blowup1/1199 |title=Aerial photograph of Pen Dinas Iron Age hillfort, Aberystwyth, 1989 |publisher=Gtj.org.uk |accessdate=2010-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010084136/http://www.gtj.org.uk/en/blowup1/1199 |archivedate=2007-10-10 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gtj.org.uk/en/blowup1/1198 |title=Aerial photograph of Pen Dinas Iron Age hillfort, Aberystwyth, 1989 |publisher=Gtj.org.uk |accessdate=2010-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927172226/http://www.gtj.org.uk/en/blowup1/1198 |archivedate=2007-09-27 }}</ref> Pen Dinas is now more popular as a tourist attraction for walkers and used in a more sedate manner for [[paragliding]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flymidwales.org.uk/site.php?site=pen-dinas |title=Pen Dinas (Open) (Mid-Wales Hang Gliding and Paragliding Club) |publisher=Flymidwales.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2010-07-15 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nPenparcau (pronounced in the local dialect as 'pen parky' or 'penpark'e with an emphasis on the e, as in the dialectical pronunciation of 'au' in North Ceredigion, where 'pethau' becomes 'pethe'(in Welsh)) in 1841 was spelled Penparke, Penparciau,<ref>[http://www.gigaflop.demon.co.uk/aber/abermap1868f.jpg ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060621184112/http://www.gigaflop.demon.co.uk/aber/abermap1868f.jpg |date=June 21, 2006 }}</ref> Penparkie or even Pen Y Parciau<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/mapsheet.aspx?compid=55182&sheetid=1321&ox=2217&oy=2807&zm=1&czm=1&x=353&y=167 |title=Maps > Ordnance Survey 1:10,560 - Epoch 1 > Wales&nbsp;\u2014 Cardiganshire > 006/SW &#124; British History Online |publisher=British-history.ac.uk |date=2003-06-22 |accessdate=2010-07-15}}</ref> (''on the 1890 OS map'') and stretched on both sides of the [[Toll road|turnpike road]] from Trefechan to Southgate. The population of the hamlet was 239, most of whom were workers in [[agriculture]] and related [[rural]] industries. There were three agricultural labourers and only one farmer; the next most important occupation was that of stonemason of whom there were eight. There were three shoemakers, two [[tailor]]s and two [[Shipbuilding|shipwrights]] as well as the following: rope-maker, joiner, [[Tanner (occupation)|tanner]], carpenter, gardener, [[Occupational surname|sawyer]], [[wheelwright]], [[Weaver (occupation)|weaver]] and [[saddle]]r.\n\nIn the 18th century, smuggling was a key part of the economy, with tea, salt, rum and tobacco being some of the things smuggled into the local area. There are records in the national archive showing an extensive smuggling ring run by the Powell and neighbouring Stedman families. The smuggled goods were bought into Penparcau to avoid the [[excise]] men stationed in Aberystwyth.\n\nThere is also interesting domestic architecture that can be assigned to Richard Emrys Bonsall<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.llgc.org.uk/ardd/pensaeri/arch013.htm |title=The Architecture of Wales&nbsp;\u2014 Architectural Drawings in The National Library of Wales |publisher=Llgc.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2010-07-15}}</ref> such as the Ebeneser Chapel, still in use today. The plans for many of these buildings can be found at the [[National Library of Wales]].\n\nA famous feature that existed in Penparcau was the [[toll house]]. It was built in 1771 and stood at the southern junction of Penparcau (hence the name Southgate). It was built of local [[slate]] stone and was roofed with [[Pembrokeshire]] slates. David Jones of Dihewyd was appointed as the first gatekeeper in November 1771, and the first tolls were charged on 23 March 1772. The building contains just one room, one end being used for the collection of tolls. A single fireplace at the opposite end of the house was used for heating and cooking. Toll houses were very unpopular with people in rural areas who had to pay to travel along the roads. At St Fagans the house has been furnished in the style of 1843, the period of the [[Rebecca Riots]] when many tollgates were destroyed in Wales. Turnpike Trusts were eventually abolished in 1864 with county councils taking over responsibility for building and maintaining the roads but the Penparcau toll house remained a residence until the 1960s.\n\n==Culture==\nThe [[United Kingdom Census 2001]] reported that over 40% of the residents of Penparcau spoke Welsh and used Welsh daily, larger than any other individual census zone within that area, when compared to the other census data sets.<ref>{{cite web|author=Neighbourhood Statistics |url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6116466&c=aberystwyth&d=14&e=16&g=415738&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1255081495663&enc=1&dsFamilyId=197 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604061541/http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6116466&c=aberystwyth&d=14&e=16&g=415738&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1255081495663&enc=1&dsFamilyId=197 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-06-04 |title=Check Browser Settings |publisher=Neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |accessdate=2010-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Residents==\nThe [[bard]] and academic writer [[D. Gwenallt Jones]] (David James Jones) lived in the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://biography.wales/article/s2-JONE-JAM-1899 |title=The National Library of Wales :: Dictionary of Welsh Biography |publisher=Yba.llgc.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2010-07-15}}</ref> More recently another resident, Ifan Morgan Jones,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eisteddfod.org.uk/english/content.php?nID=3&newsID=69 |archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20081123230740/http://www.eisteddfod.org.uk/english/content.php?nID=3&newsID=69 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-11-23 |title=Welcome &#124; The National Eisteddfod of Wales |publisher=Eisteddfod.org.uk |accessdate=2010-07-15 }}</ref> won the Daniel Owen Memorial Prize for his novel at the National [[Eisteddfod]] of Wales in 2008.\n\nThe famous Welsh composer and musician Prof [[David John de Lloyd]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://discoverwelshmusic.com/composers/david-de-lloyd/|title=David de Lloyd - Discover Welsh Music}}</ref> was raised and lived in the village.\n\nOther notable residents are the [[Bishop of Bangor]], the Right Reverend [[Andrew John]], [[Mike Jenkins (poet)|Mike Jenkins]] author, poet and father of [[Bethan Jenkins]] who was brought up in the village as a boy. The historian, [[Geraint_H._Jenkins|Emeritus Professor Geraint Huw Jenkins]], was born and raised in the village. [[Eurfyl ap Gwilym]], a Welsh economist, was from Penparcau.\n\n[[Jane Stanness]] was born in Penparcau. She is an actress, writer, singer and songwriter.<ref name=\"cam\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cambrian-news.co.uk/article.cfm?id=118971&headline=How%20Aberystwyth%20inspired%20multi-talented%20Jane&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2018 |title= How Aberystwyth inspired multi-talented Jane |publisher= cambrian-news.co.uk |year=2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180204231652/http://www.cambrian-news.co.uk/article.cfm?id=118971&headline=How%20Aberystwyth%20inspired%20multi-talented%20Jane&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2018 |archive-date= 4 February 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"som\">{{cite web|url= https://www.somersetlive.co.uk/news/somerset-news/bath-actress-describes-working-friends-3821207|title= Bath actress describes working with Friends star David Schwimmer |publisher= somersetlive.co.uk |year=2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nAberystwyth-Penparcau is the most populous electoral division in Ceredigion and elects two county councillors.\n\nPenparcau is also the name of the village which covers a portion of the electoral division consisting of the areas of Southgate and Caeffynnon.\n\nFive town councillors represent the ward on the [[Aberystwyth Town Council]], one of the 51 town and community councils in Ceredigion and consists of 19 town councillors elected in five wards. The last elections were held in May 2017.\n\nPenparcau is governed by [[Ceredigion County Council]] and Aberystwyth itself elects six of the 42 councillors in five separate wards (Bronglais, Central, North, [[Aberystwyth Rheidol|Rheidol]] and Penparcau - the Penparcau ward elects two of these). The two county councillors for Aberystwyth-Penparcau, elected in May 2017 were [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] and [[Plaid Cymru]].\n\nPenparcau has five [[Welsh Assembly]] members, one of whom is elected as a constituency AM for [[Ceredigion (Assembly constituency)|Ceredigion]], [[Elin Jones]] and four who are elected on the regional list for [[Mid and West Wales (National Assembly for Wales electoral region)|Mid and West Wales]].\n\nThe village is also within the [[Ceredigion (UK Parliament constituency)|Ceredigion]] constituency for elections to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]. The current MP is [[Ben Lake]] for [[Plaid Cymru]].\n\n==Sites of Special Scientific Interest==\nThe Penparcau electoral ward stretches from [[Tan-y-Bwlch, Aberystwyth|Tan y Bwlch]] beach to the [[River Rheidol|Rheidol]]. There are two [[Sites of Special Scientific Interest]] and the Pen Dinas and Tan y Bwlch Local Nature Reserves within this area.\n\n==Myth, folklore and legend==\nOne of the more unusual residents is the headless dog of Penparcau. The [[myth]] tells of how a giant, going to his father's rescue, rode at such a rate that his dog could not keep up with him and its head came off in the leash. The dog now roams, mournfully crying and looking for its long-lost owner.<ref>Jones, T. Gwynn (1930) ''Welsh Folklore and Folk-Custom'' London: Methuen & Co Ltd.</ref> It has also been theorised{{By whom|date=February 2020}} that the original inhabitants were the same people that made the Banc Ceilliau sun-disc<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.museumwales.ac.uk/walespast/article.shtml?id=8 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-11-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070603032948/http://www.museumwales.ac.uk/walespast/article.shtml?id=8 |archivedate=2007-06-03 }}</ref> in nearby [[Cwmystwyth]]. There are also many stories relating to the [[pirate]]s that used this part of the coastline such as Bartholomew \u2018[[Bartholomew Roberts|Black Bart]]\u2019 Roberts the Pirate.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nDuring one winter in the late 19th century, villagers woke to find mysterious footprints in the fresh snow. It soon became apparent that these had not been made by any human as they were hoofprints made by a creature who walked on two legs and not four. Villagers followed these hoofprints and found that the creature had walked through fields, roads and even managed to walk over walls and roofs in one uninterrupted path. It was believed that the Devil had walked through Penparcau that snowy night and has never been seen back since.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/mapsheet.aspx?compid=55182&sheetid=1321&ox=2217&oy=2807&zm=1&czm=1&x=353&y=167/ 1890 Map of Penparcau]\n*[http://penparcau.org Penparcau Community Site]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/PenparcauCommunityForum Penparcau Community Forum Site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928061524/http://www.coflein.gov.uk/pls/portal/COFLEIN.REP_CATLIST_B.show?p_arg_names=pnumlink&p_arg_values=6028832 Archives of the Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales 1]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928061533/http://www.coflein.gov.uk/pls/portal/COFLEIN.REP_CATLIST_B.show?p_arg_names=pnumlink&p_arg_values=6028864 Archives of the Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales 2]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928061506/http://www.coflein.gov.uk/pls/portal/COFLEIN.REP_CATLIST_B.show?p_arg_names=pnumlink&p_arg_values=6028918 Archives of the Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales 3]\n*[https://www.geograph.org.uk/search.php?i=3091249 www.geograph.co.uk : photos of Penparcau and surrounding area]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/PenparcauCommunityForum Penparcau]\n*[http://www.nomisweb.co.uk/maps/700/1308631041.aspx A map of the Penparcau ward]\n{{Ceredigion}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Ceredigion]]\n[[Category:Aberystwyth]]\n[[Category:Villages in Wales]]\n[[Category:Lists of places in Wales]]\n", "name_user": "Linguoboy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable Residents", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penparcau"}
{"title_page": "Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium", "text_new": "{{distinguish|John F. Kennedy Stadium (Philadelphia)}}\n{{short description|Multi-purpose stadium in Washington, D.C., United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name        = Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium\n| nickname            = ''RFK''\n| logo_image          = File:RFK Stadium logo.png\n| image               = File:RFK Stadium aerial photo, looking towards Capitol, 1988.jpg\n| caption             = RFK Stadium from the east in [[1988 Washington Redskins season|1988]],<br>looking towards the [[United States Capitol|U.S. Capitol]]\n| location            = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| coordinates         = {{coord|38.890|N|76.972|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=it}}\n| broke_ground        = July 8, 1960<ref name=\"bbt\">{{cite web |title=Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|url=http://www.ballparktour.com/RFK_Stadium.html|work=Ballpark Tour|access-date=March 11, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130406051839/http://www.ballparktour.com/RFK_Stadium.html|archivedate=April 6, 2013}}</ref>\n| opened              = October 1, 1961<br>({{Years or months ago|1961}})\n| closed              = \n| demolished          =\n| owner               = District of Columbia\n| operator            = [[Events DC]]\n| surface             = TifGrand [[Cynodon dactylon|Bermuda grass]]<ref name=SportsTurf>{{cite web|title=50 Years: Willie Leak maintains TifGrand bermudagrass at RFK Stadium|url=http://sportsturfonline.com/2014/01/20/50-years-willie-leak-maintains-tifgrand-bermudagrass-at-rfk-stadium/5880/|website=SportsTurf|access-date=July 11, 2015}}</ref>\n| architect           = [[George Dahl|George Leighton Dahl, Architects and Engineers, Inc.]]\n| structural engineer = [[Osborn Engineering|Osborn Engineering Company]]\n| services engineer   = [[Volkert, Inc.|Ewin Engineering Associates]]\n| general_contractor  = [[Thomas McCloskey|McCloskey and Co.]]\n| dimensions          = [[American football|Football]]: {{convert|120|x|53.333|yd|m|0|abbr=on}}<br>[[Association football|Soccer]]: {{convert|110|x|72|yd|m|0|abbr=on}}<br>[[Baseball]]:<br>'''Left field''': {{convert|335|ft|abbr=on}}<br>'''Left-center''': {{convert|380|ft|0|abbr=on}}<br>'''Center field''': {{convert|410|ft|0|abbr=on}}<br>'''Right-center''': {{convert|380|ft|0|abbr=on}}<br>'''Right field''': {{convert|335|ft|abbr=on}}<br>'''Backstop''': {{convert|54|ft|abbr=on}}\n| tenants             = [[Washington Redskins]] ([[National Football League|NFL]]) (1961\u20131996)<br>[[George Washington Colonials|Geo. Washington Colonials]] ([[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]) (1961\u20131966)<br>[[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Washington Senators]] (II) ([[Major League Baseball|MLB]]) (1962\u20131971)<br>[[Howard Bison football|Howard Bison]] ([[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]) (1974\u20131976)<br>[[Washington Whips]] ([[United Soccer Association|USA]] / [[North American Soccer League (1968\u20131984)|NASL]]) (1967\u20131968)<br>[[Washington Diplomats]] (NASL) (1974, 1977\u20131981);(ASL) (1988-1989);(APSL) (1990)<br>[[Team America (NASL)|Team America]] (NASL) (1983)<br>[[Orlando Renegades|Washington Federals]] ([[United States Football League|USFL]]) (1983\u20131984)<br>[[D.C. United]] ([[Major League Soccer|MLS]]) (1996\u20132017)<br>[[Washington Freedom]] ([[Women's United Soccer Association|WUSA]]) (2001\u20132003)<br>[[Washington Nationals]] (II) (MLB) (2005\u20132007)<br>[[Military Bowl]] (NCAA) (2008\u20132012)\n| website             = {{URL|http://eventsdc.com/Venues/RFKStadium.aspx}}\n| publictransit       = {{WMATA link logo}} '''[[Washington Metro]]''' <br> {{rint|washington|BL}}{{rint|washington|OR}}{{rint|washington|SV}} at [[Stadium\u2013Armory station|Stadium\u2013Armory]]<br>{{bus icon|12px}} [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]]: 96, 97, B2, D6\n| image_size          = 250 \n| address             = 2400 [[East Capitol Street]] SE\n| construction_cost   = [[United States dollar|$]]24 million<br>(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|US|24000000|1961}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}})\n| former_names        = District of Columbia <!--(D.C.)--> Stadium<br>(1961\u20131969) <!-- renamed January 18, dedication ceremony on June 7, 1969 -->\n| seating_capacity    = [[Baseball]]: <br>43,500 (1961)<br>45,016 (1971)<br>45,596 (2005)<br>[[American football|Football]] or [[Association football|soccer]]: <br>56,692 (1961)<br>45,596 (2005\u2013present)<br>20,000 (2012\u20132017, MLS)\n}}\n'''Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium''' (commonly known as '''RFK Stadium''', originally '''District of Columbia Stadium''') is a [[multi-purpose stadium]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] It is located about {{convert|2|mi|0|spell=in}} due east of the [[United States Capitol|U.S. Capitol building]], near the west bank of the [[Anacostia River]] and adjacent to the [[D.C. Armory]]. Opened {{Years or months ago|1961}} in 1961, it was owned by the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] until 1986.<ref name=flsdcgs>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=C4QwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YosDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1946%2C3330948 |work=Free Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |agency=Associated Press |title=District of Columbia gets RFK Stadium |date=October 18, 1986 |page=11}}</ref>\n\nRFK Stadium has been home to a [[National Football League]] (NFL) team, two [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) teams, five professional [[Association football|soccer]] teams, two [[college football]] teams, a [[bowl game]], and a [[United States Football League|USFL]] team. It has hosted five [[NFC Championship Game|NFC Championship games]], two [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|MLB All-Star Games]], men's and women's [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] matches, nine men's and women's first-round soccer games of the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Olympics]], three [[MLS Cup]] matches, two [[Major League Soccer All-Star Game|MLS All-Star games]], and numerous American friendlies and World Cup qualifying matches. It has hosted college football, college soccer, baseball exhibitions, boxing matches, a [[Tour DuPont|cycling]] race, a [[2002 American Le Mans Series|Le Mans]] auto race, marathons, and dozens of major concerts and other events.\n\nRFK was one of the first major stadiums designed to host both [[baseball]] and [[American football|football]]. Although other stadiums already served this purpose, such as [[Cleveland Stadium]] (1931) and Baltimore's [[Memorial Stadium (Baltimore)|Memorial Stadium]] (1950), RFK was one of the first to employ what became known as the circular \"[[Multi-purpose stadium|cookie-cutter]]\" design.\n\nIt is owned and operated by [[Events DC]] (the successor agency to the DC Armory Board), a quasi-public organization affiliated with the city government, under a lease that runs until 2038 from the [[National Park Service]], which owns the land.<ref>{{cite news|title=City Will Study RFK Stadium Options in Wake of Soccer Deal|first=Mike|last=DeBonis|url=https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2013-08-02/local/41000776_1_stadium-deal-soccer-deal-stadium-revenue|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=August 2, 2013|access-date=September 30, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130914225713/http://articles.washingtonpost.com/2013-08-02/local/41000776_1_stadium-deal-soccer-deal-stadium-revenue|archivedate=September 14, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn September 5, 2019, the District announced plans to demolish the stadium due to maintenance costs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCartney |first1=Robert |title=District to raze RFK Stadium by 2021 \u2014 but not necessarily so Redskins can build a new one |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/dc-politics/district-to-raze-rfk-stadium-by-2021--but-not-necessarily-so-redskins-can-build-a-new-one/2019/09/05/48b18fc6-cfea-11e9-87fa-8501a456c003_story.html |accessdate=5 September 2019 |work=The Washington Post |date=5 September 2019}}</ref>\n{{toclimit|3}}\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\nThe idea of a stadium at this location originated in 1932 when the [[Theodore Roosevelt Association|Roosevelt Memorial Association (RMA)]] proposed a [https://www.loc.gov/pictures/collection/cph/item/2002709006/  National Stadium] for the site and Allied Architects, a group of local architects organized in 1925 to secure large-scale projects from the government, made designs for it.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Scott|first1=Pamela|last2=Tepfer|first2=Diane|title=Capital Drawings: Architectural Designs for Washington, D.C., from the Library of Congress|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=tcbCO3_lq2oC}}|date=2005|publisher=JHU Press|isbn=0801872324|pages=36\u201337}}</ref> A \"National Stadium\" in Washington was an idea that had been pursued since 1916, when Congressman [[George Murray Hulbert|George Hulbert]] of [[New York's 21st congressional district|New York]] proposed the construction of a 50,000-seat stadium at [[East Potomac Park]] for the purpose of attracting the [[1920 Summer Olympics|1920 Olympics]]. It was thought that such a stadium could attract [[Davis Cup]] tennis matches, polo tournaments and the annual [[Army\u2013Navy Game|Army-Navy football game]]. A later effort by DC Director of Public Buildings and Parks [[Ulysses S. Grant III]] and Congressman [[Hamilton Fish III|Hamilton Fish]] of [[New York's 26th congressional district|New York]] sought to turn the National Stadium into a 100,000-seat memorial to [[Theodore Roosevelt]], suitable for hosting inaugurations, possibly on the [[National Mall]] or [[Theodore Roosevelt Island]]. This attracted the attention of the RMA, which suggested the East Capital location. This would allow the [[Lincoln Memorial]], then under construction west of the Capitol, and the Roosevelt memorial to become bookend monuments to the two great Republican presidents. The effort lost steam when Congress chose not to fund the stadium in time to move the [[1932 Summer Olympics|1932 Olympics]] from [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Dyersson|first1=Mark|last2=Trumpboer|first2=Robert|title=The Rise of Stadiums in the Modern United States: Cathedrals of Sport|date=13 September 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1317989288|pages=59\u201365}}</ref>\n\nThe idea of a stadium gained support in 1938, when Senator [[Robert Rice Reynolds|Robert Reynolds]] of [[North Carolina]] pushed for the creation of a municipal outdoor stadium within the District, citing the \"fact that America is the only major country not possessing a stadium with facilities to accommodate the Olympic Games\". The following year a model of the proposed stadium, to be located near the current site of RFK Stadium, was presented to the public. By 1941, the National Capital Planning Commission had begun buying property for a stadium, purchasing the land between East Capitol, C, 19th and 21st NE.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nearly All Land for D.C. Stadium bought |work=The Evening Star |date=20 February 1941}}</ref> A few years later, on December 20, 1944, Congress created a nine-man National Memorial Stadium Commission to study the idea.<ref name=\"Return\">{{cite web|last1=Roberts|first1=Jay|title=Return to RFK|url=http://jay.typepad.com/william_jay/2005/01/return_to_rfk.html|accessdate=30 December 2017}}</ref> They intended the stadium to be a memorial to the veterans of the World Wars. The commission wrote a report recommending that a 100,000-seat stadium be built near the site of RFK in time for the [[1948 Summer Olympics|1948 Olympics]], but it failed to get funding.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Adams|first1=Brett|title=Capital Sporting Grounds: A History of Stadium and Ballpark Construction in Washington, Part 3|date=24 November 2008|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0786452507|pages=139\u2013148}}</ref>\n\nIgnored in the early 1950s, a new stadium again drew interest in 1954. Congressman [[Charles R. Howell]] of [[New Jersey's 4th congressional district|New Jersey]] proposed legislation to build a stadium, again with hopes of attracting the Olympics. He pushed for a report, completed in 1956 by the National Capital Planning Commission entitled \"Preliminary Report on Sites for National Memorial Stadium\", which identified the \"East Capitol Site\" to be used for the stadium. In September 1957, \"The District of Columbia Stadium Act\" was introduced and authorized a 50,000-seat stadium to be used by the Senators and Redskins at the Armory site. It was signed into law by President [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Eisenhower]] on July 29, 1958, with an estimated cost of $7.5 to $8.6 million.<ref name=\"Return\"/> The lease for the stadium was signed by the D.C. Armory Board and the [[United States Department of the Interior|Department of the Interior]] on December 12, 1958. The stadium, the first major multisport facility built for both football and baseball, was designed by [[George Dahl]], Ewin Engineering Associates (since 1954 part of what became [[Volkert, Inc.]]) and [[Osborn Engineering]]. Groundbreaking for the {{nowrap|$24 million}} venue was in 1960 on July 8, and construction proceeded over the following 14 months.<ref name=\"History\"/> The existing venue for baseball (and football) in Washington was [[Griffith Stadium]], about {{convert|4|mi|0|spell=in}} northwest.\n\nWhile Redskins\u2019 owner [[George Preston Marshall]] was pleased with the stadium, Senators' owner [[Calvin Griffith]] was not. It wasn't where he wanted it to be (in Northwest) and he'd have to pay rent and let others run the parking and concessions. The Senators' attendance figures had suffered after the arrival of the [[Baltimore Orioles]] in [[1954 Baltimore Orioles season|1954]] and Griffith preferred the demographics and profit potential of the [[Minnesota]] market.<ref name=subsbb>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TzMaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=myUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7217%2C3690475 |work=Milwaukee Journal |agency=UPI |title=Subsidize baseball. attorney suggests |date=July 30, 1958 |page=21}}</ref> In 1960, when Major League Baseball granted the city of Minneapolis an expansion team, Griffith proposed that he be allowed to [[relocation of professional sports teams|move]] his team to [[Minneapolis-Saint Paul]] and give the expansion team to Washington. Upon league approval, the team moved to [[1961 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota]] after the [[1960 Washington Senators season|1960]] season and Washington fielded a \"new [[1961 Washington Senators season|Senators]]\" team, entering the junior circuit in {{mlby|1961}} with the [[1961 Los Angeles Angels season|Los Angeles Angels]].<ref name=\"Return\"/>\n\n===Opening===\nThe stadium opened in autumn 1961 as District of Columbia Stadium (often shortened to D.C. Stadium); its first official event was an NFL regular season game on October 1, ten days after the final MLB baseball game at [[Griffith Stadium]]. The new venue opened for football even though construction wasn't completed until the following spring<!--1962-->.<ref name=\"Jail\">{{cite news|title=Jail is Stadium's Newest Asset|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/90430898|access-date=January 17, 2018|date=September 2, 1961}}</ref> The [[1961 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]] lost that game to the [[1961 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] {{nowrap|24\u201321}} before 36,767 fans, including [[President of the United States|President]] [[John F. Kennedy]].<ref name=tlgrns>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=F3ZSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=2BAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5035%2C1151646 |work=Milwaukee Sentinel |agency=Associated Press |title=Tittle-led Giants rally nip Skins |date=October 2, 1961 |page=3, part 2}}</ref> This was slightly more than the attendance record at Griffith Stadium (36,591 on October 26, [[1947 Washington Redskins season|1947]], vs the [[1947 Chicago Bears season|Bears]]).<ref name=\"Return\"/><ref name=tlgrns/> At a college football game labeled the \"Dedication Game\", the stadium was dedicated on October 7. [[George Washington Colonials football|George Washington]] became the first home team to win at the stadium with a {{nowrap|30\u20136}} defeat of [[VMI Keydets football|VMI]].<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web |title= RFK: Our History |url= http://www.dcconvention.com/getattachment/Venues/RFKStadium/OurHistory/RFK-Our-history-copy-for-website-(2).pdf.aspx |accessdate= 29 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|title=BASEBALL TO PLAY FIRST GAME AT NATIONALS PARK |url= http://www.gwsports.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/022908aab.html |accessdate= 29 December 2017 |date= 29 February 2008}}</ref> Its first sell-out came on November 23, 1961, for the first of the annual Thanksgiving Day high school football games between the public school champion, [[Eastern High School (Washington, D.C.)|Eastern]], and the Catholic school champion, [[St. John's College High School|St. John's]], which was won by Eastern, {{nowrap|37\u201314.<ref>{{cite news|title=Preps Draw Crown|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/10505636|accessdate=20 January 2018|date=24 November 1961}}</ref>}}\n[[File:First pitch DC Stadium JFK.jpg|thumb|President <!--John F.-->Kennedy throws the first pitch of the {{mlby|1962}}<!--April 9--> baseball season at D.C. Stadium<!-- Washington, D.C.-->]]\nThe first major league baseball game was on April 9, [[1962 Washington Senators season|1962]] (after two exhibition games against the [[1962 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pirates]] had been cancelled). President Kennedy threw out the ceremonial first pitch in front of 44,383 fans who watched the Senators defeat the [[1962 Detroit Tigers season|Detroit Tigers]] {{nowrap|4\u20131}} and shortstop [[Bob Johnson (infielder)|Bob Johnson]] hit the first {{nowrap|home run.<ref name=ndfttig>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=u0RjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PnQNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1544%2C1897957 |title=Nats defeat Tigers behind Daniels, JFK |date=April 10, 1962 |page=9}}</ref><ref name=srdddty>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hNMtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=i-cDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7052%2C3545471 |work=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington) |agency=Associated Press |title=Daniels does duty; hurls opening win |date=April 10, 1962 |page=13}}</ref>}} The previous baseball attendance record was 38,701 at Griffith Stadium on October 11, [[1925 Washington Senators season|1925]], at the fourth game of the [[1925 World Series|World Series]]. The attendance figure was the largest ever for a professional sports event in Washington.<ref name=flslspotl>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wXcQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QIwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7472%2C570113 |work=Tree Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |last=Buttram |first=Bill |title=Stadium, howling Marine steal spotlight |date=April 10, 1962 |page=6}}</ref> The previous largest opening day figure was 31,728 (April 19, [[1948 Washington Senators season|1948]]).<ref name=\"Return\"/>\n\nWhen it opened, D.C. Stadium hosted the Redskins, [[Washington Senators (1961\u201371)|Senators]], and the GWU Colonial football team, all of whom had previously used Griffith Stadium. The Colonials disbanded their football team after the [[1966 college football season|1966]] season, and the Senators left in the fall of 1971 for {{nowrap|[[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex|Dallas\u2013Fort Worth]]}} and became the [[1972 Texas Rangers season|Texas Rangers]] in [[Arlington Stadium|Arlington]] in [[1972 Texas Rangers season|1972]].\n\n=== Early years ===\nFrom 1961 to 1963, D.C. Stadium hosted the annual City Title game, matching the D.C. public school champion and the winner of the area's premier Catholic league, played before capacity crowds on [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving Day]]. The 1963 game between St. John's, a predominantly white school in Northwest D.C., and Eastern, a majority-black school just blocks from the stadium, ended in a racially motivated riot, only three days after the [[State funeral of John F. Kennedy|funeral of President Kennedy]]. The City Title game for 1964 was canceled and never played again.<ref>{{cite web|title=Worst sports moments in D.C. history|url=http://www.espn.com/page2/wash/s/list/worstmoments.html|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=20 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1964, the stadium emerged as an element in the [[Bobby Baker]] bribery scandal. Don B. Reynolds, a Maryland insurance businessman, made a statement in August 1964 which he claimed that [[Matthew McCloskey]], a former [[Democratic National Committee]] chairman and Kennedy's [[List of ambassadors of the United States to Ireland|ambassador]] to [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], paid a $25,000 kickback through Reynolds and at the instruction of Baker to the [[John F. Kennedy presidential campaign, 1960|Kennedy-Johnson campaign]] as payback for the stadium construction contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=Key Man Held Back Records|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/17435272|access-date=January 29, 2018|work=Tucson Daily Citizen|date=February 2, 1965}}</ref> Baker later went to jail for tax fraud, and the FBI investigated the awarding of the stadium contract, although McCloskey was never charged.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/10391831/mccloskey_probe/ |title=McCloskey Faces Suit, FBI Probe |url-access=limited |newspaper=[[Philadelphia Daily News]] |via=newspapers.com |date=January 23, 1964 |access-date=April 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Renaming the stadium===\nThe stadium was renamed in January 1969 for [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] and [[1968 United States presidential election|presidential]] candidate [[Robert F. Kennedy]],<ref name=tbldrfk>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QfNOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BAIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4964%2C5819035 |newspaper=Toledo Blade |agency=Associated Press |title=Stadium renamed for Robert Kennedy |date=January 19, 1968 |page=16A}}</ref> who had been [[Assassination of Robert F. Kennedy|assassinated]] in Los Angeles seven months earlier. The announcement was made by [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] [[Stewart Udall]] on January 18, in the last days of the [[Presidency of Lyndon Johnson|Johnson Administration]].<ref name=ctdcssc>{{cite news |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1969/01/19/page/56/article/d-c-stadium-name-changed-to-honor-r-f-k |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |agency=UPI |title=D.C. Stadium name changed to honor R.F.K. |date=January 19, 1969 |page=2, section 2}}</ref><ref name=wtophigin>{{cite web|url=https://wtop.com/sports/2017/10/end-runs-curve-balls-last-minute-shots-rfk-stadium-got-name/slide/1/ |publisher=WTOP-TV |location=(Washington, DC) |last=Massimo |first=Rick |title=End runs, curve balls and last-minute shots: How RFK Stadium got its name|date=October 20, 2017 |accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref> The dedication ceremony at the stadium was held several months later on June 7.<ref name=wtophigin/><ref name=rddecer>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=35QtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cKAFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6041%2C3743206 |work=Reading Eagle |location=(Pennsylvania) |agency=Associated Press |title=Stadium dedicated to Sen. Kennedy |date=June 8, 1969 |page=3}}</ref>\n\n===Senators depart===\nThe Senators' final game was at RFK on Thursday night, September 30, 1971,<ref name=gingwet>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BvRNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=14oDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5342%2C3752463|work=Free Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |agency=Associated Press |last=Polk |first=James R.|title=Ginger may send Nats away wet |date=September 30, 1971 }}</ref> with less than 15,000 in attendance.<ref name=ffotsen>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=B_RNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=14oDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7276%2C3891864 |work=Free Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |agency=Associated Press |last=Lowitt |first=Bruce |title=Fans 'finish off' the Senators |date=October 1, 1971 }}</ref> Rains from [[Hurricane Ginger]] threatened the event,<ref name=gingwet/> but the game proceeded. Fan favorite Frank \"Hondo\" Howard hit a home run (RFK's last until [[2005 Washington Nationals season|2005]]) in the sixth inning to spark a four-run rally to tie the game; the Senators scored two more in the eighth to go up {{nowrap|7\u20135,}} but the game was forfeited {{nowrap|(9\u20130)}} to the [[1971 New York Yankees season|Yankees]] after unruly fans stormed the field with two outs in the top of the ninth.<ref name=\"Return\"/><ref name=gingwet/> Subsequent efforts to bring baseball back to RFK, including an attempt to attract the [[1973 San Diego Padres season|San Diego Padres]] in {{mlby|1973}},<ref name=fillstd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rABOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7IsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3050%2C4018383|work=Free Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |agency=Associated Press |last=Seppy |first=Tom|title='We're going to fill stadium,' promises D.C. mayor Washington |date=May 29, 1973|page=6}}</ref><ref name=bhtkp>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rQBOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7IsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2633%2C4170364 |work=Free Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |agency=Associated Press |title=Bavasi hoping to keep Padres in San Diego |date=May 30, 1973|page=14}}</ref><ref name=sdunfrm>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/dc-sports-bog/wp/2016/06/16/the-time-the-san-diego-padres-were-this-close-to-moving-to-d-c/ |work=Washington Post |last=Russell |first=Jake |title=San Diego Padres were once so close to moving to D.C. they had uniforms and everything |date=June 16, 2016 |accessdate=May 15, 2018}}</ref> and a plan to have the nearby [[1976 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]] play eleven home games there in [[1976 Baltimore Orioles season|1976]], all failed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Capitol Excited about new Team|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/62603749|accessdate=15 January 2018|work=The Jacksonville Daily Journal|date=30 May 1973}}</ref> The former was derailed by lease issues with the city in San Diego,<ref name=sdunfrm/> and the latter was shot down by commissioner [[Bowie Kuhn]], who wanted to bring one of four expansion teams instead.<ref name=krjbidc>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TNRHAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LowDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4540%2C2568576 |work=Free Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |agency=Associated Press |title=Kuhn rejects Birds in D.C. |date=October 15, 1975|page=9}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Birds '76 RFK Plans Rejected|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/18458714|accessdate=15 January 2018|work=Cumberland Evening Times|date=15 October 1975}}</ref> The expansion for {{mlby|1977}} was later reduced to two teams, [[1977 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto]] and [[1977 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle]], and the next wasn't until {{mlby|1993}}.\n\nIn the mid-1990s RFK was planned to be the home of the yet-to-be-named Washington team, a charter franchise of the [[United Baseball League (proposed)|United League]] (UL) which was planned to be a third league of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB).\n\nFor much of the 1970s and 1980s, RFK was primarily known as the home of the Redskins, where they played during their three Super Bowl championship seasons. It also hosted several short-lived professional soccer teams and in 1983\u20131984 the [[Washington Federals]] of the [[USFL]]. In [[1980 North American Soccer League season|1980]], it hosted the [[Soccer Bowl '80|Soccer Bowl]], the championship game of the [[North American Soccer League|NASL]].\n\n===D.C. United moves in, Redskins move out, Nationals come and go===\nMajor changes to the stadium came in 1996. Following the success of hosting matches in the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994 World Cup]] and [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Summer Olympics]], RFK became home to one of the charter teams of the new [[Major League Soccer]]. On April 20, 1996, it played host to the first home match of [[D.C. United]], a 2\u20131 loss to the [[LA Galaxy]].\n\nHowever, later that year the stadium hosted the Redskins' final home game in Washington, DC. After nearly a decade of negotiating for a new stadium with Mayors [[Sharon Pratt|Sharon Pratt Kelly]] and [[Marion Barry]], abandoning them in 1992 and 1993 in search of a suburban site and then having a 1994 agreement collapse in the face of neighborhood complaints, environmental concerns and a dispute in Congress (over what some members viewed as the team's racially insensitive name and the use of federal land for private profit), [[Jack Kent Cooke]] decided to move his team to Maryland.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weil|first1=Martin|last2=Wilgoren|first2=Debbi|title=Redskins Continue Negotiations Over RFK, New Stadium|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/redskins/longterm/1997/stadium/timeline/1992/dcdeal.htm|accessdate=29 December 2017|date=8 December 1992}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Schneider|first1=Howard|last2=Harris|first2=Hamil R.|title=BARRY'S STADIUM PLAN WOULD REPLACE RFK|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1995/11/10/barrys-stadium-plan-would-replace-rfk/0623f1dc-ffa3-4abf-a020-21b72f4e5974/|accessdate=29 December 2017|date=10 November 1995}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sell|first1=Dave|title=FOR JACK KENT COOKE, THIS WEEKEND WAS A VERY BIG DEAL|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1995/12/05/for-jack-kent-cooke-this-weekend-was-a-very-big-deal/ad292bc8-a697-4967-91da-5004d8d03e88/|accessdate=29 December 2017|date=5 December 1995}}</ref> On December 22, 1996, the Redskins won their last game at RFK Stadium 37-10 over the Dallas Cowboys, reprising their  first win there in 1961, before 65,454, the largest football crowd in stadium history. The Redskins then moved east to [[FedExField]] in [[1997 Washington Redskins season|1997]], leaving [[D.C. United]] as the stadium's only major tenant for much of the next decade, though from 2001 to 2003 they were joined by the [[Washington Freedom]] of the short-lived [[Women's United Soccer Association]].\n\nAfter hosting 16 exhibition games after the Senators' departure, baseball returned to RFK temporarily in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|title=Washington, D.C. Ballparks|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/content/printer_friendly/mlb/y2004/m09/d30/c876716.jsp|accessdate=4 January 2018}}</ref> That year the [[National League]]'s newly renamed [[Washington Nationals]] made it their home while a new permanent home, [[Nationals Park]], was constructed. On April 14, 2005, before a crowd of 45,496 including President Bush and MLB Commissioner [[Bud Selig]], the Nationals beat the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] 5-3 victory in their first game at RFK. President [[George W. Bush]], formerly a part-owner of the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] (the former Senators), threw out the first pitch becoming the last president, and the first since [[Richard Nixon]], to do so in RFK Stadium.<ref name=\"History\"/> The last MLB game at RFK, a 5-3 Nationals win over the Phillies, was played on September 23, 2007, and in [[2008 Washington Nationals season|2008]] the Nationals moved to their new stadium.\n\n===The last team leaves===\nIn 2008, RFK was once again primarily the host of [[D.C. United]], though it also hosted a [[college football]] [[bowl game]], the [[Military Bowl]], from [[2008 EagleBank Bowl|2008]] to [[2012 Military Bowl|2012]], before it moved in [[2013 Military Bowl|2013]] to {{nowrap|[[Navy\u2013Marine Corps Memorial Stadium]]}} in [[Annapolis, Maryland]].<ref name=\"Move to Annapolis\">{{cite news |title=Military Bowl Moving to Annapolis, Adds Conference USA for '13|first=Chip|last=Patterson|url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegefootball/blog/eye-on-college-football/22274326/military-bowl-moving-to-annapolis-adds-conference-usa-for-13 |work=[[CBS Sports]]|date=May 20, 2013|accessdate=May 21, 2013}}</ref> On July 25, 2013, the District of Columbia and D.C. United announced a tentative deal to build a $300 million, 20,000\u201325,000 seat stadium at [[Buzzard Point]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.stadiadirectory.com/deal-reached-for-new-d-c-united-stadium/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130927074329/http://www.stadiadirectory.com/deal-reached-for-new-d-c-united-stadium/ |url-status= dead |archive-date= September 27, 2013 |title= Deal reached for new stadium |work= StadiaDirectory |date= July 25, 2013 |accessdate= July 25, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Term Sheet DC United Stadium Project |work=District of Columbia and DC Soccer LLC |date=July 25, 2013 |publisher=District of Columbia Office of the City Administrator |url=http://oca.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/oca/page_content/attachments/Soccer%20Stadium%20Term%20Sheet%20%28executed%20copy%29.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304033833/http://oca.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/oca/page_content/attachments/Soccer%20Stadium%20Term%20Sheet%20%28executed%20copy%29.pdf |archivedate=March 4, 2016 }}</ref> Groundbreaking on the new soccer stadium, [[Audi Field]], occurred in February 2017 (and was completed the following July) and on October 22, 2017 RFK hosted its last MLS match, a 2-1 loss to the New York Red Bulls.<ref>{{cite news |title= DC United 1, New York Red Bulls 2 {{!}} 2017 MLS Match Recap |url= https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/10/22/dc-united-1-new-york-red-bulls-2-2017-mls-match-recap |accessdate= 29 December 2017 |date= 22 October 2017}}</ref>  One of the last events at RFK Memorial Stadium was to be a [[Garth Brooks]] concert in 2019, but it never was announced.\n\n===Demolition plans announced===\nOn September 5, 2019, Events DC announced plans to demolish the stadium by 2021.  Officials said the decision would save $2 million a year on maintenance and $1.5 million a year on utilities.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McCartney|first1=Robert|title=Bye-bye, bouncy seats: District to raze RFK Stadium by 2021|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/dc-politics/district-to-raze-rfk-stadium-by-2021--but-not-necessarily-so-redskins-can-build-a-new-one/2019/09/05/48b18fc6-cfea-11e9-87fa-8501a456c003_story.html|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=September 5, 2019|date=September 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Name==\nThe stadium opened in October 1961 named the District of Columbia Stadium, but the media quickly shortened that to D.C. Stadium and sometimes, in the early days, as \"Washington Stadium\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Griffith Stadium Now Ghost Park|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/294671900|accessdate=17 January 2018|date=21 September 1961}}</ref> On January 18, 1969, in the last days of the [[Lyndon B. Johnson|Johnson Administration]], [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] [[Stewart Udall]] announced that the stadium would be renamed [[Robert F. Kennedy]] Memorial Stadium, in Kennedy's honor.<ref name=wtophigin/><ref name=tbldrfk/> The official renaming ceremony was held {{nowrap|on June 7,<ref name=wtophigin/><ref name=rddecer/>}} but by then many had already been referring to it as \"RFK Stadium\" or simply \"RFK\".<ref name=Return/> Coincidentally, following the death of John F. Kennedy in 1963, the Armory Board had directed that the stadium be renamed for him,<ref>{{cite news|title=Kennedy Memorial|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/43144743|accessdate=28 January 2018|work=The High Point Enterprise|date=6 December 1963}}</ref> but the plan faltered when a few weeks later the Philadelphia city council passed a bill renaming [[John F. Kennedy Stadium (Philadelphia)|Philadelphia Stadium]] as \"John F. Kennedy Stadium\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Stadium Honors John F. Kennedy|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/56822776|accessdate=28 January 2018|work=The Times Record|date=27 December 1963}}</ref>\n\nRobert Kennedy was not without connection to the stadium; as [[United States Attorney General|attorney general]] in the early 1960s, his [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] played a role in the Redskins' racial integration.<ref name=\"Smith, Thomas G. 2011 pp. 1-2\">Smith, Thomas G., \u2013 Showdown: JFK and the Integration of the Washington Redskins, Beacon Press (2011), pp. 1-2</ref> Along with Udall, Kennedy threatened to revoke the team's lease at the federally owned stadium until it promised to sign [[African American]] players.<ref name=\"Smith, Thomas G. 2011 pp. 1-2\"/><ref name=\"npr.org\">{{cite web|last=Smith |first=Thomas G. |url=https://www.npr.org/2011/09/04/140066378/a-showdown-that-changed-footballs-racial-history |title=A 'Showdown' That Changed Football's Racial History |publisher=NPR |date=2011-09-04 |accessdate=2017-08-28}}</ref> His brother John attended the first event there and threw out the first pitch. In 2008, a nearby [[Ethel Kennedy Bridge|bridge]] was renamed for [[Ethel Kennedy]], Robert Kennedy's wife.\n\nOn April 14, 2005, just before the Nationals' home opener, the D.C. Sports and Entertainment Commission announced an agreement with the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] under which the military would pay the city about $6 million for [[naming rights]] and the right to place recruiting kiosks and signage in the stadium. In return, the stadium would be dubbed \"Armed Forces Field at RFK Stadium\".<ref name=armedforcesfield>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A51287-2005Apr13.html|title=RFK's Field May Be Named For Military|publisher=}}</ref> This plan was dropped within days, however, after several prominent members of [[United States Congress|Congress]] questioned the use of public funds for a stadium sponsorship.<ref name=profund>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/05/03/AR2005050301441.html|title=Investing Firm Close to Deal on Renaming RFK|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nSimilar proposals to sell the naming rights to the [[National Guard of the United States|National Guard]],<ref name=armedforcesfield /> ProFunds (a Bethesda, Maryland investment company),<ref name=profund /> and Sony<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/stories/2006/04/17/tidbits1.html|title=Surround sound|work=Washington Business Journal}}</ref> were formed and discarded in 2005 and 2006.\n\n==Tenants==\n===Redskins (1961\u20131996)===\nRFK Stadium was home to the Redskins for 36 seasons, from [[1961 Washington Redskins season|1961]] through [[1996 Washington Redskins season|1996]]. The football field was aligned northwest to southeast, along the first baseline.\n\n<!--The team's return to prominence as a football power began the same year ([[1960 Washington Redskins season|1960]]) that the [[Washington Senators (1901\u201360)|original baseball Senators]] played their final season, relocating in [[1961 Minnesota Twins season|1961]] to Minnesota as the [[Minnesota Twins|Twins]].-->The Redskins' first game in D.C. Stadium was its first event, a 24\u201321 loss to the [[1961 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] on October 1, [[1961 Washington Redskins season|1961]]. The first win in the stadium came at the end of the season on December 17, over its future archrival, the struggling second-year [[1961 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]]. The Redskins played 266 regular-season games at RFK, compiling a {{winning percentage|173|102|3|record=y}} record, including an impressive {{nowrap|11\u20131}} record in the playoffs.<ref name=goff20171020/>\n\nIn its twelfth season, RFK hosted its first professional football playoff game on Christmas Eve [[1972 Washington Redskins season|1972]], a 16\u20133 Redskins' win over the [[1972 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]]. It was the city's first postseason game in three decades, following the [[1942 NFL Championship Game|NFL championship game]] victory in [[1942 Washington Redskins season|1942]]. The stadium hosted the [[NFC Championship Game]] five times ([[1972\u201373 NFL playoffs|1972]], [[1982\u201383 NFL playoffs|1982]], [[1983\u201384 NFL playoffs|1983]], [[1987\u201388 NFL playoffs|1987]], and [[1991\u201392 NFL playoffs|1991]]), 2nd only to [[Candlestick Park]], and the Redskins won them all. They are the only team to win five NFC titles at the same stadium. In the subsequent [[Super Bowl]]s, Washington won three ([[Super Bowl XVII|XVII]], [[Super Bowl XXII|XXII]], [[Super Bowl XXVI|XXVI]]).\n\nThe Redskins' last game at the stadium was a victory, as 56,454 saw a {{nowrap|37\u201310}} win over the division champion [[1996 Dallas Cowboys season|Cowboys]] on December 22, [[1996 Washington Redskins season|1996]].<ref name=fparfk>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SeoyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0QcGAAAAIBAJ&pg=6112%2C4295371|work=Free Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia)|agency=Associated Press |last=White |first=Joseph |title=Final play at RFK |date=December 23, 1996 |page=A1}}</ref><ref name=iardar>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SeoyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0QcGAAAAIBAJ&pg=4219%2C4328685|work=Free Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia)|agency=Associated Press |last=White |first=Joseph |title=It's a Redskins day at RFK |date=December 23, 1996 |page=B1}}</ref> Perhaps fittingly, [[Pat Summerall]], who scored the first extra point and field goal in the first football game at the stadium, also was the TV announcer for the final game.\n\n===D.C. United (1996\u20132017)===\n[[File:Rfkstadium.png|200px|right|thumb|RFK Stadium during a [[D.C. United]] soccer match in March 2009]]\n[[D.C. United]] of [[Major League Soccer]] played over 400 matches at RFK Stadium from the team's debut in 1996 until 2017, when they moved to a new stadium. During that time, RFK hosted three [[MLS Cup]] finals, including the 1997 match won by D.C. United. At RFK, they compiled a {{winning percentage|228|113|75|record=y}} record, winning more games at RFK than any team other than the Senators.\n\nWith its new stadium, [[Audi Field]], set to open on July 14, 2018, D.C. United played its final game at RFK on October 22, 2017, completing 22 seasons at the stadium, during which the team won four league titles.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Alicia|title=DC United to open Audi Field on July 14 vs. Vancouver Whitecaps FC|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/01/04/dc-united-open-audi-field-july-14-vs-vancouver-whitecaps-fc|accessdate=12 January 2018|date=4 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=goff20171022>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2017/10/22/d-c-united-celebrates-its-past-on-emotional-final-day-at-rfk-stadium/|title=D.C. United celebrates its past on emotional final day at RFK Stadium|first=Steven|last=Goff|date=October 22, 2017|publisher=|access-date=February 1, 2018|via=www.WashingtonPost.com}}</ref> At the time, RFK Stadium was the longest-used stadium in MLS and the only one left from the league's debut season. When they shared the stadium with the Nationals from 2005 to 2007, the playing surface drew criticism along with the dimensions of the field that resulted from baseball use. D.C. United's departure left RFK with no professional sports tenant, however after moving to Audi Field, D.C. United continued to use the outer practice fields at RFK for training and leased locker room and basement space there.<ref name=goff20171020/>\n\n===Senators (1962\u20131971)===\n[[File:District of Columbia Stadium 1963.jpeg|thumb|220px|D.C. Stadium in [[1963 Washington Senators season|1963]], looking west]]\nThe expansion [[Washington Senators (1961\u201371)|Washington Senators]] of the [[American League]] played at RFK Stadium from [[1962 Washington Senators season|1962]] through [[1971 Washington Senators season|1971]]. They played their first season in [[1961 Washington Senators season|1961]] at [[Griffith Stadium]].\n\nIn its ten seasons as the Senators' home field, RFK Stadium was known as a hitters' park, aided by the stagnant heat (and humidity) of Washington summers. Slugger Frank Howard, ({{height|ft=6|in=7}}, {{convert|255|lb|abbr=on}})<!--left fielder-->, hit a number of tape-measure home runs, few of which landed in the center field area of the upper deck. The seats he hit with his home runs are painted white, rather than the gold of the rest of the upper deck. Howard came to the Senators from the [[1964 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] in [[1965 Washington Senators season|1965]]. He hit the Senators\u2032 final RFK homer, in the sixth inning on September 30, 1971. With two outs in the top of the ninth,<ref name=mjffss>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=6t8jAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5CgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3441%2C216303 |newspaper=Milwaukee Journal |agency=press dispatches |title=Fans' farewell: 'Short stinks' |date=October 1, 1971 |page=14, part 2 }}</ref> a fan riot turned a 7\u20135 Senators lead over the [[1971 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] into a 9\u20130 forfeit loss, the first in the [[Major League Baseball|majors]] in 17 years.<ref name=ffothes>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=B_RNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=14oDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7276%2C3891864 |newspaper=Free Lance-Star |location=Fredericksburg, Virginia |agency=Associated Press |last=Lowitt |first=Bruce |title=Fans 'finish off' Senators |date=October 1, 1971 |page=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1971/10/01/page/63/article/senators-last-hurrah-fans-cause-forfeit-9-0 |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |agency=UPI |title=Senators last 'hurrah;' fans cause forfeit 9-0 |date=October 1, 1971 |page=1, section 3}}</ref>\n\nThese Senators' only winning season came in [[1969 Washington Senators season|1969]] at {{nowrap|{{Winning percentage|86|76|record=y}}}}; they never made the postseason. They had a home record at RFK of {{nowrap|{{winning percentage|363|441|record=y}},}} representing the most games, wins, and losses by any team at RFK in any sport. The stadium hosted the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] twice, in [[1962 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|1962]] (first of two) and [[1969 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1969]], both won by the visiting National League. Presidents Kennedy, Johnson and Nixon all attended games there. President Johnson was scheduled to throw out the first pitch in [[1968 Washington Senators season|1968]], but the opening game was delayed following the [[Assassination of Martin Luther King Jr.|assassination]] of [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]], so [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Hubert Humphrey]] got the privilege.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vice President Opens 1968 Baseball Season|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16960018/|accessdate=29 January 2018|work=Beckley Post-Herald|date=11 April 1968}}</ref> President Nixon was to throw out the first ball at the 1969 game to celebrate baseball's centennial, but it was postponed due to rain and so Nixon chose instead to greet the [[Apollo 11]] astronauts. Vice President [[Spiro Agnew]] filled in.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hopes Pinned on Improved Weather Today|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/283253092|accessdate=15 January 2018|work=The Daily Times of Salisbury, Maryland|date=23 July 1969}}</ref>\n\n===Diplomats (1974\u20131981, 1988\u20131990)===\nBetween 1974 and 1990, three soccer teams played at RFK under the name [[Washington Diplomats]]. In [[1974 North American Soccer League season|1974]], two Maryland businessmen purchased the rights to the Baltimore Bays of the semi-professional [[American Soccer League (1933\u201383)|American Soccer League]], moved the team to the District and renamed it the Washington Diplomats. They signed a lease calculating that an average of 12,000 spectators would allow them to break even. Despite [[white flight]], owners thought that recent completion of the [[Interstate 495 (Capital Beltway)|Beltway]], the stadium's 12,000 parking spaces and future completion of a [[Washington Metro|Metro]] station would facilitate attendance. Games were scheduled for Saturday and prices were set low. The Diplomats inaugural game was on May 4 with an attendance of 10,175; Mayor [[Walter Washington]] ceremonially kicked off the game, but the Dips lost 5\u20131 to the [[1973 North American Soccer League season|defending]] [[North American Soccer League (1968\u201384)|NASL]] champion [[Philadelphia Atoms]]. Attendance dropped throughout the season.<ref name=\"DartsWhipsDips\">{{cite book|last1=Elzey|first1=Chris|last2=Wiggins|first2=David K.|title=DC Sports: The Nation's Capital at Play|date=Jul 15, 2015|publisher=University of Arkansas Press|isbn=9781610755665|pages=159\u2013161}}</ref>\n\nIn [[1975 North American Soccer League season|1975]], the Diplomats were informed that the recently installed natural turf at RFK would not be ready for opening day, so they scheduled their first two home games that season for [[Wilbert Tucker Woodson High School|W.T. Woodson High School]] in [[Fairfax, Virginia]]. After the games attracted more than 10,000 fans each, the Diplomats moved most of their home games to Woodson, but then moved the last five back to RFK once soccer superstar [[Pel\u00e9]] was added to the roster of the [[New York Cosmos (1970\u201385)|New York Cosmos]]. Pel\u00e9 was so popular that the 1975 Cosmos-Diplomats match broke the NASL attendance record at 35,620.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pele Packs Stands at RFK Stadium|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/43269802|accessdate=30 January 2018|work=The Capitol|date=30 June 1975}}</ref> Even with the success of the Cosmos game, attendance declined again and before the [[1976 North American Soccer League season|1976]] season the Diplomats announced that they had scheduled every home game, except the one against the Cosmos, at Woodson. During the season, they moved that game to Woodson.<ref name=\"DartsWhipsDips\"/>\n\nAfter averaging 5,963 at Woodson, the Diplomats decided to ramp up their marketing and move back to RFK in [[1977 North American Soccer League season|1977]]. The team changed everything from the uniforms to the cheerleaders, but the team's disappointing on-the-field performance hurt attendance (a ~31,000 fan game against Pel\u00e9 and the Cosmos notwithstanding). In [[1978 North American Soccer League season|1978]], attendance continued to fall, even though the Dips made the playoffs. Success on the field during the 1978 and [[1979 North American Soccer League season|1979]] seasons (including a franchise-best 19 wins in '79) did not translate to ticket a sales and even with a negligible amount of revenue from \u201c[[Indoor soccer|indoor]] Dips\u201d games at the D.C. Armory during the offseason, the franchise continued to lose money.<ref name=\"DartsWhipsDips\"/>\n\nIn [[1980 North American Soccer League season|1980]], they signed Dutch international superstar [[Johan Cruyff]], the Pel\u00e9 of the [[Potomac River|Potomac]], from the [[Los Angeles Aztecs]]. Needing 20,000 fans per game to break even, they managed to attract 24,000 for the opener and a District record 53,351 for the game against the Pele-less Cosmos (the fifth-largest soccer crowd at RFK ever), but the team failed to break-even financially. After racking up debts of $5 million, the first incarnation of the Dips folded.<ref name=\"DartsWhipsDips\"/>\n\nThree months later, the [[Detroit Express]] announced a move to D.C. for [[1981 North American Soccer League season|1981]], and that they would also be the Diplomats. They had trouble attracting fans;<!--after the NASL championship game, the \"[[Soccer Bowl '80|Soccer Bowl]]\", was held at RFK,--> and soon folded.\n\nThe Diplomats of the NASL, racked up an impressive {{winning percentage|60|29|record=y}} record at RFK, the best winning percentage of any RFK home team, and were {{nowrap|1\u20131}} in the playoffs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Washington Diplomats Games|url=http://soccerstats.us/teams/washington-diplomats/games/|website=Soccer Stats|accessdate=30 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"DartsWhipsDips\"/>\n\nIn 1987, a new soccer team also called the [[Washington Diplomats (1988\u201390)|Washington Diplomats]], was formed. They played at RFK, and sometimes at the RFK auxiliary field, for three seasons as part of the [[American Soccer League (1988\u201389)|ASL]] and then the [[American Professional Soccer League|APSL]]. They won the ASL Championship in 1988 but often drew fewer than 1000 fans. In 1990 they finished last in the Southern Division of the APSL East, were unable to pay the rent and folded in October 1990.<ref name=\"Merger\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Jackson|first1=James H.|title=Bays, Stars merger Diplomats kick in|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1990-10-30/sports/1990303001_1_maryland-bays-diplomats-baltimore-washington-area|accessdate=31 January 2018|date=30 October 1990}}</ref> Over the course of 4 seasons they were {{winning percentage|18|15|record=y}} at RFK, and 2-0 at the RFK auxiliary field.\n\n===George Washington Colonials (1961\u20131966)===\nThe other team to move from Griffith to D.C. Stadium was the [[George Washington Colonials football|George Washington University Colonials]] [[college football]] team. The stadium was dedicated during the October 7, 1961 game against VMI, the first college football game there, which GWU won 30-6. The Colonials were forced to play their first three games on the road to allow the stadium to be completed. In the following years, because the Senators had priority, GWU waited until October (when baseball season was over) to schedule games. From 1961 to 1964 they played road games in September, and in 1965 and 1966 they played at high school stadiums in [[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington]] and [[Alexandria, Virginia]].<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"History\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=George Washington U Drops Grid Program|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16522053/|accessdate=14 January 2018|date=20 January 1967}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Colonials, Like Cats, Seek First Win Saturday|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16522071/|accessdate=14 January 2018|work=The Daily Herald|date=27 September 1962}}</ref>\n\nThe Colonials had no real success at D.C. Stadium. GWU was {{winning percentage|22|35|record=y}} during its D.C. Stadium years and never posted a winning record. The Colonials weren't much better at D.C. Stadium where their record was {{winning percentage|11|13|record=y}}, facing off against [[1962 Army Cadets football team|Army]] twice and against a [[1964 Liberty Bowl|Liberty Bowl]]-bound [[1964 West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]] in 1964 (all losses).<ref>{{cite web|title=George Washington Colonials School History|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/george-washington/|website=Sports Reference|accessdate=14 January 2018}}</ref> Perhaps their biggest win was the 1964 upset of [[1964 Villanova Wildcats football team|Villanova]], which came to Washington with a 6\u20131 record. Sophomore quarterback [[Garry Lyle]], the school's last [[1967 NFL/AFL Draft#Round three|NFL draftee]], led the Colonials to a {{nowrap|13\u20136 win.<ref>{{cite news|title=George Washington Upsets Villanova|work=Oakland Tribune|date=15 November 1964}}</ref>}}\n\nThe final George Washington football game to date, and the last at D.C. Stadium, came on [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving Day]], November 24, 1966, when the team lost to {{cfb link|team=Villanova Wildcats|title=Villanova}}, 16\u20137.<ref name=lastgame>Denlinger, Kenneth. \"[http://search.proquest.com/docview/142961877/ Villanova Claws GW In Final, 16-7]\". ''The Washington Post''. November 25, 1966. p. D1.</ref>\n\nAfter the season was over, GW President Dr. [[Lloyd Hartman Elliott|Lloyd H. Elliott]] chose to reevaluate GW's football program.<ref name= decides>Denlinger, Kenneth. \"[http://search.proquest.com/docview/143289963/ GW Decides On Football Path Today]\". ''The Washington Post''. January 19, 1967. p. G1.</ref> On December 19, 1966, head coach [[Jim Camp]], conference coach of the year, resigned citing the uncertainty. The next day, a member of the Board of Trustees announced that the school would drop football.<ref>{{cite news|title=George Washington Will Drop Football|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16521823/|accessdate=14 January 2018|date=21 December 1966}}</ref> On January 19, 1967, the decision became official.<ref name=endfootball>Denlinger, Kenneth. \"[http://search.proquest.com/docview/143245607/ Within Reach GW Will Put Emphasis on Basketball Recruiters Abound Transfer Rules Waived]\". ''The Washington Post''. January 20, 1967. p. E1.</ref> GW decided to use the football program's funding to build a new field house for the basketball team.<ref name= endfootball/> Poor game attendance and the expense, estimated at $254,000 during the 1966 season, contributed to the decision. Former GW player Harry Ledford believed that most people were unwilling to drive on Friday nights to D.C. Stadium, which was perceived as an unsafe area and lacked rail transit. [[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland]] and [[Virginia Cavaliers football|Virginia]] were nationally competitive teams that drew potential suburban spectators away from GW.<ref name=\"gwh\">[http://media.www.gwhatchet.com/media/storage/paper332/news/1999/08/30/Sports/When-We.Played.Football.The.Gw.Boys.Of.Fall.18901966-16420.shtml When we played football: the GW boys of fall, 1890-1966] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727164627/http://media.www.gwhatchet.com/media/storage/paper332/news/1999/08/30/Sports/When-We.Played.Football.The.Gw.Boys.Of.Fall.18901966-16420.shtml |date=2011-07-27 }}, ''[[The GW Hatchet]]'', August 30, 1999.</ref>\n\n===Nationals (2005\u20132007)===\nAfter playing as the [[Montreal Expos]] from [[1969 Montreal Expos season|1969]] to [[2004 Montreal Expos season|2004]], the Expos franchise moved to Washington, D.C., to become the [[Washington Nationals]] for the [[2005 Washington Nationals season|2005 season]]. The Nationals played their first three seasons ([[2005 Washington Nationals season|2005]]\u2013[[2007 Washington Nationals season|2007]]) at RFK, then moved to [[Nationals Park]] in [[2008 Washington Nationals season|2008]]. While the Nationals played at RFK, it was the fourth-oldest active stadium in the [[Major League Baseball|majors]], behind [[Fenway Park]], [[Wrigley Field]] and [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|Yankee Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gwhatchet.com/2007/09/24/ross-romano-nats-move-from-halfway-house-to-home/|last=Romano|first=Ross|title=Nats Move From Halfway House to Home|newspaper=GW Hatchet|date=September 24, 2007|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Nationals\u2032 three seasons there, RFK then became known as a pitchers' park. While [[Frank Howard (baseball)|Frank Howard]] hit at least 44 home runs for three straight seasons at RFK for the [[Washington Senators (1961-1971)|second Washington Senators franchise]] from [[1968 Washington Senators season|1968]] through [[1970 Washington Senators season|1970]], the 2005 Nationals had only one-hitter with more than 15 home runs, [[Jos\u00e9 Guill\u00e9n]] with 24. However, in his lone season with the team in [[2006 Washington Nationals season|2006]], [[Alfonso Soriano]] hit 46 home runs.\n\nDuring their three seasons at RFK, the Nationals failed to make the playoffs or post a winning record. They went 41-40 at home in 2005 and 2006 and 40-41 in 2007 to finish with a {{winning percentage|122|121|record=y}} record at RFK.\n\n=== Howard Bison (1970\u20132016) ===\nNo team has a long history with RFK Stadium than the [[Howard Bison football]] team, who played there 42 times over nearly 46 years (the Detroit Tigers are 2nd by ~8 months, having played their first game there April 9, 1962, and they're last on June 20, 2007). Between their first game in 1970 and last, in 2016, they earned a {{winning percentage|22|17|3|record=y}} record, winning more games at RFK than any other college football program.\n\nLooking to play on a bigger stage than [[William H. Greene Stadium|Howard Stadium]], they began scheduling games at RFK. Howard's first RFK game was a 24\u20137 victory over [[Fisk University|Fisk]] on October 24, 1970.<ref>{{cite news|title=Perfect 1920 Bisons Reunite After 50 Years|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/39194087|accessdate=19 January 2018|date=17 October 1970}}</ref> From 1974 to 1976, Howard played all but one of their home games at RFK and in 1977 they played half their home games there.<ref>{{cite news|title=Washington, D.C.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/39204083/|accessdate=19 January 2018|work=The Pittsburgh Courier|date=10 August 1974}}</ref> After the 1977 season they returned to Howard Stadium, but continued to play their annual homecoming game at RFK through 1985. After the 1985 season, Howard Stadium was refurbished and renamed, and for the next 7 years, Howard played all of their home games there.\n\nIn 1992 they returned to RFK for a game against [[Bowie State University|Bowie State]] that was marked by taunting and a game-ending scuffle.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hente|first1=Karl|title=HOWARD ROUTS BOWIE ST. IN CONTEST CALLED OFF WITH 2:36 LEFT|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1992/11/01/howard-routs-bowie-st-in-contest-called-off-with-236-left/032d78d5-9d04-4fc3-962f-b4256182f754/|accessdate=21 January 2018|date=1 November 1992}}</ref> From 1993 to 1999 Howard played at least one game a year at RFK including the Greater Washington Urban League Classic, at one point called the Hampton-Howard Classic, against Hampton from 1994 to 1999. In 2000 that game moved to Giants Stadium and Howard spent more than a decade away from RFK.\n\nStarting in 2011 and through the 2016 season, Howard played in the Nation's Football Classic at RFK, matching up against [[Morehouse College|Morehouse]] at first and then Hampton again.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wang|first1=Gene|title=Howard and Hampton reprise the battle for the 'real HU'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/colleges/howard-and-hampton-reprise-the-battle-for-the-real-hu/2015/09/17/16a0aec6-5d6c-11e5-8e9e-dce8a2a2a679_story.html|access-date=January 21, 2018|date=September 17, 2005}}</ref> In 2017, Events DC announced that they would discontinue the Classic and thus the last Bison game at RFK Stadium was a 34-7 loss to Hampton on September 16, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hopkins|first1=Tatyana|title=Nation's Football Classic Cancelled|url=http://washingtoninformer.com/nations-football-classic-cancelled/|accessdate=21 January 2018|work=The Washington Informer|date=12 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Wang|first1=Gene|title=Howard football suffers demoralizing loss to Hampton in Nation's Football Classic|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/colleges/howard-football-suffers-demoralizing-loss-to-hampton-in-nations-football-classic/2016/09/17/dc237f00-7d1b-11e6-ac8e-cf8e0dd91dc7_story.html|access-date=January 15, 2018|date=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Freedom (2001\u20132003)===\nFor three seasons, RFK was home to the [[Women's United Soccer Association]] Washington team, the [[Washington Freedom]]. On April 14, 2001, the  Freedom defeated the [[Bay Area CyberRays]] 1-0 in WUSA's inaugural match before 34,198 fans, the largest crowd in WUSA history and the largest crowd to watch a women's professional sports event in DC history (the largest crowd for a women's sporting event was 45,946 for the 1996 women's Olympic soccer tournament, also at RFK). Over three years, the Freedom racked up a 15-9-6 record at RFK and finished as one of the league's top teams. They came in 2nd in 2002 and won the league's Founder's Cup in 2003. They played all of their home games at RFK, except for one in 2001 at Navy-Marine Corps Memorial Stadium in Annapolis to avoid the Washington Grand Prix. Their last game at RFK as part of WUSA was on August 2, 2003, when they defeated the San Jose Cyber Rays. They won the final Founder's Cup in August 2003 and returned to RFK a few days later - minus the players who were playing in the 2003 Women's World Cup - for a victory celebration with the fans, which would be their final WUSA event at RFK. WUSA suspended operation the next month. Their victory in the Founders Cup means that the Freedom won both the first and last games in WUSA history. For a time, their championship banner hung in RFK, but when the Nationals moved in, the banner was moved to the [[Maryland SoccerPlex|Maryland Soccerplex]].\n\nThe Freedom continued, first as an exhibition team called the Washington Freedom Soccer Club, and then as a member of the W-League and the Women's Professional Soccer league in 2006. Their home stadium was the Maryland Soccerplex, but they continued to play a few games at RFK. In 2004, the played an exhibition at Nottingham Forest, which they won 8-0.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sweezy|first1=Christian|title=Nothing Left to Lose|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A50308-2004Jul14.html|accessdate=26 February 2018|date=15 July 2015}}</ref> They returned on June 22, 2008, in a W-League match, which they won 5-0, against the [[Richmond Kickers Destiny]] that was part of a doubleheader with DC United.<ref>{{cite web|title=2008 Washington Freedom W-League Thread|url=http://www.bigsoccer.com/threads/2008-washington-freedom-w-league-thread-r.646674/page-2|accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref> In 2009, the Freedom moved to the WPS and while they continued to play most of their home games in Maryland, they played 3 of 10 home games at RFK in 2009 and one game there in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=D.C. UNITED AND WASHINGTON FREEDOM TO PLAY DOUBLE-HEADER AT RFK STADIUM MAY 1|url=http://www.dcsec.com/pdf/rfk-stadium-hosts-soccer-double-header-may%201.pdf|accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Goff|first1=Stephen|title=Freedom, United Kick Off First of Three Twin Bills at RFK Stadium|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/05/22/AR2009052203348.html|accessdate=26 February 2018|date=23 May 2009}}</ref> In the years after WUSA suspended operations, the Freedom went 5-0-1 at RFK, bringing their combined RFK total to {{winning percentage|20|9|7|record=y}}. After the 2010 season, the Freedom's owners had had enough and sold the team to [[Dan Borislow]], owner of the phone service [[MagicJack]]. He moved them to Boca Raton, Florida for the team's last season. The Freedom's final game at RFK was a 3-1 victory over [[Saint Louis Athletica]] on May 1, 2010.\n\n===Whips (1967\u201368) ===\nIn 1967, D.C. Stadium became the home of its first professional soccer team, the [[Washington Whips]]. They played 23 regular-season games at D.C. Stadium over 16 months, putting together a {{winning percentage|13|5|5|record=y}} home record as well as losing an exhibition against [[Pele|Pele's]] Santos Club for a total RFK record of {{winning percentage|13|6|5|record=y}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Washington Whips Games|url=http://soccerstats.us/teams/washington-whips/games/|accessdate=2 February 2018}}<!--Note that the Boston Beacons game on Aug 25, 1968, is a repeat of the one from the 23rd. There was no match on the 25th --></ref> 20,189 fans attended the Santos exhibition, more than three times as large as a typical Whips match, making it the most heavily attended soccer game in DC history at the time. The game was heavily promoted in the local press and the Whips, who were struggling to attract fans to their regular matches, provided additional incentive through a \u201cMeet Pele\u201d contest.<ref name=\"DartsWhipsDips\"/>\n\nRFK served as the venue for the inaugural match of the [[United Soccer Association]] (USA), a May 26, 1967 match between the Whips and the [[Cleveland Stokers]], won by the Stokers.<ref name=\"DartsWhipsDips\"/>\n\nIn their first season, the Whips were one of the league's top teams and they were staffed by the Aberdeen Football Club of the Scottish Football League or the Aberdeen Dons. They finished 5\u20132\u20135<!-- The Whips played 13 matches, but a 1\u20131 tie with the wolves on June 20 was vacated and the game replayed at the end of the season. The Whips won that game. -->, good enough to win the Eastern Division and play for the USA Championship against the [[Los Angeles Wolves]].\n\nThe owners estimated that they needed to attract 16,000 fans per game, but they never broke 10,000 and averaged only 6,200. Towards the end of the 1967 season, the Whips resorted to organizing British Isles sporting contests such as cricket, hurling, and rugby before games in hopes of luring expatriates.<ref name=\"DartsWhipsDips\"/>\n\nIn 1968, to stay viable, they negotiated a reduction in the lease payment and reduced admission prices by one-third; among other discounts. The USA merged with the [[National Professional Soccer League (1967)|National Professional Soccer League]] to form the new [[North American Soccer League (1968\u201384)|North American Soccer League]]. Despite problems on and off the field, the team found itself in a battle for a playoff spot and towards the end of the season crowds swelled to as much as 14,227 in what proved to be the deciding match for the NASL Atlantic Division title. This September 7, 1968 match against the [[Atlanta Chiefs]] was the last for the Whips at D.C. Stadium. That season, the team went 15-10-7 drawing an average of 6,586 fans. After a tour of Europe, the Whips folded in October 1968.<ref name=\"DartsWhipsDips\"/>\n\n===Federals (1983\u20131984)===\nWashington's only [[USFL]] team, the [[Washington Federals]], played two seasons at RFK and during that time, they had the league's worst record each season, and, in 1984, the lowest per-game attendance. For the opening game, 38,000 fans showed up to see the return of former Redskins coach [[George Allen (American football coach)|George Allen]], the coach of the [[Chicago Blitz]], in a game, the Federals lost, 28\u20137. But attendance quickly dropped off, with as few as 7,303 showing up for a late-season game against the [[Boston Breakers]]. The team went 4-14 in 1983 and 3-15 in 1984, averaging 7,700 fans.\n\nWith six games remaining in the 1984 season, owner Berl Bernhard sold the team to Florida real estate developer Woody Weiser. In the off-season, that deal fell through. Donald Dizney bought the team, moved it to Orlando and renamed it the Renegades.\n\nAfter going {{winning percentage|7|29|record=y}} overall, and {{winning percentage|5|18|record=y}} at RFK, the Federals ended their run with a 20-17 win over the [[New Orleans Breakers]] on June 24, 1984.\n\n===Team America (1983)===\n[[Team America (NASL)|Team America]] was a professional version of the United States men's national soccer team which played like a franchise in the [[North American Soccer League]] (NASL) during the 1983 season. The team played its home games at RFK Stadium and was intended by the NASL and the United States Soccer Federation to build fan support for the league and create a cohesive and internationally competitive national team. However, the team finished in the last place drawing 12,000 fans per game.\n\nTeam America played 19 games at RFK. In those games they went 5-10 in NASL matches and tied three friendlies against [[Watford F.C.]] (from the [[United Kingdom]]), [[FC Dinamo Minsk]] (from the [[Soviet Union]]), and [[Juventus F.C.]] (from [[Italy]]) for a final record of {{winning percentage|5|10|3|record=y}}.\n\nThe team's attendance averaged 19,952 through the first seven home matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com:80/vault/article/magazine/MAG1121147/index.htm|title=Red, White, Black and Blue|publisher=Sports Illustrated|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504211958/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1121147/index.htm|archivedate=May 4, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> including the 50,108 who attended a match vs. Fort Lauderdale that featured a free [[Beach Boys]] concert. Losses led to declining attendance as the season wore on. Attendance averaged 13,002 for the entire 1983 season, having played only a single season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kenn.com/the_blog/?page_id=496|title=Attendance Project: NASL \u2013 kenn.com blog|website=www.kenn.com}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\nThe stadium's design was circular, attempting to facilitate both football and baseball. It was the first to use the so-called \"[[cookie-cutter stadium|cookie-cutter]]\" concept, an approach also used in [[Veterans Stadium|Philadelphia]], [[Shea Stadium|New York]], [[Reliant Astrodome|Houston]], [[Atlanta\u2013Fulton County Stadium|Atlanta]], [[Busch Memorial Stadium|St. Louis]], [[Qualcomm Stadium|San Diego]], [[Riverfront Stadium|Cincinnati]], [[Oakland\u2013Alameda County Coliseum|Oakland]], and [[Three Rivers Stadium|Pittsburgh]]. RFK Stadium ultimately outlasted all of them except Houston, San Diego, and Oakland (the former is still standing but is no longer actively used, while the latter two are still active).\n\nWhile the perimeter of the stadium is circular, the front edge of the upper and lower decks form a \"V\" shape in deference to the baseball configuration.  The rows of seating in the upper and lower decks follow the \"V\" layout, and the discrepancy between the shapes of the inner and outer rings permits more rows of seats to be inserted along the foul lines than at home plate and in the outfield.  As a result, the height of the outside wall rises and falls in waves, and this is echoed in the roof, resulting in a \"butterfly\" appearance when seen at ground level from the west.  This feature is unique among the circular stadiums of the 1960s.\n\nIn 1961, the stadium represented a new level of luxury. It offered 50,000 seats, each {{convert|22|in|cm}} wide (at a time when the typical seat was only {{convert|15|\u2013|16|in|cm|abbr=on}}), air-conditioned locker rooms and a lounge for player's wives. It had a machine-operated tarpaulin to cover the field, yard-wide aisles, and ramps that made it possible to empty the stadium in just 15 minutes. The ticket office was connected to the ticket windows by pneumatic tubes. The press boxes could be enclosed and expanded for big events. The stadium had a holding cell for drunks and brawlers. It had 12,000 parking spaces and was served by 300 buses. It had lighting that was twice as bright as Griffith Stadium.<ref name=\"Jail\"/>\n\nIt was not ideal for either sport, due to the different geometries of the playing fields. As the playing field dimensions for football and baseball vary greatly, seating had to accommodate the larger playing surface. This would prove to be the case at nearly every multi-purpose/cookie-cutter stadium.\n\nAs a baseball park, RFK was a target of scorn from baseball purists, largely because it was one of the few stadiums with no lower-deck seats in the outfield. The only outfield seats were in the upper deck, above a high wall. According to ''[[The Sporting News|Sporting News]]'' publications in the 1960s, over 27,000 seats\u2014roughly 60% of the listed capacity of 45,000 for baseball\u2014were in the upper tier or mezzanine levels. The lower-to-upper proportion improved for the Redskins with end-zone seats. The first ten rows of the football configuration were nearly at the field level, making it difficult to see over the players. The baseball diamond was aligned due east (home plate to center field), and the football field ran along the first baseline (northwest to southeast).\n\n{{wide image|DC United.jpg|800px<!--|align-cap=center-->|Panoramic view <!--of Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium--> in 2012, from the west corner (home plate to center field, due east)}}\n\nA [[Movable seating|complex conversion]] was necessary, at a cost of $40,000 each time, to change the stadium from a football configuration to baseball and back again; in its final form, this included rolling the third-base lower-level seats into the outfield along a buried rail, dropping the hydraulic pitcher's mound {{convert|3|ft|1}} into the ground, and laying sod over the infield dirt. Later facilities were designed so the seating configuration could be changed more quickly and at a lower cost. The conversion was required several times per year during the Senators' joint tenancy with the Redskins (1962\u201371) but became much more frequent during the Nationals/D.C. United era; in 2005, the conversion was made over twenty times.\n\nOriginally the seats located behind the stadium's third-base dugout were removed for baseball games and put back in place when the stadium was converted to the football (and later soccer) configuration. When these sections were in place, RFK seated approximately 56,000. With the Nationals' arrival in 2005, this particular segment of the stands was permanently removed to facilitate the switch between the baseball and soccer configurations. These seats were not restored following the Nationals' move to Nationals Park, leaving the stadium's [[seating capacity]] at approximately 46,000. The majority of the upper-deck seats normally were not made available for D.C. United matches, so the stadium's reduced capacity normally was not problematic for the club.\n\n<!--The football/soccer field alignment is northwest to southeast, approximately along the baseball diamond's first base line.-->\nDuring the years when the stadium was without baseball (1972\u20132004)<!--used only for Redskins games (1972\u201396)-->, the rotating seats remained in the football configuration. If an exhibition baseball game was scheduled, the left-field wall was only {{convert|250|ft|0}} from home plate, and a large screen was erected in left field for some games.\n\n[[File:Capitol from top of Washington Monument.JPG|250px|thumb|View east from [[Washington Monument]],<br>RFK Stadium in background]]\nSome of RFK's quirks endear the venue to fans and players.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} The large rolling bleacher section is less stable than other seating, allowing fans to jump in rhythm to cause the whole area to bounce. Also, despite its small size (it never seated more than 58,000), because of the stadium's design and the proximity of the fans to the field when configured for football, the stadium was extremely loud when the usual sell-out Redskins crowds became vocal. Legend has it that Redskins head coach [[George Allen (American football coach)|George Allen]] would order a large rolling door in the side of the stadium to be opened when visiting teams were attempting field goals at critical moments in games so that a swirling wind from off the Potomac and Anacostia rivers might interfere with the flight of the kicked ball.\n\nSince the stadium is on a direct sightline with the [[Washington Monument]] and the [[United States Capitol|U.S. Capitol]], light towers were not allowed; instead, [[Arc lamp|arc lights]] were placed on its curved, dipping roof.\n\nEvents D.C.\u2014the city agency which operates RFK Stadium\u2014began a strategic planning process in November 2013 to study options for the future of the stadium, its {{convert|80|acre|ha}} campus and the nonmilitary portions of the adjacent [[D.C. Armory]]. Events D.C. said one option to be studied was demolition within a decade, while another would be the status quo. The strategic planning process also included the design and development of options. The agency said that RFK Stadium has generated $4 million to $5 million a year in revenues since 1997, which did not cover operating expenses.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/blog/top-shelf/2013/11/events-dc-looks-at-next-steps-for-rfk.html|last=Cooper|first=Rebecca|title=Events D.C. Looks at Next Steps for RFK|newspaper=Washington Business Journal|date=November 27, 2013|access-date=August 25, 2014}}</ref> In August 2014, Events D.C. chose the consulting firm of Brailsford & Dunlavey to create the master plan.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/breaking_ground/2014/08/events-d-c-awards-contract-for-rfk-memorial.html|last=Sernovitz|first=Daniel J.|title=Events D.C. to Award Contract for RFK Memorial Stadium Master Plan|newspaper=Washington Business Journal|date=August 18, 2014|access-date=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Seating capacity===\n[[File:RFK Stadium Washington DC August 4 2017.jpg|250px|thumb|right|South exterior<!--of RFK Stadium--> in August 2017]]\n\n{{col-begin}}{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Baseball\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{Baseball primary style|Washington Nationals}};\"|Years\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{Baseball primary style|Washington Nationals}};\"|Capacity\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Washington Nationals}};\"|1962\u20131970\n| 43,500<ref name=\"ballparks\">[http://www.ballparks.com/baseball/american/rfksta.htm RFK Stadium]. Ballparks.com. Retrieved on December 24, 2011.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Washington Nationals}};\"|1971\u20132004\n| 45,016<ref name=\"ballparks\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{Baseball secondary style|Washington Nationals}};\"|2005\u20132007\n| 45,596<ref name=\"ballparks\"/>\n|}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Football \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|Years\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|Capacity\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|1961\u20131964\n| 49,219<ref>{{cite news |title=Jurgensen Hurls 4 Scoring Passes; Mitchell, Carpenter, Taylor and Cola Elude WeakenedDefensive Secondary|first=William N.|last=Wallace|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/30/archives/jurgensen-hurls-4-scoring-passes-mitchell-carpenter-taylor-and-coia.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 30, 1964|access-date=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|1965\u20131969\n| 50,000<ref>{{cite news |title=Draft Choices to Play in U.S. Bowl|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=I7xeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9jAMAAAAIBAJ&pg=5089,817455&dq=en|newspaper=[[The Idaho Press-Tribune|Lewiston Morning Tribune]]|date=January 6, 1962|access-date=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|1970\n| 50,415<ref>{{cite news |title=Larry Brown Gains 1,000-Yard Club|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5dJNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XooDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3587,2288263&dq=en|newspaper=[[The Free Lance\u2013Star]]|location=Fredericksburg, Virginia|date=December 14, 1970|access-date=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|1971\n| 53,041<ref>{{cite news |title=Redskins Smash Giants|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=XHkyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HLcFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2793,3956307&dq=en|newspaper=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|date=December 6, 1971|access-date=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|1972\n| 53,039<ref>{{cite news |title=Packer Rookie Picked Clean|first=Jerry|last=Izenberg|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/1946162442.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+28%2C+1972&author=&pub=Boston+Globe+(1960-1979)&desc=Packer+rookie+picked+clean&pqatl=google|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=November 28, 1972|access-date=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|1973\n| 54,381<ref>{{cite web |title=1973 Washington Redskins Schedule|url=http://www.nfl.com/teams/schedule?team=WAS&season=1973&seasonType=REG|publisher=National Football League|access-date=November 28, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|1974\n| 54,395<ref>{{cite news |title=Grambling Is Seeking Bid to Bowl|first=Al|last=Harving|url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0E17F73D5F14738DDDAF0894D9415B858BF1D3|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 6, 1975|accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|1975\u20131976\n| 55,004<ref>{{cite news |title=Sunday Scouting Report|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/679425572.html?dids=679425572:679425572&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Sep+19%2C+1975&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=SUNDAY+SCOUTING+REPORT&pqatl=google|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=September 19, 1975|accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|1977\u20131979\n| 55,031<ref>{{cite news |title=Cowboys Win, 14\u20137, on Dorsett's TD|first=Leonard|last=Shapiro|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/redskins/longterm/1997/history/allart/dw1977b.htm|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=November 28, 1977|accessdate=November 27, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|1980\u20131983\n| 55,045<ref>{{cite news |title=Redskins Nip Eagles to Stay Undefeated|first=Cameron C.|last=Snyder|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/baltsun/access/1787491722.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+29%2C+1982&author=&pub=The+Sun+(1837-1985)&desc=Redskins+nip+Eagles+to+stay+undefeated&pqatl=google|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|date=November 29, 1982|accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|1984\n| 55,431<ref>{{cite news |title=Redskins Run Over Cowboys as Riggins hits 10,000 Yards|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=c9lRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TW4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=7007,3751818&dq=en|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date=October 15, 1984|accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|1985\u20131991\n| 55,750<ref>{{cite news |title=Redskins Reload; Champs Have Firepower to Win Again; Prospects of Repeating Downplayed|first=Gary|last=Mihoces|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/55861912.html?dids=55861912:55861912&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug+30%2C+1988&author=Gary+Mihoces&pub=USA+TODAY+(pre-1997+Fulltext)&desc=Redskins+reload%3BChamps+have+firepower+to+win+again%3BProspects+of+repeating+downplayed&pqatl=google|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=August 30, 1988|accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"{{NFLAltPrimaryStyle|Washington Redskins}};\"|1992\u20132004\n| 56,454<ref>{{cite news |title=Pro Football, NFC: Young and Rice Re-Ignite 49er Fireworks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/29/sports/pro-football-nfc-young-and-rice-re-ignite-49er-fireworks.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 29, 1993|accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n|}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Soccer\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#000; color:#fff;\"|Years\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#000; color:#fff;\"|Capacity\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"background:#eb0027; color:#fff;\"|2005\u20132017\n| 46,000<ref>{{cite news |title=USA vs. Germany friendly at RFK Stadium|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/soccer-insider/wp/2013/06/02/usa-vs-germany-friendly-at-rfk-stadium/|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=June 2, 2013|accessdate=June 2, 2013}}</ref>\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Dimensions===\n[[File: RFK Stadium satellite view.png|300px|thumb|right|Satellite view of the stadium in pre-2005 soccer configuration; the darker red seats at the northwest end are not part of the current setup]]\nThe dimensions of the baseball field were {{convert|335|ft}} down the foul lines, {{convert|380|ft|0}} to the power alleys and {{convert|408|ft}} to center field during the Senators' time. The official distances when the Nationals arrived were identical, except for two additional feet to center field. After complaints from Nationals hitters it was discovered in July 2005 that the fence had actually been put in place incorrectly, and it was {{convert|394.74|ft|1}} to the power alleys in left; {{convert|395|ft}} to the right-field power alley; and {{convert|407.83|ft|1}} to center field. The section of wall containing the {{convert|380|ft|0|adj=on}} sign was moved closer to the foul lines to more accurately represent the distance shown on the signs but no changes were made to the actual dimensions.\n\nThe approximate [[elevation]] of the playing field is {{convert|10|ft}} above [[sea level]].\n\n==Sports events==\n\n===Baseball===\n[[File:RFK Stadium baseball.JPG|thumb|300px|right|A [[Washington Nationals]] game at RFK, June 2005]]\n\nTwo major league teams called RFK home, the Senators (1962\u201371) and the Nationals (2005\u201307). In between, the stadium hosted an assortment of exhibition games, old-timer games, and at least one college baseball exhibition game. In addition, from 1988 to 1991 the RFK auxiliary field served as the home stadium of the George Washington Colonials college baseball team, and hosted some Howard University and Interhigh League and D.C. Interscholastic Athletic Association championship baseball games.\n\n* April 9, 1962: The [[1962 Washington Senators season|Washington Senators]] defeated the [[1962 Detroit Tigers season|Detroit Tigers]] 4-1 in the first baseball game played at D.C. Stadium. President [[John F. Kennedy]] \u2013 the brother of the stadium's future namesake, then-[[United States Attorney General]] Robert F. Kennedy \u2013 threw out the [[ceremonial first pitch]].\n* July 10, 1962: With 45,480 in attendance, D.C. Stadium hosted its first [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]], the [[1962 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|first of two]] during the {{mlby|1962}} season. President Kennedy threw out the first pitch and the [[National League]] won 3\u20131.\n* June 12, 1967: The [[1967 Washington Senators season|Senators]] defeated the [[1967 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]] 6\u20135 in the longest night game to date in major league history.<ref name=onon22>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=C1dYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tvcDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5288%2C3447990 |work=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=(Washington) |agency=Associated Press |title=Teams battle on and on - then Solons win in 22nd |date=June 13, 1967 |page=15}}</ref> The 22-inning game lasted 6 hours and 38 minutes and ended at 2:43&nbsp;a.m. EDT.<ref name=senoutsox>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=t6lVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=JeEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5615%2C2748913 |work=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon) |agency=Associated Press |title=Senators outlast Sox in 22 innings|date=June 13, 1967 |page=3B}}</ref>\n* April 7, 1969: With President [[Richard Nixon]] and about 45,000 on hand on Monday afternoon, rookie manager [[Ted Williams]] made his debut with the [[1969 Washington Senators season|Senators]], an 8\u20134 loss to the [[1969 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]].<ref name=tedspoir>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=obEwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wYoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=642%2C2627691|work=Free Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |agency=Associated Press |last=Polk |first=James R. |title=Ted sees spoiler role for Nats |date=April 7, 1969 |page=15}}</ref><ref name=optff>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=orEwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wYoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=739%2C2568057 |work=Free Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |agency=Associated Press |last=Nissenson |first=Herschel |title=New managers find openers little tough|date=April 8, 1969 |page=6}}</ref><ref name=\"apthisdateinbaseball20120329\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/wire/_/section/mlb/id/7750299 |title=This Date In Baseball|first=Paul|last=Montella |date=March 29, 2012|website=ESPN.com|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n* June 7, 1969: The stadium was renamed for Robert Kennedy on January 18; while the Senators were away at [[1969 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota]], the rededication ceremony {{nowrap|was held.<ref name=wtophigin/><ref name=rddecer/>}}\n* July 23, 1969: The stadium hosted its [[1969 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|second and last All-Star Game]], a National League 9\u20133 victory before 45,259. Postponed by a rainout the night before, the game was on Wednesday {{nowrap|afternoon,<ref name=asgrout>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7N8RAAAAIBAJ&sjid=X-sDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7234%2C2725766 |work=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington) |agency=Associated Press |title=All-Star Game rained out; rescheduled this morning |date=July 23, 1969 |page=16}}</ref><ref name=jaxmost>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=icpNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K4oDAAAAIBAJ&pg=649%2C2661503 |work=Free-Lance Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |agency=Associated Press |last=Rathet |first=Mike |title=Jackson says N.L. has more stars |date=July 24, 1969 |page=8}}</ref>}} the final MLB All-Star Game to conclude during daylight. President Nixon was scheduled to throw out the first pitch the evening before;<ref name=ioffl>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=iMpNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K4oDAAAAIBAJ&pg=795%2C2456683 |work=Free-Lance Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |agency=Associated Press |last=Grimsley |first=Will |title=It's official: Nixon No. 1 fan |date=July 23, 1969 |page=8}}</ref> because of the postponement, he missed the game to personally greet the returning [[Apollo 11]] crew aboard the [[USS Hornet (CV-12)|USS ''Hornet'']].<ref name=nhdsmcr>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7N8RAAAAIBAJ&sjid=X-sDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6681%2C3013528 |work=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington) |agency=Associated Press |title=Nixon heads for recovery of moon craft |date=July 24, 1969 |page=1 }}</ref> [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Spiro Agnew]] threw out the first pitch.<ref name=bawhrl>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=JXRQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NREEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7250%2C4916471 |work=Milwaukee Sentinel |last=Chapman |first=Lou |title=Bombs away! NL stars shell AL hurlers, 9-3 |date=July 24, 1969 |page=1, part 2 }}</ref>\n* September 30, 1971: In the [[1971 Washington Senators season|Senators']] final game (on a Thursday night), they led the [[1971 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] 7\u20135 with two outs in the top of the ninth. After an obese teenager ran onto the field, picked up first base, and ran off, fans stormed the field and tore up bases, grass patches, and anything else for souvenirs. Washington [[Forfeit (baseball)|forfeited]] the game, {{nowrap|9\u20130,<ref name=ffotsen/><ref name=Lowry>{{cite book |title=Green Cathedrals |last=Lowry|first=Philip|year=2006|publisher=Walker & Company|isbn=978-0-8027-1608-8|page=239|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=Afo5vtVTz4wC|page=1}}}}</ref>}} the first forfeit in the majors in seventeen years.<ref name=ffotsen/> It was the last MLB home game at RFK until [[2005 Washington Nationals season|2005]].\n* July 19, 1982: At the first [[Old-Timers' Day|Cracker Jack Old Timers Baseball Classic]] exhibition game, attended by nearly thirty thousand, 75-year-old [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Famer]] [[Luke Appling]] hit a home run against the National League's {{nowrap|[[Warren Spahn]].<ref name=ageflair>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=s2NRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_4oDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3632%2C2473317 |work=Free Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |agency=Associated Press |last=Nelson |first=John |title=Age hasn't diminished flair for drama |date=July 20, 1982 |page=6}}</ref><ref name=ergwpot82>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EPNVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=R-IDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6106%2C4694888 |work=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon) |agency=(Washington Post)|last=Boswell |first=Thomas |title=The best time for oldtimers |date=July 20, 1982 |page=E1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Old timers game to be played again |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1320&dat=19821201&id=MrURAAAAIBAJ&sjid=q-kDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3360,167621|newspaper=[[Gainesville Sun]]|location=(Florida) |agency=Associated Press|date=December 1, 1982<!--|accessdate=January 6, 2014-->|page=5D}}</ref><ref name=otmsake>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=V0xSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XnsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2613%2C3881996 |work=St. Petersburg Times |location=(Florida) |agency=AP photos|title=They played just for old times' sake |date=July 20, 1982 |page=1C}}</ref>}} Although he had a .310 lifetime batting average, Appling only hit 45 home runs in 20 seasons. However, because the stadium had not been fully reconfigured, it was just {{convert|260|ft|0}} to the left-field foul pole, far shorter than normal, and Spahn applauded him as he rounded the bases. Five more Cracker Jack All Star games were hosted at RFK,<ref name=rcj84sn>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dxgiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BaYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2766%2C1093459 |work=Reading Eagle |location=(Pennsylvania) |agency=(Baltimore Sun) |last=Baker |first=Kent |title=This old-timers game is a real crackerjack |date=July 1, 1984 |page=101}}</ref> until summer construction at RFK in 1988 moved it north to [[Sahlen Field|Buffalo]].<ref name=otgmtb>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1987/12/03/old-timers-game-moves-to-buffalo/4644b1cf-3a3c-420b-b101-943b10f3f64e/ |work=Washington Post |title=Old-timers game moves to Buffalo |date=December 3, 1987 |accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref><ref name=gnfbpst>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-05-29/sports/sp-5410_1_baseball-memories |work=Los Angeles Times |agency=Associated Press |title=Glory names from baseball's past will play in Buffalo on June 20 |date=May 29, 1988 |accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref> During that time, Hall of Famers and stars such as [[Joe Dimaggio]], [[Bob Feller]], [[Stan Musial]], [[Hank Aaron]], [[Willie Mays]], [[Sandy Koufax]], [[Roger Maris]], [[Whitey Ford]], and Washington favorite [[Frank Howard (baseball)|Frank Howard]] would take the field. There was even a conversation about allowing then-Vice President [[George H.W. Bush]], who'd captained Yale's College World Series team, to play one year.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Appel|first1=Marty|title=CRACKER JACK OLD TIMERS GAMES|url=https://www.thenationalpastimemuseum.com/article/cracker-jack-old-timers-games|website=The National Past Time Museum|access-date=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n* April 5, 1987: RFK Stadium hosted an exhibition game between the [[1987 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]] and the [[1987 New York Mets season|New York Mets]], the first MLB game played in Washington, D.C., since a pair of exhibition games in {{mlby|1972}}. The game was a sell-out, with 45,614 tickets sold, and a crowd of 38,437 actually attended on a cold, rainy afternoon. Mets pitcher [[Sid Fernandez]] threw a one-hitter, and the Mets won, 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ghostsofdc.org/2012/05/08/phillies-mets-rfk-stadium-1987/|title=Baseball is Back at RFK Stadium in 1987 - Ghosts of DC|date=May 8, 2012|website=GhostsOfDC.org|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1987/02/24/washingtons-baseball-morsel/d86e4801-38cf-4977-acb7-7a56e9c262de/|title=WASHINGTON'S BASEBALL MORSEL|first=THOMAS|last=BOSWELL|date=February 24, 1987|publisher=|access-date=February 1, 2018|via=www.WashingtonPost.com}}</ref>\n* April 3, 1988: The [[1988 New York Mets season|Mets]] and [[1988 Baltimore Orioles season|Orioles]] met at RFK for an exhibition game watched by 36,123 as the Mets won 10-7 off a three-run homer by [[Darryl Strawberry]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Justice |first1=Richard |title=36,123 See Orioles Lose at RFK to Mets |work=The Washington Post |date=4 April 1989}}</ref>\n* April 2, 1989: The [[1989 St. Louis Cardinals season|Cardinals]] and [[1989 Baltimore Orioles season|Orioles]] met at RFK for an exhibition game watched by 37,204 as the Orioles won 7-6 in the 10th inning.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gildea |first1=William |title=Baseball a Memory--Again |work=The Washington Post |date=3 April 1989}}</ref>\n* May 6, 1989: George Washington University defeated the Soviet national baseball team 20\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gazuza Hurls Win Against Soviet Nine|work=The Journal News - White Plains New York|date=May 7, 1989}}</ref>\n* April 7, 1990: The [[1990 St. Louis Cardinals season|Cardinals]] and [[1990 Baltimore Orioles season|Orioles]] met at RFK for an exhibition game watched by 21,298 as the Orioles won 11-10.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goff |first1=Stephen |title=Chilly RFK Exhibition Stokes Fire for Expansion |work=The Washington Post |date=8 April 1990}}</ref>  \n* April 6-7, 1991: The [[1991 Boston Red Sox season|Red Sox]] and [[1991 Baltimore Orioles season|Orioles]] played a pair of exhibition games at RFK. The first was watched by 37,458 as the Orioles won 4-1. The Stadium was in its baseball configuration for the first time since September 30, 1971.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Justice |first1=Richard |title=Lining Up for Baseball |work=The Washington Post |date=7 April 1991}}</ref> 43,624 watched the Orioles lose the 2nd game 6-5, and [[Dan Quayle]] threw out the first pitch.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Maske |first1=Mark |title=Orioles Downed at RFK, Head for Home, Opener |work=The Washington Post |date=8 April 1991}}</ref>\n* April 4-5, 1992: The [[1992 Boston Red Sox season|Red Sox]] and [[1992 Baltimore Orioles season|Orioles]] met at RFK for an exhibition game watched by 20,551 as the Sox won 4-3. The next day the Red Sox played the [[1992 Philadelphia Phillies season|Phllies]] at RFK in a game watched by 16,823.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fachet |first1=Robert |title=In Washington for Just a Day, Orioles Fall at RFK |work=The Washington Post |date=5 April 1992}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gildea |first1=William |title=The Faithful Come to RFK, Knowing This Is All There Is |work=The Washington Post |date=6 April 1992}}</ref>\n* April 3, 1998: The [[1998 Baltimore Orioles season|Orioles]] and [[1998 New York Mets season|Mets]] met for an exhibition game.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Justice|first1=Richard|title=ORIOLES ON SEASON'S DOORSTEP AT RFK|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1988/04/03/orioles-on-seasons-doorstep-at-rfk/5c7b991a-fa82-49b5-a28b-6fbe2aeffad0/|access-date=December 28, 2017|date=April 3, 1998}}</ref>\n* April 2 and 4, 1999: [[1999 Montreal Expos season|Montreal Expos]] and [[1999 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis Cardinals]] met in a pair of exhibition games. The stadium was restored to its full baseball configuration for the first time since the 1991 exhibition. Rumors already swirled then that the Expos could soon call RFK home, a possibility which came to pass after the 2004 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=RFK Set For Expos, Cardinals|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1999/03/28/rfk-set-for-expos-cardinals/4299ee35-2a53-47f9-801b-125f1695f8ee/|accessdate=28 December 2017|date=28 March 1999}}</ref>\n* April 3, 2005: The [[2005 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]] (formerly the [[2004 Montreal Expos season|Montreal Expos]]) lost to the [[2005 New York Mets season|Mets]] 4\u20133 in an exhibition game before a paid crowd of 25,453 in their first game in Washington. It was the first MLB home game at RFK since 1971. Mayor [[Anthony Williams]] threw out the first pitch.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nakamura |first1=David |last2=Farenthold |first2=David A. |title=In Nationals' D.C. Debut, Fans Shrug Off Snags |work=Washington Post |date=4 April 2005}}</ref>\n* April 14, 2005: The [[2005 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]] defeated the [[2005 Arizona Diamondbacks season|Arizona Diamondbacks]] 5\u20133 before a crowd of 45,596 in their first regular season game in {{nowrap|Washington.<ref name=lwwfdc>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=b2BWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ePADAAAAIBAJ&pg=2646%2C3538047|work=Eugene Register-Guard |location=(Oregon) |agency=Associated Press |title=Long wait worth it for D.C. faithful |last=Fendrich |first=Howard |date=April 15, 2005 |page=C1}}</ref><ref name=nenjvw>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wjEzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hwgGAAAAIBAJ&pg=1854%2C4706613 |work=Free Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |last=Jacobson |first=Todd |title=Nationals enjoying the view from the top |date=April 15, 2005 |page=C1}}</ref>}} President [[George W. Bush]] threw out the first pitch,<ref name=lwwfdc/><ref name=thfrnyrs>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wTEzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hwgGAAAAIBAJ&pg=2528%2C4066852 |work=Free Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |last=Warters |first=Nathan |title=34 years, nine games later |date=April 14, 2005 |page=B1}}</ref> and Washington swept the three-game series<!--Thu, Sat, Sun--> to improve {{nowrap|to 8\u20134.<ref name=bromsbrk>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=xDEzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hwgGAAAAIBAJ&pg=6095%2C5480510 |work=Free Lance-Star |location=(Fredericksburg, Virginia) |last=Jacobson |first=Todd |title=Nationals break out brooms |date=April 18, 2005 |page=C1}}</ref>}}\n* June 18, 2006: [[2006 Washington Nationals season|Nationals]] third baseman [[Ryan Zimmerman]], who became known as \"Mr. Walk-Off\" for his penchant for hitting game-ending home runs, hit his first walk-off home run off [[2006 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] pitcher [[Chien-Ming Wang]] in the bottom of the ninth inning for a 3\u20132 Nats victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/cutfour/2017/10/22/259346516/top-baseball-moments-at-rfk-stadium|title=Looking back at five great baseball moments at RFK Stadium |first=Andrew |last=Mearns |date=October 22, 2017|website=Major League Baseball|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n* September 16, 2006: The [[2006 Washington Nationals season|Nationals]]' [[Alfonso Soriano]] stole second base in the first inning against the [[2006 Milwaukee Brewers season|Milwaukee Brewers]] and became the fourth player to hit 40 home runs and steal 40 bases in a season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Soriano Joins Elite Group|first=Bill|last=Ladson|url=http://washington.nationals.mlb.com/news/wrap.jsp?ymd=20060916&content_id=1666470&vkey=wrapup2005&fext=.jsp&team=home|publisher=[[Major League Baseball Advanced Media]]|date=September 16, 2006|accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n* September 23, 2007: The [[2007 Washington Nationals season|Nationals]] defeated the [[2007 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]] {{nowrap|5\u20133}} before 40,519 in the final major league game played at RFK Stadium.<ref name=pfnrelilo>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BVVVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_j4NAAAAIBAJ&pg=4935%2C129451 |work=Reading Eagle |location=(Pennsylvania) |title=Phils find no relief in loss |date=September 24, 2007 |page=D1}}</ref> The win gave the Nationals an overall home record of {{winning percentage|122|121|record=y}} in three seasons at the stadium.\n\n===Football===\n\nRFK was the home of two professional football teams, two college football teams, a bowl game and more than one college all-star game. It hosted neutral-site college football games, various [[Historically black colleges and universities|HBCU]] games, and high school championship games.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gildea|first1=William|title=A Day for Feasting on Football|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1986/11/27/a-day-for-feasting-on-football/5919a293-00bd-4fff-8a79-a0034d22d20f/|accessdate=20 February 2018|work=The Washington Post|date=27 November 1986}}</ref>\n\n====Professional football====\n* November 27, 1966: The [[1966 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] beat the [[1966 New York Giants season|New York Giants]] 72\u201341. The 113 combined points are the most ever scored in an NFL game.\n* December 14, 1969: The Redskins defeat the New Orleans Saints 17-14 in what would be [[Vince Lombardi|Vince Lombardi's]] last victory. The Redskins would lose the next week at Dallas, and Lombardi would die just before the start of the 1970 season. \n* November 20, 1972: RFK Stadium hosts its first ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' game. The [[1972 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] defeat the [[1972 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] 24-13.\n* December 31, 1972, the [[1972 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]] defeat the [[1972 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]] 26\u20133 in the [[NFC Championship Game]] to earn a trip to [[Super Bowl VII]].\n* October 8, 1973: In a ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' game, [[1973 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]] safety [[Ken Houston]] stops Cowboys' running back [[Walt Garrison]] at the goal line as time expired to secure a win.\n* December 17, 1977: The [[1977 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]] defeat the [[1977 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]] 17\u201314 in what would be head coach [[George Allen (American football coach)|George Allen]]'s final game with the team.\n* October 25, 1981: The [[1981 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]] narrowly beat the [[1981 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] 24\u201322 to earn head coach [[Joe Gibbs]] his first win at RFK Stadium.\n* October 17, 1982: First NFLPA's all-star games during the 1982 NFL strike<ref>{{cite news|title=The scheduled 19-game round robin series involving NFL All-Stars|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1982/10/13/The-scheduled-19-game-round-robin-series-involving-NFL-All/7166403329600/|accessdate=28 December 2017|date=13 October 1982}}</ref>\n* January 22, 1983: The stadium physically shakes as a capacity crowd of 54,000 chants \"We Want Dallas\" taunting the hated Cowboys in the NFC Championship Game. The [[1982 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]] go on to defeat the [[1982 Dallas Cowboys season|Cowboys]] 31\u201317 to earn a trip to [[Super Bowl XVII]] where they beat the [[1982 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]] 27\u201317 to claim the franchise's first Super Bowl win.\n* March 6, 1983: The [[Washington Federals]] of the [[United States Football League]] play their first game, losing to the [[Chicago Blitz]] 28-7 before 38,007 fans at RFK stadium in the USFL's first nationally televised game.<ref name=fun8384Federals>{{cite web|url=http://www.funwhileitlasted.net/2014/01/16/1983-1984-washington-federals/|title=Washington Federals, United States Football League|date=January 16, 2014|website=FunWhileItLasted.net|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref> The Federals never draw more than 15,000 fans again.<ref name=fun8384Federals/>\n* September 5, 1983: [[1983 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]]' rookie cornerback [[Darrell Green]] chases down [[1983 Dallas Cowboys season|Cowboys]]' running back [[Tony Dorsett]] from behind to prevent him from scoring. However, the Redskins ended up losing late in the fourth quarter.\n* May 6, 1984: The [[Washington Federals]] play their final game, losing in overtime to the [[Memphis Showboats]] at RFK Stadium before 4,432 fans, the smallest crowd in USFL history.<ref name=fun8384Federals/>\n* November 18, 1985: [[1985 New York Giants season|Giants]]' linebacker [[Lawrence Taylor]] sacks [[1985 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]]' quarterback [[Joe Theismann]], severely breaking his leg and ending his NFL career. Backup quarterback [[Jay Schroeder]] comes in and leads the Redskins to a 23\u201321 victory on ''Monday Night Football''.\n* January 17, 1988: Cornerback [[Darrell Green]] knocks down a [[Wade Wilson (American football)|Wade Wilson]] pass at the goal line to clinch a victory over the [[1987 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]] in the NFC Championship game. The [[1987 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]] go on to defeat the [[1987 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] 42\u201310 in [[Super Bowl XXII]].\n* January 4, 1992: In a pouring rain, the [[1991 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]] beat the [[1991 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] 24\u20137 in the Divisional round of the playoffs. After a touchdown scored by Redskins fullback [[Gerald Riggs]] with 6:32 remaining in the fourth quarter, the fans shower the field with the free yellow seat cushions given to them when they entered the stadium.\n* January 12, 1992: The Redskins beat the [[1991 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]] 41\u201310 in the NFC Championship Game earning a trip to [[Super Bowl XXVI]] where they beat the [[1991 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]] 37\u201324. This was the last time the RFK held a post-season game.\n* December 13, 1992: Redskins' head coach [[Joe Gibbs]] coaches what would be his last win at RFK Stadium. The [[1992 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]] defeat the [[1992 Dallas Cowboys season|Cowboys]] 20\u201317.\n* September 6, 1993: RFK Stadium hosts its last ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' game as the [[1993 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]] open their season by defeating the [[1993 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]] 35-16.\n* December 22, 1996: The [[1996 Washington Redskins season|Redskins]] won their last game in the stadium, defeating their arch-rivals, the [[1996 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]], 37\u201310. A capacity crowd of 56,454 fans watched the game, tying the football record set against the Detroit Lions in 1995. It was the last professional football game played at RFK. In a halftime ceremony, several past Redskins greats were introduced, wearing replicas of the jerseys of their time. After the game, fans storm the field and rip up chunks of grass as souvenirs. In the parking lot, fans are seen walking away with the stadium's burgundy and gold seats.\n\n=====Records=====\n* Most passing yards and passing TDs at RFK, Career - [[Sonny Jurgenson]], 12,985 yards, 108 TDs\n* Most rushing yards and rushing TDs at RFK, Career - [[John Riggins]], 3448 yards, 32 TDs\n* Most receiving yards at RFK, Career - [[Art Monk]], 6329 yards\n* Most receiving TDs at RFK, Career - [[Charley Taylor]], 42 TDs\n* Most passing yards, Game - [[Boomer Esiason]], 522 yards, 11/10/1996\n* Most passing TDs, Game - [[Mark Rypien]], 6 TDs, 11/10/1991\n* Highest quarterback rating, Game - [[Dan Marino]], 150.4, 09/02/1994\n* Most rushing yards, Game - [[Gerald Riggs]], 3448 yards, 32 TDs\n* Most rushing TDs, Game - tie [[Earnest Byner]], [[Dick James]], [[Terry Allen (running back)|Terry Allen]], [[Joe Morris (American football)|Joe Morris]], [[John Riggins]], [[Duane Thomas]]; 3\n* Most receiving yards, game - [[Anthony Allen (wide receiver)|Anthony Allen]], 255 yards, 10/04/1987\n* Most receiving TDs, game - tie [[Anthony Allen (wide receiver)|Anthony Allen]], [[Gary Clark]], [[Michael Irvin]], [[Keith Jackson]], [[Del Shofner]]; 3\n\n====Bowl games====\n\n* December 20, 2008: [[2008 Wake Forest Demon Deacons football team|Wake Forest]] defeats [[2008 Navy Midshipmen football team|Navy]] 29\u201319 in the [[2008 EagleBank Bowl|inaugural EagleBank Bowl]] before a crowd of 28,777 in the first [[bowl game]] to be played in Washington, D.C.\n* December 29, 2009: [[2009 UCLA Bruins football team|UCLA]] defeats [[2009 Temple Owls football team|Temple]] 30\u201321 before a crowd of 23,072 in the second annual [[2009 EagleBank Bowl|EagleBank Bowl]].\n* December 29, 2010: [[2010 Maryland Terrapins football team|Maryland]] defeats [[2010 East Carolina Pirates football team|East Carolina]] 51\u201320 before a crowd of 38,062 in the [[2010 Military Bowl]], formerly the EagleBank Bowl. Great fan turnout from both universities set a bowl attendance record in Maryland coach [[Ralph Friedgen]]'s final game.\n* December 28, 2011: [[2011 Toledo Rockets football team|Toledo]] defeats [[2011 Air Force Falcons football team|Air Force]] 42\u201341 before a crowd of 25,042 in the [[2011 Military Bowl]].\n* December 27, 2012: In the last Military Bowl hosted at RFK Stadium, [[2012 San Jose State Spartans football team|San Jose State]] defeats [[2012 Bowling Green Falcons football team|Bowling Green]] 29\u201320 in the [[2012 Military Bowl]] before a crowd of 17,835, the lowest bowl attendance figure since the [[2005 Hawaii Bowl]] had only 16,134 attendees.<ref>{{cite news|last=Solomon|first=Jon|title=Military Bowl reports college football's smallest bowl crowd in 7 years|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2012/12/military_bowl_reports_college.html|access-date=December 28, 2012|newspaper=AL.com|date=December 28, 2012}}</ref> Beginning in [[2013 Military Bowl|2013]], [[Navy\u2013Marine Corps Memorial Stadium]] in [[Annapolis, Maryland]], replaced RFK Stadium as the site of the Military Bowl.\n\n====HBCU games====\n\n* October 24, 1970 - First Howard University game at RFK, a 24-7 victory over Fisk.\n* September 30, 1972 - Grambling beat Prairie View, 38-12.\n* Timmie Football Classic (1974-1975) Grambling vs. Morgan State<ref>{{cite news|title=Grambling-Morgan State Collide at RFK Stadium|work=The Pittsburgh Courier|date=6 September 1975}}</ref>\n* Nov 4, 1978 - Tennessee State vs North Carolina-Central faced off in an attempted reboot of the Capitol Classic, though renamed \"A Touch of Greatness\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carter|first1=Russell|title=Name Changes, Teams Same|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1978/10/31/name-changes-teams-same/70e54395-5c95-4c99-9e65-a0a0080218ef/|access-date=January 22, 2018|date=October 31, 1978}}</ref>\n* Nation's Capital Football Classic (1991) - Delaware State defeated Jackson State 37-34<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hente|first1=Kent|title=BISON AGAIN ENJOYING THE CLASSICS|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1991/10/04/bison-again-enjoying-the-classics/c78568b6-b06a-440e-8192-d484b2f900f4/|access-date=December 28, 2017|date=October 4, 1991}}</ref>\n* September 16, 2016  - The last Howard University game at RFK, a 34-7 loss to Hampton.\n\n====College All-Star Games====\n\n* U.S. Bowl (1962) - A college all-star game that lasted only one season. [[Galen Hall]] was the game's only MVP.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fogg|first1=Sam|title=Hall Aerials West to 33-19 Victory|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/42310629|accessdate=22 January 2018|date=8 January 1962}}</ref>\n* Freedom Bowl All-Star Classic (1986)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Greenberger|first1=Neil H.|title=All-Star Game Debuts at RFK|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1986/12/14/all-star-game-debuts-at-rfk/7e008c7a-83ae-4d64-91d7-93ed9e590ab3/|accessdate=28 December 2017|date=14 December 1986}}</ref>\n* All-America Classic (1993)<ref>{{cite news|title=FOOTBALL CLASSIC AT RFK GIVES OTHERS A CHANCE|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1993/01/14/football-classic-at-rfk-gives-others-a-chance/ae064c92-92fa-450d-babe-e1c7bdf79ca3/|accessdate=28 December 2017|date=14 January 1993}}</ref>\n\n====Neutral site games for local colleges====\n\n* October 17, 1965: Navy beat Pitt, 12-0.<ref>{{cite news|title=Navy Blitz made Pitt 12-0 Victim|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/40441609|accessdate=22 January 2018|date=18 October 1965}}</ref>\n* October 17, 1970: In their 4th ever meeting, Air Force beat Navy 26-3.<ref>{{cite news|title=Frostburg Gains Sixth Straight Victory|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/21333539|accessdate=22 January 2018|work=The Morning Herald|date=19 October 1970}}</ref>\n* November 4, 1972: Kentucky State defeated [[University of the District of Columbia|Federal City]] 26-8, in the only football game by a UDC school.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kentucky State has talent, lacks depth|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/110070226/|accessdate=22 January 2018|date=27 August 1972}}</ref>\n* October 4, 1975: Navy beat Air Force, 17-0.<ref>{{cite news|title=Navy-Air Force|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/30842486|accessdate=22 January 2018|work=Hobbs Daily News|date=5 October 1975}}</ref>\n* November 11, 1995: [[1995 Virginia Tech Hokies football team|Virginia Tech]] clinched a share of the Big East title with a win over Temple.<ref>{{cite news|title=TWO TACKLES, VA. TECH WRAP UP PIECE OF TITLE|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1995/11/12/two-tackles-va-tech-wrap-up-piece-of-title/2655f310-8f03-4ffd-b208-59ae3f252eb3/|accessdate=28 December 2017|date=12 November 1995}}</ref>\n* November 11, 2000: Salisbury defeated Frostburg State, 18-8 to win the 2nd Regents Cup.<ref>{{cite web|title=REGENTS CUP GAME|url=http://www.agametailgate.com/regentscup.htm|accessdate=22 January 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901121116/http://agametailgate.com/regentscup.htm|archivedate=September 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* November 10, 2001: In the only college football game at RFK to go into overtime, Frostburg State beat Salisbury 30-24 to win the 3rd Regents Cup.<ref>{{cite news|title=Football Shoots Down Salisbury in OT to Win Third Annual Regents' Cup Game|url=https://internal.frostburg.edu/home/news/university-news-portal/football-shoots-down-salisbury-in-ot-to-win-third-annual-regents-cup-game/|accessdate=22 January 2018|date=11 October 2001}}</ref>\n* September 30, 2017: Harvard defeated Georgetown, 41-2 in what may be the last college football game at RFK.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brooks|first1=J.|title=Georgetown football to host Harvard at RFK Stadium|url=https://wtop.com/ncaa-football/2017/08/hoya-football-host-harvard-rfk-stadium/|accessdate=28 December 2017|date=1 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n====High schools====\nRFK has occasionally hosted high school football games, but never has done so regularly.<ref name=pell20180814>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/recruiting-insider/wp/2018/08/14/d-c-high-school-football-triple-header-set-for-rfk-stadium-in-september/ Pell, Samantha, \"D.C. high school football triple-header set for RFK Stadium in September,\" washingtonpost.com, August 14, 2018 Retrieved August 18, 2018.]</ref> On August 14, 2018, DC Events announced the DC Events Kickoff Classic, a football tripleheader featuring six Washington, D.C., high schools, with games between [[Dunbar High School (Washington, D.C.)|Dunbar]] and [[Maret School|Maret]], [[Archbishop Carroll High School (Washington, D.C.)|Archbishop Carroll]] and [[Woodrow Wilson High School (Washington, D.C.)|Woodrow Wilson]], and [[Friendship Collegiate Academy Public Charter School|Friendship Collegiate Academy]] and [[H.D. Woodson High School|H. D. Woodson]].<ref name=pell20180814/> The first Classic was held on September 15, 2018, and DC Events indicated that it would become an annual event if attendance at the inaugural Classic was high enough.<ref name=pell20180814/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Williams |first1=Gary |title=Friendship, Wilson, Dunbar Victorious in DC Kickoff Classic |url=https://washingtoninformer.com/friendship-wilson-dunbar-victorious-in-dc-kickoff-classic/ |accessdate=20 February 2019 |date=17 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Soccer===\n[[File:DC United post-game victory celebration (RFK Memorial Stadium, 06-11-2004).jpg|300px|right|thumb|[[D.C. United]] after their win in the 2004 MLS Eastern Conference finals]]\n\n{{Main|D.C. United|Washington Freedom|United States men's national soccer team|United States women's national soccer team}}\n\nAlthough not designed for soccer, RFK Stadium, starting in the mid-1970s, became a center of American soccer, rivaled only by the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]] in [[Pasadena, California]], in terms of its history as a soccer venue.<ref name=goff20171020>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2017/10/19/soccer-at-rfk-stadium-its-dirty-and-disgusting-and-ugly-but-its-ours/|title=Perspective - American soccer made its home at aging, funky RFK Stadium|first=Steven|last=Goff|date=October 20, 2017|publisher=|access-date=February 1, 2018|via=www.WashingtonPost.com}}</ref> It is the only facility in the world to have hosted the [[FIFA World Cup]] (in [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]]), the [[FIFA Women's World Cup]] (in [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup|2003]]), [[Summer Olympic Games|Olympic]] group stages for men and women (in [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996]]), the [[MLS Cup]] (in [[1997 Major League Soccer season|1997]], [[2000 Major League Soccer season|2000]], and [[2007 Major League Soccer season|2007]]), the [[North American Soccer League]]'s [[Soccer Bowl]] (in [[Soccer Bowl '80|1980]]) and [[CONCACAF Champions' Cup]] matches (in [[1988 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|1988]] and [[1998 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|1998]]).<ref name=goff20171020/> The [[United States men's national soccer team]] played more of its matches at RFK stadium than at any other site,<ref name=goff20171020/> and D.C. United played 347 regular-season matches there.\n\nIn addition to being the home stadium of DC United, the Diplomats, the Freedom, the Whips and Team America, RFK also hosted three friendly [[Washington Darts]] games in 1970.<ref>{{cite news|title=D.C. Soccer Scheduled|work=The Federal Times|date=13 May 1970}}</ref>\n\nNotable soccer dates at the stadium include:\n* May 26, 1967: Professional soccer's debut game at D.C. Stadium is also the inaugural game of the new [[United Soccer Association]]. 9,403 fans show up to watch the [[Washington Whips]] lose 2-1 to the [[Cleveland Stokers]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Stokers Defeat Washington|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17023712/|access-date=January 31, 2018|work=Medina County Gazette|date=May 27, 1967}}</ref>\n* July 14, 1968: [[Pel\u00e9]]'s D.C. Stadium debut, before a District record soccer crowd of 20,189 fans. Pele's Santos squad defeated the Washington Whips 3 to 1. \n* September 7, 1968: In a de facto Atlantic Division championship game, the Whips lost to the Atlanta Chiefs before 14,227 fans, the largest, non-exhibition home crowd in Whips history. It would be the last Whips game at D.C. Stadium.\n* September 19, 1970: In what we be the largest crowd to ever watch a [[Washington Darts]] match, 13,878 fans come to RFK to watch them take on [[Pel\u00e9]] and his Santos squad. They lost 7-4. The Darts also lost their two other RFK matches, against Hertha Berlin and Coventry City the prior May.<ref>{{cite web|title=Washington Darts Friendlies|url=http://www.nasljerseys.com/Friendlies/Teams/Darts%20Friendlies.htm|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n* May 4, 1974: The Washington Diplomats play their first game at RFK, a 5-1 loss to the Philadelphia Atoms. 10,145 fans attend.\n* June 29, 1975: A District record 35,620 fans show up to see [[Pel\u00e9]] in his first game in DC with the [[New York Cosmos (1970\u201385)|New York Cosmos]] as they take on the Washington Diplomats. Cosmos wins 9-2.\n* August 6, 1977: Playing for the [[New York Cosmos (1970\u201385)|New York Cosmos]], [[Pel\u00e9]] plays his final regular-season game in the [[North American Soccer League]], facing the [[Washington Diplomats]] at RFK Stadium. He scores the Cosmos' only goal, but the Diplomats upset the Cosmos 2-1 before 31,283 fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.funwhileitlasted.net/2013/04/24/august-6-1977-washington-diplomats-vs-new-york-cosmos/|title=Washington Diplomats Archives \u2022 Fun While It Lasted|website=Fun While It Lasted|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n* October 6, 1977: The [[United States men's national soccer team]] plays its first match at the stadium versus China.\n* August 19, 1979: The Diplomats drop their first-ever home playoff game to the Los Angeles Aztecs 4-1. \n* June 1, 1980: In a nationally televised game, before a then District record crowd of 53,351 - the largest ever for NASL game in DC - the Diplomats lose a controversial game to the Cosmos, 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Feinstein|first1=John|title=Dips Stripped of 2 Goals, Lose, 2-1, Before 53,351|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1980/06/02/dips-stripped-of-2-goals-lose-2-1-before-53351/90c423bc-dad1-42e9-bde9-60d79dedd4ca/|access-date=January 30, 2018|work=The Washington Post|date=June 2, 1980}}</ref><ref name=\"rank\"/>\n* August 27, 1980: The Diplomats top the [[Los Angeles Aztecs]] 1-0 in the only home playoff victory in the franchise's NASL history.\n* September 21, 1980: In the [[Soccer Bowl '80]], before a crowd of 50,768, the [[New York Cosmos (1971\u201385)|New York Cosmos]] defeat the [[Fort Lauderdale Strikers (1977\u201383)|Fort Lauderdale Strikers]], 3\u20130.\n* August 16, 1981: The Washington Diplomats of the [[North American Soccer League|NASL]] play their last game at RFK, a 5-1 victory over the Toronto Blizzard. \n* April 23, 1983: [[Team America (NASL)|Team America]], a Washington, D.C.-based [[North American Soccer League|NASL]] franchise, plays its first game, defeating the [[Seattle Sounders]] 1-0 at RFK Stadium.<ref name=funlastedteamamerica>{{cite web|url=http://www.funwhileitlasted.net/2013/12/22/1983-team-america/|title=Team America, North American Soccer League|date=December 22, 2013|website=FunWhileItLasted.net|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n* June 14: 1983: 50,108 fans come to watch Team America play Fort Lauderdale followed a Beach Boys concert. The largest NASL crowd in RFK history saw Team America win 2-1 after a shootout.\n* September 3, 1983: Team America plays its last game, a 2-0 loss to the [[Fort Lauderdale Strikers (1977\u20131983)|Fort Lauderdale Strikers]] at RFK Stadium. The team folds after a single season, leaving Washington, D.C., without a professional soccer franchise until 1988.<ref name=funlastedteamamerica/>\n* June 7, 1987: In the final game of the US Ambassador Cup tournament, the newly-formed Washington Diplomats tie Honduran National Team to win the cup in front of 5,117 fans.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Berkowitz |first1=Steve |title=Diplomats Gain Tie in Final |work=The Washington Post |date=8 June 1987}}</ref>\n* April 17, 1988: In the first professional soccer game in DC in over 4 years, the new Washington Diplomats lost 2-1 to the [[New Jersey Eagles]] in front of a crowd of just 2,451.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Huff|first1=Donald|title=Diplomats Lose, 2-1, In Opener; 2,451 Fans Watch Eagles Win at RFK|date=18 April 1988}}</ref>\n* June 28, 1988: The [[Washington Diplomats]] lose to [[Monarcas Morelia]] 2-1 in the first of a two-game second-round series between the teams as part of the [[1988 CONCACAF Champions' Cup|CONCACAF Champions' Cup]]. The second game, two days later, would also result in a 2-1 loss.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Freeman|first1=Mike|title=Soccer|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1988/06/29/soccer/93092864-75ae-463c-87e6-956145adee7b/|access-date=January 31, 2018|date=June 29, 1988}}</ref>\n* August 13, 1988: In their first ever home playoff game in the ASL, the Diplomats top the [[New Jersey Eagles]], 4-1.\n* August 21, 1988: In the first game of the [[1988 American Soccer League]] finals, the [[Washington Diplomats (1988\u201390)|Washington Diplomats]] defeat the [[Fort Lauderdale Strikers (1988\u201394)|Fort Lauderdale Strikers]] 5-3 before 5,745 fans at RFK Stadium. The Diplomats will defeat the Strikers again at [[Fort Lauderdale]], [[Florida]], for a surprising [[American Soccer League (1988\u201389)|American Soccer League]] championship in the league's first season.\n* June 29, 1989: The Diplomats host the ASL All-Star game, losing to the All-Stars 2-1 in front of a crowd of 4,375.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goff |first1=Steven |title=All-Stars Overcome Diplomats, 2-1 |work=The Washington Post |date=30 June 1989}}</ref>\n* June 24, 1990: In their last game at RFK Stadium, the Diplomats lose to the Maryland Bays 4-2. Because of conflicts with concerts, they played their last two home games at RFK Stadium's auxiliary field, losing their last one 4-0 to the Miami Freedom on July 22, 1990.<ref name=\"Merger\">{{cite news|last1=Goff|first1=Stephen|title=MERGER PROPOSAL FOLLOWS DROP IN ATTENDANCE, STRAIN ON BUDGETS|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1990/06/28/merger-proposal-follows-drop-in-attendance-strain-on-budgets/1343dfad-86ae-4842-a123-6e21f46f673e/|access-date=January 31, 2018|work=The Washington Post|date=June 28, 1990}}</ref> Professional soccer would not return to RFK Stadium for more than five years.\n* June 13, 1993: a record-setting crowd of 54,118 show up to watch England tie Brazil 1-1 in the [[US Cup]].<ref name=\"rank\"/>\n* August 21, 1993: [[A.C. Milan]] defeats [[Torino F.C.]] 1\u20130 to win their second consecutive [[Supercoppa Italiana]].\n* June 28, 1994: 53,186 fans show up to watch Italy and Mexico during the World Cup in what becomes the 6th highest attendance soccer match in RFK history.<ref name=\"rank\"/>\n* June 29, 1994: [[Saeed Al-Owairan]] of the [[Saudi Arabia national football team]] sprints the length of the field and weaves through a maze of [[Belgium national football team]] players to score a stunning individual goal, giving [[Saudi Arabia]] a 1-0 upset victory over Belgium in [[1994 FIFA World Cup Group F|Group F of the FIFA 1994 World Cup]]. The goal later is voted the sixth-greatest [[FIFA World Cup]] goal of the 20th century. The win helps Saudi Arabia to advance to the second round of the [[FIFA World Cup]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ghostsofdc.org/2012/03/25/belgium-v-saudi-arabia-94-world-cup-game-at-rfk-stadium/|title=Belgium v. Saudi Arabia: '94 World Cup Game at RFK Stadium - Ghosts of DC|date=March 25, 2012|website=GhostsOfDC.org|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/news/y=2002/m=5/news=diego-maradona-goal-voted-the-fifa-world-cup-153-goal-the-century-82406.html|title=Diego Maradona goal voted the FIFA World Cup&#153; Goal of the Century|last=FIFA.com|date=May 30, 2002|website=FIFA.com|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n* July 2, 1994: The [[1994 FIFA World Cup]] concludes its play in RFK as [[Spain national football team|Spain]] defeats [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] 3\u20130 in the Round of Sixteen (RFK had earlier hosted four group-play games).\n* June 18, 1995: In the [[U.S. Cup]] the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] defeats [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] 4-0, with goals by [[Roy Wegerle]] (3' min), [[Thomas Dooley]] (25th min), [[John Harkes]] (36' min) and [[Claudio Reyna]] (67' min).\n* April 20, 1996: [[D.C. United]] plays its first game at RFK Stadium, losing 2-1 to the [[LA Galaxy]].\n* July 21, 1996: 45,946 fans show up to watch a group play match between Norway and Brazil in the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|1996 Olympics Women's Soccer tournament]]. It is the largest crowd for women's sports in Washington history. Two other women's Olympic matches were played in RFK as part of the [[1996 Summer Olympics|Atlanta Olympics]]. \n* July 24, 1996: RFK hosted the final match for the US men's side in the [[Football at the 1996 Summer Olympics|1996 Olympics Men's Soccer tournament]]. 58,012 spectators, the largest crowd in RFK history, watched the men tie Portugal 1-1, which was not enough to advance as they needed a win. Five other men's Olympic matches were played in RFK as part of the [[1996 Summer Olympics|Atlanta Olympics]].<ref>[http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1996/1996v1.pdf 1996 Summer Olympics official report.] Volume 1. p. 543.</ref><ref name=\"rank\">{{cite news|last1=Goff|first1=Steven|title=U.S. vs. Brazil friendly at FedEx Field ranks third in attendance in Washington area, first for a national team match|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/soccer-insider/post/us-vs-brazil-friendly-at-fedex-field-ranks-third-in-attendance-in-washington-area-first-for-a-national-team-match/2012/05/31/gJQA9Jfi4U_blog.html|access-date=January 31, 2018|date=May 31, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Constable |first1=Pamela |title=At RFK, A Home Team Sell-Out |work=The Washington Post |date=25 July 1996}}</ref>\n* October 30, 1996: Ten days after winning the first Major League Soccer title, [[1996 D.C. United season|D.C. United]] defeats the [[Rochester Raging Rhinos]] 3\u20131 in the [[Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]] final, achieving the first [[Double (association football)|\"double\"]] in the modern American soccer era.\n* October 26, 1997: [[1997 D.C. United season|D.C. United]] defeats the [[Colorado Rapids]] 2\u20131 to win their second consecutive [[1997 MLS Cup|MLS Cup]]. 57,431 fans attend, the 2nd largest soccer crowd in DC history, and the largest for a professional league match.<ref name=\"rank\"/> \n* August 16, 1998: D.C. United defeats [[Deportivo Toluca F.C.|CD Toluca]] of Mexico 1\u20130 to win the [[CONCACAF Champions' Cup]], becoming the first American team to do so and marking their first victory in an international tournament.\n* October 15, 2000: the [[2000 Kansas City Wizards season|Kansas City Wizards]] defeat the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] 1\u20130 to win their first [[MLS Cup 2000|MLS Cup]].\n* April 11, 2001: [[D.C. United]] defeats [[Arnett Gardens]] 2\u20131 in the second leg of the [[CONCACAF Giants Cup]] quarterfinals.\n* April 14, 2001: The [[Washington Freedom]] defeats the [[San Jose CyberRays|Bay Area CyberRays]] 1\u20130 in the inaugural match of the [[Women's United Soccer Association]].\n* Sept. 1, 2001: 54,282 people, the largest ever for a world cup qualifier at RFK, show up to watch the USA men vs. Honduras.<ref name=\"rank\"/>\n* August 3, 2002: In the [[Major League Soccer All-Star Game|MLS All-Star Game]], a team of MLS players defeat the [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S. Men's National Team]] [[2002 MLS All-Star Game|3\u20132]]. D.C. United midfielder [[Marco Etcheverry]] is named MVP.\n* July 30, 2003: [[Ronaldinho]] makes his debut for [[FC Barcelona]] against [[A.C. Milan]] in a pre-season tour of the United States. Ronaldinho had a goal and an assist as Barcelona defeated defending European champion Milan 2\u20130 in an exhibition game that drew 45,864 to RFK Stadium.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldinho Gives Glimpse|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/news/2003/07/30/barca_milan_ap/|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=July 30, 2003|accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ronaldinhosamba.com/ronaldinho_barcelona%20career_info_goal_news_new_barca_life.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080104054436/http://www.ronaldinhosamba.com/ronaldinho_barcelona%20career_info_goal_news_new_barca_life.html|title=Ronaldinhosamba barcelona career life info barca report knowledge|date=24 March 2007|archivedate=4 January 2008|publisher=}}</ref>\n* August 2, 2003: The [[Washington Freedom]] defeat the San Jose Cyber Rays in their last game at RFK as part of WUSA. The win clinches them a playoff spot and the Freedom go on to win the last Founder's Cup, which is awarded to the winner of the post-season playoff.\n* September 21, 2003: RFK hosts the [[2003 FIFA Women's World Cup]] opening ceremonies and first match. RFK would host six matches during the tournament.\n* April 3, 2004: [[Freddy Adu]] debuts with [[2004 D.C. United season|D.C. United]] at RFK with a capacity soccer crowd of 24,603.<ref>{{cite web |title=Adu Starts Well Out of the Blocks|first=Marc|last=Connolly|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story?id=296253&root=mls&cc=5901|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=April 3, 2004|accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref> At age 14, Adu was, and still is, the youngest player to play in [[Major League Soccer|MLS]].\n* November 6, 2004: D.C. United win the Eastern Conference final by tying the [[New England Revolution]] 3\u20133 and advancing on penalty kicks in what is generally regarded as one of the greatest games in MLS history. They would go on to defeat the [[2004 Kansas City Wizards season|Kansas City Wizards]] 3\u20132 in the [[MLS Cup 2004|MLS Cup]].\n* July 31, 2004: RFK Stadium hosts its second and last [[2004 MLS All-Star Game|MLS All-Star Game]]. The East beats the West 3-2.\n* August 9, 2007: [[David Beckham]] debuts for the MLS [[Los Angeles Galaxy]], losing to home team [[2007 D.C. United season|D.C. United]] before a sellout crowd of 46,686 fans, the fourth largest to watch MLS at RFK Stadium.\n* September 2, 2009: [[2009 Seattle Sounders FC season|Seattle Sounders FC]] defeats [[2009 D.C. United season|D.C. United]] 2\u20131 in the [[2009 Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup Final]]. This marked the first of Seattle's record-tying three consecutive [[Lamar Hunt U.S. Open Cup]] titles.\n* October 23, 2010: [[Jaime Moreno (footballer, born 1974)|Jaime Moreno]] scores on a penalty kick in his final game as a D.C. United player to retire as the all-time leading scorer in MLS history. [[2010 D.C. United season|United]] would lose the match, 3\u20132, to [[2010 Toronto FC season|Toronto FC]].\n* May 1, 2010: The Washington Freedom's last game at RFK, a 3-1 victory over [[Saint Louis Athletica]]\n* June 19, 2011: Quarterfinal of [[2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], USA vs. Jamaica. US defeats Jamaica 2\u20130 and moves onto the Semi-Final. In the second game of the double header [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]] played [[Panama national football team|Panama]] to a 1\u20131 tie. Panama won in a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|shoot out]] in front of 46,000 people.\n* June 2, 2013: The [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] defeated #2 ranked [[Germany national football team|Germany]] 4\u20133 in a friendly commemorating the 100th anniversary of the U.S. Soccer Federation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dempsey, U.S. Stun Germany in 7-goal Thriller|url=http://espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/1466756/dempsey-us-stun-germany-7-goal-thriller?cc=5901|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=June 2, 2013|accessdate=August 12, 2013}}</ref> \n* September 3, 2014: RFK hosts a triple-header on the first day of the group stage of the [[2014 Copa Centroamericana|Central American Cup USA 2014]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Central American Cup 2014 to Open in Washington, D.C. with Triple-Header|url=http://www.concacaf.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/Central-American-Cup-2014-to-Open-in-Washington-D.C.-with-Triple-Header.pdf|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref>\n* October 20, 2014: The [[United States women's national soccer team]] defeats the [[Haiti women's national football team]] 6-0 in the [[2014 CONCACAF Women's Championship]], which also acts as a qualifying tournament for the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup]].\n* March 1, 2016: Quer\u00e9taro eliminated D.C. United from the CONCACAF Champions League with a 1-1 tie, the last of four Champions League matches at RFK during the [[2015\u201316 CONCACAF Champions League|2015-2016]] season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Goff|first1=Steven|title=D.C. United exits CONCACAF Champions League|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/dcunited/dc-united-exits-concacaf-champions-league/2016/03/01/9cfc8c22-e022-11e5-8c00-8aa03741dced_story.html|access-date=January 31, 2018|date=March 1, 2016}}</ref>\n* October 22, 2017: In front of 41,418 fans (the highest attendance at the stadium since David Beckham's debut game), the [[New York Red Bulls]] beat D.C. United 2-1 in United's last match at RFK Stadium.<ref name=goff20171022/>\n* June 10, 2018: Alianza del El Salvador defeated Olimpia de Honduras 3-1 in a friendly\n* March 25, 2019: El Salvador defeated Peru 2-0 in a friendly.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goff |first1=Steven |title=RFK Stadium comes back to life for one night of old-school soccer charm |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/03/27/rfk-stadium-comes-back-life-one-night-old-school-soccer-charm/ |accessdate=29 March 2019 |work=The Washington Post |date=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n====College soccer====\nRFK hosted at least two college soccer games, once when Maryland moved their game there due to wet field conditions at Ludwig Field and again for a scheduled game following their national championship season. It has hosted several other Maryland games at the auxiliary field.\n\n* November 8, 1997: Maryland Terps defeated Ohio State 2-1<ref>{{cite web|title=ACC Champs End Regular Season at Home|url=http://www.umterps.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=29700&ATCLID=207268344|accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref>\n* April 20, 2009: Maryland lost to Wake Forest 3-1.<ref>{{cite news|title=Deacs Close Spring Season with 3-1 Win Against Maryland|url=http://www.wakeforestsports.com/sports/m-soccer/spec-rel/042009aaa.html|accessdate=5 March 2018|date=20 April 2009}}</ref>\n\n====United States men's national team matches====\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:CharlieDaviesTributeRFKUSA.jpg||300px|right|thumb|[[The American Outlaws]] [[tifo]] display for [[Charlie Davies]] during a World Cup Qualifier against Costa Rica in October 2009 at RFK.]] -->\nThe [[United States men's national soccer team]] has played more games at RFK Stadium than any other stadium.<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. Ready for 2011 CONCACAF Gold Cup Quarterfinal Match Against Jamaica|url=http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Mens-National-Team/2011/06/US-Ready-for-Gold-Cup-Quarterfinal-Match-against-Jamaica.aspx|publisher=US Soccer|date=June 17, 2011|accessdate=December 24, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120130045851/http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Mens-National-Team/2011/06/US-Ready-for-Gold-Cup-Quarterfinal-Match-against-Jamaica.aspx|archivedate=January 30, 2012}}</ref> At times it was suggested that due to the nature of RFK and its quirkiness that it would be a suitable [[national stadium]] if US Soccer were ever to seek one out.<ref>{{cite web|title=RFK as our National Soccer Stadium|url=http://www.matchfitusa.com/2009/10/rfk-national-soccer-stadium.html|work=Match Fit USA|date=October 20, 2009|access-date=December 24, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306184251/http://www.matchfitusa.com/2009/10/rfk-national-soccer-stadium.html|archivedate=March 6, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Every Big American Soccer Game Should Be Played in RFK|first=Bill|last=Simmons|authorlink=Bill Simmons|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=simmonsnflpicks/091016|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=October 16, 2009|access-date=December 24, 2011}}</ref> Several prominent members of the national team have scored at RFK, including [[Brian McBride]], [[Cobi Jones]], [[Eric Wynalda]], [[Joe-Max Moore]], [[Clint Dempsey]], [[Michael Bradley (soccer)|Michael Bradley]], and [[Landon Donovan]]. Winners are listed first.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Competition\n!Team\n!Score\n!Team\n!Attendance\n|- align=\"center\"\n|October 6, 1977||Friendly||{{fb|CHN}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20131||{{fb|USA}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"| Unknown\n|- align=\"center\"\n|May 12, 1990||Friendly||{{flagicon|NED}} [[AFC Ajax]]||style=\"text-align:center;\"|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lZCoiwWWgUE 1\u20131]||{{fb|USA}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 18,245\n|- align=\"center\"\n|October 19, 1991||Friendly||'''{{fb|PRK|1948}}'''||style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\u20131||{{fb|USA}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"| 16,351\n|- align=\"center\"\n|May 30, 1992||[[1992 U.S. Cup]]||'''{{fb|USA}}'''||style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\u20131||{{fb|IRL}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|35,696\n|- align=\"center\"\n|October 13, 1993||Friendly||{{fb|MEX}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20131||{{fb|USA}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|23,927\n|- align=\"center\"\n|June 18, 1995||[[1995 U.S. Cup]]||'''{{fb|USA}}'''||style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\u20130||{{fb|MEX}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|38,615\n|- align=\"center\"\n|October 8, 1995||Friendly||'''{{fb|USA}}'''||style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\u20133||{{fb|SAU}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|10,216\n|- align=\"center\"\n|June 12, 1996||[[1996 U.S. Cup]]||'''{{fb|BOL}}'''||style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\u20130||{{fb|USA}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|19,350\n|- align=\"center\"\n|November 3, 1996||[[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)]]||'''{{fb|USA}}'''||style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\u20130||{{fb|GUA}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|30,082\n|- align=\"center\"\n|October 3, 1997||[[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)]]||{{fb|JAM}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20131||{{fb|USA}}||style=\"text-align:center;\"|51,528\n|- align=\"center\"\n|May 30, 1998||Friendly||{{fb|SCO}}||style=\"text-align: