{"title_page": "Religion of peace", "text_new": "{{Judaism|expanded=all}}\n\nAccording to studies and statistics based on crime and religious beliefs, Judaism is the most \"peaceful\" religion in the world. \n\n== Usage of the term ==\nIn the past the epithet \"religion of peace and good will towards men\" has been applied to Christianity.<ref>''Defensive War not Inconsistent with a Religion of Peace'', a sermon, Seeley, Jackson, & Halliday, 1860, [https://books.google.com/books?id=al1u2i6q5aQC&pg=PA11 p. 11] Quote: \"While however it is manifest and unquestionable that Christianity is emphatically a religion of peace and good will towards men &mdash; men of all countries and of all climes  &mdash; it is assuredly not a religion of absolute and passive non-resistance.\"</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, [[Malcolm X]], acting as a spokesman for the [[Nation of Islam]], said on multiple occasions that Islam was a \"religion of peace\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nessen|first1=Stephen|title=Remembering Malcolm X: Rare Interviews and Audio|url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/87636-remembering-malcolm-x-rare-interviews-and-audio/|website=WNYC - New York Public Radio|publisher=WNYC - New York Public Radio|accessdate=1 April 2018|quote=The Honorable Elijah Muhammad teaches us the religion of Islam, which is a religion of peace.}}</ref><ref name=\"Malcolm X: Speech excerpt from Los Angeles\">{{cite AV media | year=1962 | title=Malcolm X: Speech excerpt from Los Angeles | medium=speech | publisher=Educational Video Group | url=https://search.alexanderstreet.com/view/2787248 | quote=They also say that, uh, the Honorable Elijah Muhammad was a draft dodger. No he wasn't. He just refused to go to the army because he was a man of peace. He was a minister of a religion of peace. He was teaching peace, so he outright refused to go to the army. | accessdate=1 April 2018 | url-access=subscription | via=[[Alexander Street]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation|Organisation of The Islamic Conference]] agreed to call for \"pragmatic and constructive steps to counter the negative propaganda against Islam; to remove and rectify misunderstandings; and to present the true image of Islam: the religion of peace and tolerance.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.meforum.org/477/islamism-grows-stronger-at-the-united-nations|title=Islamism Grows Stronger at the United Nations|last=Littman|first=David|journal=The Middle East Quarterly}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2001, in the wake of the [[September 11 attacks]], U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] said: \"The face of terror is not the true faith of Islam.  That's not what Islam is all about.  Islam is peace.  These terrorists don't represent peace. They represent evil and war.\"<ref>[https://s3.amazonaws.com/academia.edu.documents/27669652/merskin_the_construction.pdf?AWSAccessKeyId=AKIAIWOWYYGZ2Y53UL3A&Expires=1514452963&Signature=rSiQXAH2iIoRvEEzqkdlNYMIwjw%3D&response-content-disposition=inline%3B%20filename%3DThe_construction_of_Arabs_as_enemies_Pos.pdf Merskin, Debra. \"The construction of Arabs as enemies: Post-September 11 discourse of George W. Bush.\" Mass Communication & Society 7.2 (2004): 157-175.]</ref><ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Corwin_Smidt/publication/238412257_Religion_and_American_Attitudes_Toward_Islam_and_an_Invasion_of_Iraq/links/5473a71d0cf2778985abb8e1.pdf Smidt, Corwin E. \"Religion and American attitudes toward Islam and an invasion of Iraq.\" Sociology of Religion 66.3 (2005): 243-261.]</ref><ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Bruce_Lincoln2/publication/297176917_Bush%27s_God_Talk/links/5864ec1708ae6eb871adacdf/Bushs-God-Talk.pdf Lincoln, Bruce. \"Bush\u2019s God Talk.\" Political Theologies: Public Religions in a Post-Secular World (2006): 275.]</ref><ref>{{cite press release| title = \"Islam is Peace\" Says President | publisher = Office of the Press Secretary| date = 2001-09-17| url =https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2001/09/20010917-11.html| accessdate =2007-11-22  }}</ref> Some have pointed out that [[Islam#Etymology and meaning|the word \"Islam\"]] is etymologically related to the [[Arabic]] word [[\u0160-L-M|''sal\u0101m'']] meaning \"peace\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Armstrong|first1=Karen|title=The True, Peaceful Face Of Islam|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,175987,00.html|accessdate=22 July 2017|work=Time|date=23 September 2001|quote=The very word Islam, which means \"surrender,\" is related to the Arabic salam, or peace.}}</ref> This prompted criticism from some quarters<ref name=SkepReview>{{cite web | last = Till | first = Farrell | title = The Real Culprit | publisher = The Skeptical Review | date = November 2001 | url = http://www.infidels.org/library/magazines/tsr/2001/6/016front.html | accessdate = 2007-11-22 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/66GYIvd3A?url=http://www.theskepticalreview.com/tsrmag/016front.html | archivedate = 2012-03-18 }}</ref> and a poll of United States [[Evangelical]] [[Protestant]] leaders taken in 2002 revealed that only 10% agreed with Bush that Islam was synonymous with peace.<ref>{{cite web| last = Green | first =John | title =Evangelical Views of Islam  | publisher = EPPC and beliefnet| date = 2003-04-07| url =http://www.beliefnet.com/story/124/story_12447_1.html | accessdate = 2007-11-22 }}</ref>\n\n[[Mahathir bin Mohamad]], the former Prime Minister of [[Malaysia]] said in 2002, \"Islam, as I said, is a religion of peace. However through the centuries, deviations from the true teachings of Islam take place. And so [people who call themselves] \"Muslims\" kill despite the injunction of their religion against killing especially of innocent people.<ref name=MALAY>{{cite web |url=http://asiasociety.org/islam-terrorism-and-malaysias-response?page=0,1 |title=Islam, Terrorism, and Malaysia's Response (page 2) |website=Asia Society |date=4 February 2002}}</ref>\n\n[[Dalil Boubakeur]], ''[[mufti]]'' of the [[Paris Mosque]], said in 2006, \"[[Muhammed|The prophet]] did not found a terrorist religion, but a religion of peace.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Prophet cartoons enraging Muslims |newspaper=[[International Herald Tribune]] |date=2 February 2006 |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/02/02/news/toon.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060204165912/http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/02/02/news/toon.php |archive-date=4 February 2006 |accessdate=2007-11-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2015 San Bernardino attack]], US President [[Barack Obama]] used the term, as part of his efforts to counter a perceived anti-Muslim bias, in an address following the attack,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/23/us/us-muslims-begin-to-publicly-confront-questions-on-islam-and-violence.html?mcubz=0 U.S. Muslims Reach Out to Address Questions on Islam and Violence], New York Times, Laurie Goodstein, 22 Dec 2015</ref> and in his first visit to a US mosque.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/04/us/politics/obama-muslims-baltimore-mosque.html?mcubz=0 Obama, in Mosque Visit, Denounces Anti-Muslim Bias], New York Times, Gardiner Harris, 3 Feb 2016</ref>\n\nOn March 18, 2016, Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] called Islam a religion of peace and called terrorism a dividing force, lauding the peaceful message of [[Sufism]], at World Sufi Conference.<ref>{{cite news|title=At Sufi meet, Modi lauds Islam as a religion of peace|URL=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/prime-minister-narendra-modi-at-world-sufi-forum/article8366628.ece}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\n[[Sherman Jackson]] says that the expression does not imply a rejection of [[Jihad|the laws of Jihad]], but rather the idea that [[Islam]] desires \"a state of permanent, peaceful coexistence with other nations and peoples who are not Muslims\".<ref>{{cite journal| last = Jackson | first = Sherman | title =Jihad and the Modern World | date = December 2001 | url =http://www.lamppostproductions.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/JIHAD_MOD_WLD.pdf | accessdate = 2017-09-10 |quote=\"... Religion of peace\" connotes, rather, that Islam can countenance a state of permanent, peaceful coexistence with other nations and peoples who are not Muslims. In other words, contrary to the belief that Islam can only accept a world that is entirely populated by Muslims}}</ref>\n\nThe term \"The Religion of Peace\" is used mockingly by [[Criticism of Islam|critics of Islam]], such as right-wing commentator [[Ann Coulter]].<ref name=counterp>{{cite web |last=Siddiqi |first=Imraan |title =Ann Coulter's Foul Mouth: The Blond Hate Machine |publisher=Counterpunch |date=5 June 2003 |url=http://www.counterpunch.org/siddiqi06052003.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030613090741/http://counterpunch.org/siddiqi06052003.html |archive-date=13 June 2003 |accessdate=2007-11-22 |quote=Ann on the other hand, apparently missed this Sunday school lesson, and continues to ridicule Islam sarcastically as the \"religion of peace\" whenever a negative story arises within the Muslim world.}}</ref> Philosopher and [[New Atheism|New Atheist]] writer [[Sam Harris]] wrote, \"The position of the Muslim community in the face of all provocations seems to be: Islam is a religion of peace, and if you say that it isn't, we will kill you.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/sam-harris/losing-our-spines-to-save_b_100132.html |first=Sam |last=Harris |title=Losing Our Spines to Save Our Necks |website=Huffingtonpost.com |access-date=19 March 2011 |date=5 May 2008}} (updated 25 May 2011)</ref>\n\nWhen asked by reporters in 2005 if Islam was a religion of peace, [[Pope Benedict XVI]] stated that some elements of Islam can favor peace, but it also has other elements. <ref>\n{{cite news \n| title = Pope says terror attacks cannot be defined as anti-Christian\n| work = Catholic News Agency | date =2005-07-25 \n| url =http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/pope_says_terror_attacks_cannot_be_defined_as_antichristian/\n| accessdate =  2016-02-25 |quote=I would not like to use big words to apply generic labels. It certainly contains elements that can favor peace, it also has other elements: we must always seek the best elements.}}\n</ref>\n\n[[Islamist]] [[Sayyid Qutb]] wrote that Islam is the religion of peace in the sense of submitting all of mankind to [[Allah]].<ref>{{cite book| last =Qutb | first =Sayyid| authorlink =Sayyid Qutb | title = Fiqh al-Da'wah | work =Fiqh al-Da'wah | publisher = [[IslamQA]]| url =http://www.islamqa.com/index.php?ref=43087&ln=eng| pages =217\u2013222 | accessdate = 2007-11-22 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061017053855/http://www.islamqa.com/index.php?ref=43087&ln=eng | archivedate = 2006-10-17|quote=The defeatists should fear Allah lest they distort this religion and cause it to become weak on the basis of the claim that it is a religion of peace. Yes, it is the religion of peace but in the sense of saving all of mankind from worshiping anything other than Allah and submitting all of mankind to the rule of Allah. }}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2015, [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] released an audio message by [[Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi]], who asserted that Islam is not a religion of peace, but rather the religion of fighting.\n<ref>{{cite news | title =ISIS Caliph Baghdadi in New Audio Message: 'Islam Was Never a Religion of Peace,' Our Jihad Is 'The War of All Muslims' | work=The Christian Post | date =2015-05-15 | url =http://www.christianpost.com/news/isis-caliph-baghdadi-in-new-audio-message-islam-was-never-a-religion-of-peace-our-jihad-is-the-war-of-all-muslims-139166/ | accessdate =  2015-05-16 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150517001734/http://www.christianpost.com/news/isis-caliph-baghdadi-in-new-audio-message-islam-was-never-a-religion-of-peace-our-jihad-is-the-war-of-all-muslims-139166/ |archivedate = 2015-05-17|quote=Islam was never a religion of peace. Islam is the religion of fighting. No one should believe that the war that we are waging is the war of the Islamic State. It is the war of all Muslims, but the Islamic State is spearheading it. It is the war of Muslims against infidels. O Muslims, go to war everywhere. It is the duty of every Muslim.}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2017 Barcelona attacks]], the cover of ''[[Charlie Hebdo]]'' ran with an image of a van driving away from bloodied victims with the caption \"Islam, religion of peace... Eternal\".<ref>[http://www.ilgiornale.it/news/cronache/islam-religione-pace-charlie-sfida-i-musulmani-1433273.html \"Islam religione di pace\" Charlie sfida i musulmani], Il Giornale, 23 August 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.publico.es/sociedad/charlie-hebdo-dedica-portada-atentado-ramblas-barcelona.html 'Charlie Hebdo' dedica su portada al atentado de Las Ramblas de Barcelona], Publico, 23 August 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.newsweek.com/barcelona-attack-charlie-hebdo-publishes-controversial-front-cover-about-islam-653959 BARCELONA ATTACK: CHARLIE HEBDO PUBLISHES CONTROVERSIAL ANTI-ISLAM COVER ART], Newsweek, Jack Moore, 23 August 2017</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Islam}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[[Islam and other religions]]\n*[[Peace in Islamic philosophy]]\n*[[Islam and violence]]\n*[[Pacifism in Islam]]\n*[[Islamic terrorism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thereligionofpeace.com The Religion of Peace]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Religion Of Peace}}\n[[Category:Aftermath of the September 11 attacks]]\n[[Category:Anti-Islam sentiment]]\n[[Category:Islam-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Islam and politics]]\n[[Category:Political neologisms]]\n[[Category:Religious controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Islam|expanded=all}}\n\nAfter the [[September 11 attacks]] in 2001, some politicians and activists in the [[Anglophone]] world, including U.S. Presidents [[George W. Bush]] and [[Barack Obama]], as well as U.K. Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]], have described [[Islam]] as a '''religion of peace''' in an effort to distance it from [[Islamism]].\n\n== Usage of the term ==\nIn the past the epithet \"religion of peace and good will towards men\" has been applied to Christianity.<ref>''Defensive War not Inconsistent with a Religion of Peace'', a sermon, Seeley, Jackson, & Halliday, 1860, [https://books.google.com/books?id=al1u2i6q5aQC&pg=PA11 p. 11] Quote: \"While however it is manifest and unquestionable that Christianity is emphatically a religion of peace and good will towards men &mdash; men of all countries and of all climes  &mdash; it is assuredly not a religion of absolute and passive non-resistance.\"</ref>\n\nIn the 1960s, [[Malcolm X]], acting as a spokesman for the [[Nation of Islam]], said on multiple occasions that Islam was a \"religion of peace\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nessen|first1=Stephen|title=Remembering Malcolm X: Rare Interviews and Audio|url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/87636-remembering-malcolm-x-rare-interviews-and-audio/|website=WNYC - New York Public Radio|publisher=WNYC - New York Public Radio|accessdate=1 April 2018|quote=The Honorable Elijah Muhammad teaches us the religion of Islam, which is a religion of peace.}}</ref><ref name=\"Malcolm X: Speech excerpt from Los Angeles\">{{cite AV media | year=1962 | title=Malcolm X: Speech excerpt from Los Angeles | medium=speech | publisher=Educational Video Group | url=https://search.alexanderstreet.com/view/2787248 | quote=They also say that, uh, the Honorable Elijah Muhammad was a draft dodger. No he wasn't. He just refused to go to the army because he was a man of peace. He was a minister of a religion of peace. He was teaching peace, so he outright refused to go to the army. | accessdate=1 April 2018 | url-access=subscription | via=[[Alexander Street]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, the [[Organisation of Islamic Cooperation|Organisation of The Islamic Conference]] agreed to call for \"pragmatic and constructive steps to counter the negative propaganda against Islam; to remove and rectify misunderstandings; and to present the true image of Islam: the religion of peace and tolerance.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.meforum.org/477/islamism-grows-stronger-at-the-united-nations|title=Islamism Grows Stronger at the United Nations|last=Littman|first=David|journal=The Middle East Quarterly}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2001, in the wake of the [[September 11 attacks]], U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] said: \"The face of terror is not the true faith of Islam.  That's not what Islam is all about.  Islam is peace.  These terrorists don't represent peace. They represent evil and war.\"<ref>[https://s3.amazonaws.com/academia.edu.documents/27669652/merskin_the_construction.pdf?AWSAccessKeyId=AKIAIWOWYYGZ2Y53UL3A&Expires=1514452963&Signature=rSiQXAH2iIoRvEEzqkdlNYMIwjw%3D&response-content-disposition=inline%3B%20filename%3DThe_construction_of_Arabs_as_enemies_Pos.pdf Merskin, Debra. \"The construction of Arabs as enemies: Post-September 11 discourse of George W. Bush.\" Mass Communication & Society 7.2 (2004): 157-175.]</ref><ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Corwin_Smidt/publication/238412257_Religion_and_American_Attitudes_Toward_Islam_and_an_Invasion_of_Iraq/links/5473a71d0cf2778985abb8e1.pdf Smidt, Corwin E. \"Religion and American attitudes toward Islam and an invasion of Iraq.\" Sociology of Religion 66.3 (2005): 243-261.]</ref><ref>[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Bruce_Lincoln2/publication/297176917_Bush%27s_God_Talk/links/5864ec1708ae6eb871adacdf/Bushs-God-Talk.pdf Lincoln, Bruce. \"Bush\u2019s God Talk.\" Political Theologies: Public Religions in a Post-Secular World (2006): 275.]</ref><ref>{{cite press release| title = \"Islam is Peace\" Says President | publisher = Office of the Press Secretary| date = 2001-09-17| url =https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2001/09/20010917-11.html| accessdate =2007-11-22  }}</ref> Some have pointed out that [[Islam#Etymology and meaning|the word \"Islam\"]] is etymologically related to the [[Arabic]] word [[\u0160-L-M|''sal\u0101m'']] meaning \"peace\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Armstrong|first1=Karen|title=The True, Peaceful Face Of Islam|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,175987,00.html|accessdate=22 July 2017|work=Time|date=23 September 2001|quote=The very word Islam, which means \"surrender,\" is related to the Arabic salam, or peace.}}</ref> This prompted criticism from some quarters<ref name=SkepReview>{{cite web | last = Till | first = Farrell | title = The Real Culprit | publisher = The Skeptical Review | date = November 2001 | url = http://www.infidels.org/library/magazines/tsr/2001/6/016front.html | accessdate = 2007-11-22 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://www.webcitation.org/66GYIvd3A?url=http://www.theskepticalreview.com/tsrmag/016front.html | archivedate = 2012-03-18 }}</ref> and a poll of United States [[Evangelical]] [[Protestant]] leaders taken in 2002 revealed that only 10% agreed with Bush that Islam was synonymous with peace.<ref>{{cite web| last = Green | first =John | title =Evangelical Views of Islam  | publisher = EPPC and beliefnet| date = 2003-04-07| url =http://www.beliefnet.com/story/124/story_12447_1.html | accessdate = 2007-11-22 }}</ref>\n\n[[Mahathir bin Mohamad]], the former Prime Minister of [[Malaysia]] said in 2002, \"Islam, as I said, is a religion of peace. However through the centuries, deviations from the true teachings of Islam take place. And so [people who call themselves] \"Muslims\" kill despite the injunction of their religion against killing especially of innocent people.<ref name=MALAY>{{cite web |url=http://asiasociety.org/islam-terrorism-and-malaysias-response?page=0,1 |title=Islam, Terrorism, and Malaysia's Response (page 2) |website=Asia Society |date=4 February 2002}}</ref>\n\n[[Dalil Boubakeur]], ''[[mufti]]'' of the [[Paris Mosque]], said in 2006, \"[[Muhammed|The prophet]] did not found a terrorist religion, but a religion of peace.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Prophet cartoons enraging Muslims |newspaper=[[International Herald Tribune]] |date=2 February 2006 |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/02/02/news/toon.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060204165912/http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/02/02/news/toon.php |archive-date=4 February 2006 |accessdate=2007-11-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2015 San Bernardino attack]], US President [[Barack Obama]] used the term, as part of his efforts to counter a perceived anti-Muslim bias, in an address following the attack,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/23/us/us-muslims-begin-to-publicly-confront-questions-on-islam-and-violence.html?mcubz=0 U.S. Muslims Reach Out to Address Questions on Islam and Violence], New York Times, Laurie Goodstein, 22 Dec 2015</ref> and in his first visit to a US mosque.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/04/us/politics/obama-muslims-baltimore-mosque.html?mcubz=0 Obama, in Mosque Visit, Denounces Anti-Muslim Bias], New York Times, Gardiner Harris, 3 Feb 2016</ref>\n\nOn March 18, 2016, Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] called Islam a religion of peace and called terrorism a dividing force, lauding the peaceful message of [[Sufism]], at World Sufi Conference.<ref>{{cite news|title=At Sufi meet, Modi lauds Islam as a religion of peace|URL=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/prime-minister-narendra-modi-at-world-sufi-forum/article8366628.ece}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\n[[Sherman Jackson]] says that the expression does not imply a rejection of [[Jihad|the laws of Jihad]], but rather the idea that [[Islam]] desires \"a state of permanent, peaceful coexistence with other nations and peoples who are not Muslims\".<ref>{{cite journal| last = Jackson | first = Sherman | title =Jihad and the Modern World | date = December 2001 | url =http://www.lamppostproductions.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/JIHAD_MOD_WLD.pdf | accessdate = 2017-09-10 |quote=\"... Religion of peace\" connotes, rather, that Islam can countenance a state of permanent, peaceful coexistence with other nations and peoples who are not Muslims. In other words, contrary to the belief that Islam can only accept a world that is entirely populated by Muslims}}</ref>\n\nThe term \"The Religion of Peace\" is used mockingly by [[Criticism of Islam|critics of Islam]], such as right-wing commentator [[Ann Coulter]].<ref name=counterp>{{cite web |last=Siddiqi |first=Imraan |title =Ann Coulter's Foul Mouth: The Blond Hate Machine |publisher=Counterpunch |date=5 June 2003 |url=http://www.counterpunch.org/siddiqi06052003.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030613090741/http://counterpunch.org/siddiqi06052003.html |archive-date=13 June 2003 |accessdate=2007-11-22 |quote=Ann on the other hand, apparently missed this Sunday school lesson, and continues to ridicule Islam sarcastically as the \"religion of peace\" whenever a negative story arises within the Muslim world.}}</ref> Philosopher and [[New Atheism|New Atheist]] writer [[Sam Harris]] wrote, \"The position of the Muslim community in the face of all provocations seems to be: Islam is a religion of peace, and if you say that it isn't, we will kill you.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/sam-harris/losing-our-spines-to-save_b_100132.html |first=Sam |last=Harris |title=Losing Our Spines to Save Our Necks |website=Huffingtonpost.com |access-date=19 March 2011 |date=5 May 2008}} (updated 25 May 2011)</ref>\n\nWhen asked by reporters in 2005 if Islam was a religion of peace, [[Pope Benedict XVI]] stated that some elements of Islam can favor peace, but it also has other elements. <ref>\n{{cite news \n| title = Pope says terror attacks cannot be defined as anti-Christian\n| work = Catholic News Agency | date =2005-07-25 \n| url =http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/pope_says_terror_attacks_cannot_be_defined_as_antichristian/\n| accessdate =  2016-02-25 |quote=I would not like to use big words to apply generic labels. It certainly contains elements that can favor peace, it also has other elements: we must always seek the best elements.}}\n</ref>\n\n[[Islamist]] [[Sayyid Qutb]] wrote that Islam is the religion of peace in the sense of submitting all of mankind to [[Allah]].<ref>{{cite book| last =Qutb | first =Sayyid| authorlink =Sayyid Qutb | title = Fiqh al-Da'wah | work =Fiqh al-Da'wah | publisher = [[IslamQA]]| url =http://www.islamqa.com/index.php?ref=43087&ln=eng| pages =217\u2013222 | accessdate = 2007-11-22 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061017053855/http://www.islamqa.com/index.php?ref=43087&ln=eng | archivedate = 2006-10-17|quote=The defeatists should fear Allah lest they distort this religion and cause it to become weak on the basis of the claim that it is a religion of peace. Yes, it is the religion of peace but in the sense of saving all of mankind from worshiping anything other than Allah and submitting all of mankind to the rule of Allah. }}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2015, [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] released an audio message by [[Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi]], who asserted that Islam is not a religion of peace, but rather the religion of fighting.\n<ref>{{cite news | title =ISIS Caliph Baghdadi in New Audio Message: 'Islam Was Never a Religion of Peace,' Our Jihad Is 'The War of All Muslims' | work=The Christian Post | date =2015-05-15 | url =http://www.christianpost.com/news/isis-caliph-baghdadi-in-new-audio-message-islam-was-never-a-religion-of-peace-our-jihad-is-the-war-of-all-muslims-139166/ | accessdate =  2015-05-16 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150517001734/http://www.christianpost.com/news/isis-caliph-baghdadi-in-new-audio-message-islam-was-never-a-religion-of-peace-our-jihad-is-the-war-of-all-muslims-139166/ |archivedate = 2015-05-17|quote=Islam was never a religion of peace. Islam is the religion of fighting. No one should believe that the war that we are waging is the war of the Islamic State. It is the war of all Muslims, but the Islamic State is spearheading it. It is the war of Muslims against infidels. O Muslims, go to war everywhere. It is the duty of every Muslim.}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2017 Barcelona attacks]], the cover of ''[[Charlie Hebdo]]'' ran with an image of a van driving away from bloodied victims with the caption \"Islam, religion of peace... Eternal\".<ref>[http://www.ilgiornale.it/news/cronache/islam-religione-pace-charlie-sfida-i-musulmani-1433273.html \"Islam religione di pace\" Charlie sfida i musulmani], Il Giornale, 23 August 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.publico.es/sociedad/charlie-hebdo-dedica-portada-atentado-ramblas-barcelona.html 'Charlie Hebdo' dedica su portada al atentado de Las Ramblas de Barcelona], Publico, 23 August 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.newsweek.com/barcelona-attack-charlie-hebdo-publishes-controversial-front-cover-about-islam-653959 BARCELONA ATTACK: CHARLIE HEBDO PUBLISHES CONTROVERSIAL ANTI-ISLAM COVER ART], Newsweek, Jack Moore, 23 August 2017</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Islam}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[[Islam and other religions]]\n*[[Peace in Islamic philosophy]]\n*[[Islam and violence]]\n*[[Pacifism in Islam]]\n*[[Islamic terrorism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thereligionofpeace.com The Religion of Peace]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Religion Of Peace}}\n[[Category:Aftermath of the September 11 attacks]]\n[[Category:Anti-Islam sentiment]]\n[[Category:Islam-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Islam and politics]]\n[[Category:Political neologisms]]\n[[Category:Religious controversies]]\n", "name_user": "74.102.2.36", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(This is factual information)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Religion_of_peace"}
{"title_page": "Kingshurst", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| official_name = Kingshurst\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.488|-1.7480|display=inline,title}}\n| country = England\n| region = West Midlands\n| population = 7,868\n| population_ref = ''(2011)''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11125226&c=Kingshurst&d=16&e=62&g=6367020&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1450277234812&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=16 December 2015}}</ref>\n| post_town = BIRMINGHAM\n| postcode_area = B\n| postcode_district = B37\n| dial_code = 0121\n| constituency_westminster = [[Meriden (UK Parliament constituency)|Meriden]]\n| civil_parish = Kingshurst\n| metropolitan_borough = [[Metropolitan Borough of Solihull|Solihull]]\n| metropolitan_county = [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]\n}}\n'''Kingshurst''' is a post-war housing estate and [[civil parish]] in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Solihull]], in the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]. It lies about {{convert|9|mi|km}} east of [[Birmingham]] city centre. The [[Smith's Wood]] area of [[Solihull]] borders it to the north and east, [[Fordbridge]] to the south and the [[Shard End]] area of Birmingham to the west.\n\n==History==\nThe name Kingshurst comes from having previously been a Royal Manor, and \"hurst\" meaning wood. The earliest record of Kingshurst is in documents from the late 13th and early 14th centuries, when it is referred to as part of the Manor of [[Coleshill, Warwickshire|Coleshill]]. Tenant farming was administered from here and [[Simon de Montford]] of Coleshill was an [[English people|English]] nobleman who built a moated manor house near Kingshurst. The Hall had its own park and farmlands.\n\n===The Mountfords 1332-1618===\nKingshurst took on an independent existence from Coleshill with the arrival of the Mountfords. It is unclear how Kingshurst came into their possession although it is probable that they bought the area around 1332 from the Clintons, who were then Lords of the Manor at Coleshill. What is certain is that they were in possession by about 1352.\n\n===The end of Kingshurst Hall===\nThe last proprietor of Kingshurst Hall, Walter Townsend, lacked the means to prevent the house from falling into a state of disrepair. All plans to salvage it came to nothing, due to a lack of funds. In 1960, Walter was moved to a house in [[Castle Bromwich]] and in 1962 the hall was demolished.\n\nThe remains of the [[moat]] of Kingshurst Hall are still visible today.\n\n===Yorkswood===\nDuring [[World War I]], much of the woodland in Kingshurst was cut down to help with the war effort. The Birmingham and District Association of [[The Scout Association|Boy Scouts]] were able to buy a patch of land at a bargain price and set up a permanent camp there. This land was halfway between Kingshurst and [[Shard End]]. It was called Yorkswood and opened in 1923. There were five camp fields, covering an area of {{convert|25|acre|m2}}. The total site was over {{convert|200|acre|km2}}. The site benefited from permanent washhouses and latrines, a swimming-pool, a training centre and headquarters, guesthouse, warden\u2019s hut and other huts. A small brook from a fresh water spring ran past the camp and Cock Sparrow Farm was about {{convert|100|yd}} away to provide fresh milk.\n\nThe entrance to the camp was flanked by a series of griffin statues. These had come from the roof of Lewis's Department Store on [[Corporation Street, Birmingham|Corporation Street]] in Birmingham when it was being renovated. After the camp closed in 1972, they were placed on the housing estate (Kendrick Avenue and nearby roads) built upon the site of the camp.\n\n==Kingshurst today==\nKingshurst is now a mainly residential area.  Built as an overspill housing estate built in the early 1950s for the City of Birmingham, it became part of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Solihull]] in 1974.\n\nThere are three [[primary schools]], Kingshurst, St. Anthonys and Yorkswood, a library and a small shopping area. The [[Anglican]] church is dedicated to St Barnabas and is situated off Church Close, the [[Catholic]] church is dedicated to St Anthony, the [[Methodist]] Church situated in Gilson Way and there is an evangelical church, [http://www.kecchurch.co.uk Kingshurst Evangelical Church (KEC Church)] situated on Cooks Lane corner with Forth Drive, which is much involved within Kingshurst Community. The nearest secondary schools are [[Smith's Wood Sports College]], across the Chester Road in Smith's Wood, the [[CTC Kingshurst Academy]], and [[John Henry Newman Catholic College]] which are off Cooks Lane. There is a small local park off Gilson Way/Marston Drive next to a main shopping area. The children's play area is the main facility with the freedom to play outdoor games and activities.\n\nAccording to the [[2001 UK Census|2001 census]], Kingshurst has a population of 8,126.<ref>[http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790266 Office for National Statistics : ''Census 2001 : Parish Headcounts : Solihull''] Retrieved 2009-11-22</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n[[Gary Shaw (footballer, born 1961)|Gary Shaw]], the former [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] footballer, was born at a house on Meriden Drive in January 1961 and lived there until the 1980s, by which time he was established as a key player at Villa.\n\nRapper [[Lady Leshurr]] was born and raised in Kingshurst.\n\n[[Inspector Clouseau|Mike Kendall]] Famous [[clown|sleuth]] and [[gypsy|traveller]] attended Kingshurst Boys School in the [[old age|1970s]]. Reportedly his ideal travel destination is [[Vindication Island]], although he has not yet been.\n\n==Parish council==\nKingshurst has a [[Parish councils in England|parish council]], to which it elects 12 members every four years.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Kingshurst}}\n*[http://maps.google.co.uk/maps?oi=eu_map&q=Kingshurst&hl=en Map of Kingshurst]\n*[http://www.kingshurst.ac.uk City Technology College]\n*[http://www.northsolihull.co.uk/  North Solihull Regeneration website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in the West Midlands (county)]]\n[[Category:Solihull]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| official_name = Kingshurst\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.488|-1.7480|display=inline,title}}\n| country = England\n| region = West Midlands\n| population = 7,868\n| population_ref = ''(2011)''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11125226&c=Kingshurst&d=16&e=62&g=6367020&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1450277234812&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=16 December 2015}}</ref>\n| post_town = BIRMINGHAM\n| postcode_area = B\n| postcode_district = B37\n| dial_code = 0121\n| constituency_westminster = [[Meriden (UK Parliament constituency)|Meriden]]\n| civil_parish = Kingshurst\n| metropolitan_borough = [[Metropolitan Borough of Solihull|Solihull]]\n| metropolitan_county = [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]\n}}\n'''Kingshurst''' is a post-war housing estate and [[civil parish]] in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Solihull]], in the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]. It lies about {{convert|9|mi|km}} east of [[Birmingham]] city centre. The [[Smith's Wood]] area of [[Solihull]] borders it to the north and east, [[Fordbridge]] to the south and the [[Shard End]] area of Birmingham to the west.\n\n==History==\nThe name Kingshurst comes from having previously been a Royal Manor, and \"hurst\" meaning wood. The earliest record of Kingshurst is in documents from the late 13th and early 14th centuries, when it is referred to as part of the Manor of [[Coleshill, Warwickshire|Coleshill]]. Tenant farming was administered from here and [[Simon de Montford]] of Coleshill was an [[English people|English]] nobleman who built a moated manor house near Kingshurst. The Hall had its own park and farmlands.\n\n===The Mountfords 1332-1618===\nKingshurst took on an independent existence from Coleshill with the arrival of the Mountfords. It is unclear how Kingshurst came into their possession although it is probable that they bought the area around 1332 from the Clintons, who were then Lords of the Manor at Coleshill. What is certain is that they were in possession by about 1352.\n\n===The end of Kingshurst Hall===\nThe last proprietor of Kingshurst Hall, Walter Townsend, lacked the means to prevent the house from falling into a state of disrepair. All plans to salvage it came to nothing, due to a lack of funds. In 1960, Walter was moved to a house in [[Castle Bromwich]] and in 1962 the hall was demolished.\n\nThe remains of the [[moat]] of Kingshurst Hall are still visible today.\n\n===Yorkswood===\nDuring [[World War I]], much of the woodland in Kingshurst was cut down to help with the war effort. The Birmingham and District Association of [[The Scout Association|Boy Scouts]] were able to buy a patch of land at a bargain price and set up a permanent camp there. This land was halfway between Kingshurst and [[Shard End]]. It was called Yorkswood and opened in 1923. There were five camp fields, covering an area of {{convert|25|acre|m2}}. The total site was over {{convert|200|acre|km2}}. The site benefited from permanent washhouses and latrines, a swimming-pool, a training centre and headquarters, guesthouse, warden\u2019s hut and other huts. A small brook from a fresh water spring ran past the camp and Cock Sparrow Farm was about {{convert|100|yd}} away to provide fresh milk.\n\nThe entrance to the camp was flanked by a series of griffin statues. These had come from the roof of Lewis's Department Store on [[Corporation Street, Birmingham|Corporation Street]] in Birmingham when it was being renovated. After the camp closed in 1972, they were placed on the housing estate (Kendrick Avenue and nearby roads) built upon the site of the camp.\n\n==Kingshurst today==\nKingshurst is now a mainly residential area.  Built as an overspill housing estate built in the early 1950s for the City of Birmingham, it became part of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Solihull]] in 1974.\n\nThere are three [[primary schools]], Kingshurst, St. Anthonys and Yorkswood, a library and a small shopping area. The [[Anglican]] church is dedicated to St Barnabas and is situated off Church Close, the [[Catholic]] church is dedicated to St Anthony, the [[Methodist]] Church situated in Gilson Way and there is an evangelical church, [http://www.kecchurch.co.uk Kingshurst Evangelical Church (KEC Church)] situated on Cooks Lane corner with Forth Drive, which is much involved within Kingshurst Community. The nearest secondary schools are [[Smith's Wood Sports College]], across the Chester Road in Smith's Wood, the [[CTC Kingshurst Academy]], and [[John Henry Newman Catholic College]] which are off Cooks Lane. There is a small local park off Gilson Way/Marston Drive next to a main shopping area. The children's play area is the main facility with the freedom to play outdoor games and activities.\n\nAccording to the [[2001 UK Census|2001 census]], Kingshurst has a population of 8,126.<ref>[http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790266 Office for National Statistics : ''Census 2001 : Parish Headcounts : Solihull''] Retrieved 2009-11-22</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n[[Gary Shaw]], the former [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] footballer, was born at a house on Meriden Drive in January 1961 and lived there until the 1980s, by which time he was established as a key player at Villa.\n\nRapper [[Lady Leshurr]] was born and raised in Kingshurst.\n\n